<TITLE>The Verona Initiative</TITLE>

<BODY background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<P>
<IMG src="publhead.gif"> <BR>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../homeknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../prevknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<H3>Press Background 05 </H3>

<P>
20 November 1996<BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8, 2100 Copenhagen<BR>
Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and (45) 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80<BR>

<H2>The Verona Initiative to Provide New Arena for Health Debate
</H2>


The Fondazione Incontri Madruzzo (Italy), the City of Verona and
the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office for Europe
have announced plans jointly to launch a new European arena for
innovative debate on the measures that can produce health and
wellbeing. This so-called Verona initiative will provide mechanisms
for clarifying policy options aimed at creating and sustaining
health and recommend actions based on solid evidence of their
potential benefits.
<P>
&quot;Throughout Europe decision makers on all levels in both
public and private sectors are searching for ways to maximize
the social and economic impact of limited developmental resources,&quot;
noted Dr. Marc Danzon, Director of Health Promotion and Disease
Prevention for the WHO Regional Office for Europe, speaking to
decision-makers from government and industry gathered at the Fondazione
Incontri di Madruzzo project launch in Verona. &quot;While much
experience and knowledge exist, lessons learned are not effectively
being disseminated and integrated into practice.&quot;
<P>
The Verona initiative aims to address this challenge by:
<UL>
<LI>commissioning some of the world's best economic and social
thinkers to review key trends and actions affecting health and
to draw conclusions about what appears to be working and what
is not;
<LI>convening the experts to report and debate their findings
in a series of symposia over the next four years; and
<LI>utilizing print and telecommunications widely to publicize
and disseminate the outcomes and recommendations of these debates.

</UL>


&quot;Verona will be the stage, the whole of Europe will be the
audience.&quot; declared Erio Ziglio, WHO Regional Adviser for
Health Promotion and Investment. &quot;Good work alone is not
enough. The Verona initiative will provide both a scientific and
ethical platform for communicating information essential to public
health creation as we enter the new millennium.&quot;
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=2>For further information on this matter,
please contact: WHO <BR>
Regional Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8, DK-2100 <BR>
Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark. You may telephone directly to</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>Franklin Apfel and Annette Andkjaer in Communication
and Public Affairs</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44 or
fax on (45) 39 17 80 80 </FONT></CENTER>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD><B><IMG src="../whoblk.gif"></B></TD><TD>&copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/<BR>
<I>Updated 17 January 1997 - jfr@who.dk</I></FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>



