<HEAD>

<TITLE>Health as an Investment in Poland</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<P>
<IMG src="publhead.gif"> <BR>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../homeknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../prevknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<H3>Press Background 06 </H3>

<P>
12 December 1996<BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8, 2100 Copenhagen<BR>
Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80<BR>

<H2>Investment for Health in Poland <BR>
Overcoming the Obstacles to Collaborative Action </H2>

<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office for Europe
will convene top-level national and regional policy-makers from
Poland's key health-creating sectors: housing, education, health
and social services in Warsaw on 12-14 December. An action learning
workshop will be held that will focus on managing change and innovation
in health promotion. In collaboration with the Health Promotion
Department of Poland's National Institute of Cardiology and under
the auspices of the Ministry of Health and Social Welfare, this
gathering will for the first time bring together leaders from
different sectors to explore common strategies to invest scarce
resources to produce the most benefit to health.
<P>
&quot;This important workshop aims to catalyse a process to remove
obstacles to effective collaborative action,&quot; notes Erio
Ziglio WHO Regional Adviser Health Promotion and Investment. &quot;Many
of the determinants of health - such as environmental factors
or lifestyles - are themselves multicausal. This means that no
sector or agency can control all the factors that are involved
in promoting health. Innovative collaborative approaches are required.&quot;
<P>
The WHO Investment for Health team has assisted decision-makers
in municipalities and regions throughout Europe to draw upon their
and others' experience with identifying ways to overcome barriers
to effective collaborative action.
<P>
&quot;We have found that health can serve as a very useful common
ground for resolving priority conflicts between competing sectors,&quot;
notes Professor Alfred Rutten, Director of the Regional Centre
for Health Promotion, University of Chemnitz-Zwickau, Germany.
&quot;In our region of West Saxony a multisectoral investment
for health strategy is transforming severe economic, social and
ecological problems into sustainable strengths for future development.&quot;

<P>
&quot;By identifying practical organizational and managerial tools
and interventions to support change and innovation within the
Polish context,&quot; notes Professor Lowell Levin, a professor
at the School of Public Health, Yale University, USA and one of
the WHO experts coordinating the Warsaw workshop, &quot;we expect
the participants to overcome traditional obstacles to cooperation
and enhance their capacities to contribute not only to improved
health but also to their country's social and economic development.&quot;
<H3>Obstacles to collaborative action</H3>

<P>
Obstacles to collaborative action include:
<UL>
<LI>lack of understanding about the benefits that might be achieved;
<LI>territorialism - organizations and decision-makers guarding
their area of expertise and responsibility against perceived &quot;threats
of invasion&quot;, loss of prestige and power, etc.;
<LI>competition for limited financial resources;
<LI>inflexibility in the formal budget-setting process;
<LI>rules and regulations governing what can and can not be done
by an individual sector;
<LI>insecurity about the implications of change;
<LI>lack of trust between individuals and departments;
<LI>clashes in organizational culture and working practices;
<LI>organizational cultures that discourage creative thinking
and risk taking;
<LI>differences in power, status and influence;
<LI>hidden agendas - personal as well as departmental;
<LI>concern about blurring of responsibilities;
<LI>career structures that do not recognize or reward intersectoral
work;
<LI>rapid changes in organizations and politics and turnover of
people, which hinder continuity; 
<LI>data systems that focus on single sectors and communication
processes that inhibit cross-sectoral work.
</UL>

<P>
<CENTER>For further information on this matter, please contact:
<BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8, DK-2100<BR>
Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark. You may telephone directly to<BR>
Franklin Apfel and Annette Andkjaer in Communication and Public
Affairs<BR>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44 or fax on (45) 39 17 80
80</CENTER>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD><B><IMG src="../whoblk.gif"></B></TD><TD>&copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/<BR>
<I>Updated 12 December 1996 - jfr@who.dk</I></FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>

