<HTML>


<TITLE>Annual Report 1995</TITLE>

<BODY background="../../cbcbg01.gif">

<P>
<IMG src="../techhead.gif"> <BR>
<A href="../../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<A href="../tech.htm"><IMG src="../../sectknap.gif"></A> <A href="../tech.htm"><IMG src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<A href="../tech.htm"><IMG src="../../nextknap.gif"></A> <IMG src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<H1><CENTER>War and Health </CENTER></H1>

<H2><CENTER>Crossing the bridge to peace </CENTER></H2>

<H2><CENTER>Annual Report 1995 </CENTER></H2>

<H3><CENTER>WHO humanitarian assistance to Bosnia and Herzegovina,
Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)
</CENTER></H3>

<P>
<CENTER><BR clear=left>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Contents</H2>

<UL>
<LI><A href="ar01.htm">Introduction</A>
<LI><A href="ar02.htm">What does WHO do?</A>
<LI><A href="ar03.htm">Public health</A>
<LI><A href="ar04.htm">Into the fray with supplies</A>
<LI><A href="ar05.htm">Capacity building</A>
<LI><A href="ar06.htm">Crossing over</A>
<LI><A href="ar07.htm">After the crisis</A>
<LI><A href="ar08.htm">Finances</A>
<LI><A href="ar09.htm">Sharing the vision</A>
</UL>

<P>
Since September 1992, the World Health Organization (WHO) through
its Regional Office for Europe, has been providing humanitarian
assistance to Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro). After more than
three years of nonpartisan work on and behind the battle lines,
many lessons have been learned about preserving and promoting
public health in war conditions. WHO's 1995 report describes how
this coordinated public health response has saved lives, reduced
suffering, and supported and developed local capacities for action,
and how it now provides a platform for reconstruction and development.
<P>
<IMG src="ar02.gif" align=left border=5>
<H3>Crossing the bridge to peace</H3>

<HR>

<P>
Mostar Bridge, January 1996.<BR>
As all the people of Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, and the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) begin to
cross the bridge to peace, WHO will continue to work on all sides
for the improvement of the health situation, the re-establishment
of personal, professional, and political connections and networks,
reconciliation and the substantiation of the peace.<BR>
<BR clear=left>

<P>
This report is dedicated to the memory of all the health workers
in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) who lost their lives in this
terrible war and to the many doctors, nurses and other health
professionals with whom WHO has worked over the past four years
to preserve and promote health in the most difficult of conditions.
<BR>

<H3><A href="ar10.htm">Acknowledgement</A></H3>

<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD><B><IMG src="../../whoblk.gif"></B></TD><TD>&copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/<BR>
<I>Updated 4 September 1996 - jfr@who.dk</I></FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>


