<HTML>


<TITLE>ISMS</TITLE>

<BODY background ="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>

<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tpch.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tpch.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>



<IMG SRC="ismslog2.gif" align=left>

<CENTER>
<H2>WHO European Information Service <BR>on Medical Supplies
(ISMS)
</H2>
<HR>
</center>

The Information Service for Medical Supplies (ISMS) produces quarterly
updated reports on the current situation of medical needs and
supplies in the newly independent states (NIS). Information selected
from the latest reports on vaccines, life-saving drugs and basic
medical equipment in the NIS is presented:
<h4>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Background">Background</A>

<LI><A HREF="overview.htm">Vaccines</A>
<LI><A HREF="overview.htm">Life-saving drugs</A>
<LI><A HREF="overview.htm">Basic medical equipment </A>
<LI><A HREF="#further">Further information</A>
</UL>
</h4>


<HR>

<H2><A NAME="Background">Background</A> </H2>


The establishment of the WHO European Information Service on Medical
Supplies (ISMS) originates in the conclusions of the meeting of
the Medical Working Group of the Coordinating Conference on Assistance
to the Newly Independent States, in Washington, DC, on 22-23 January,1992.
Confronted with the enormous difficulties of assessing the health
needs of these countries, the group gave a mandate to WHO to create
a centre to provide up-to-date information on specific health
needs to potential donors. This mandate was confirmed at the Second
Coordinating Conference in Lisbon on 23-24 May 1992. <BR>
<BR>
Following this decision, WHO created a clearing-house whose task
was to collect, process and distribute a broad range of health-related
information and data in connection with the health status and
needs of the populations of NIS. Given the immediate priorities
that needed to be addressed first and foremost, as a result of
the breakdown of supplies of all kinds in these countries, the
format of the clearing-house was reviewed and its objectives were
adjusted. Subsequently, ISMS was incorporated into the EUROHEALTH
programme and put under the responsibility of the Country Health
Development Department in WHO/Europe. On this basis, top priority
has been given to identifying the short-term availability of essential
medical supplies in the form of vaccines, pharmaceutical products
and basic medical equipment in the NIS and the Baltic States.


<P>
The choice of vaccines is based on the WHO Expanded Programme
on Immunization (EPI) routine, which includes the following: OPV,
DPT, BCG and measles vaccine. As regards pharmaceutical products,
a list of life-saving drugs has been drawn up by WHO/Europe for
which each interested country is requested to indicate its level
of needs and supplies. ISMS issues the following hard-copy quarterly
reports on medical needs for vaccines and life-saving drugs in
the NIS:


<UL>
<LI>summary overview report on vaccine needs and supplies in the
NIS (updated quarterly).

<LI>summary overview report on life-saving drugs needs in the
NIS (updated quarterly).

<LI>country quarterly reports on the status of needs for and supplies
of vaccines and life-saving drugs. (These reports contain a wealth
of information on projections of needs, production where applicable,
purchases and donations delivered in the previous quarter. They
also contain information on planned imports and donations in the
next quarter).

<LI>annual summary report 1995 on needs for basic medical equipment
in the NIS.

</UL>

<HR>

<H2><A NAME="further">Further information</A>
</H2>


For further information, please
contact:
<P>
WHO Regional Office for Europe <BR>
8 Scherfigsvej <BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen <BR>
Denmark

<P>
 ISMS Information Service on Medical Supplies <BR>
Tel. (45) 3917 1717 <BR>
Fax(Direct) (45) 3917 1899 <BR>
Fax (45) 3917 1818 <BR>



<H3>Medical Officer:
</H3>
Dr J.N. Ormsby<BR>
Tel. (45) 3917 1394<BR>
<A href=mailto:jno@who.dk>E-mail: jno@who.dk</A>




<P>

