</h4>
<H1><a name="P01">Alarming upsurge of syphilis in the newly independent
states</A></H1>


Recent data on sexually transmitted diseases reported from the
countries of central and eastern Europe (CCEE) and the newly independent
states (NIS) indicate a dramatic upsurge of sexually transmitted
diseases (STDs), especially in some NIS. The data on syphilis
are particularly alarming (see Table 1) and they are strong indicators
of a general trend towards a rise in STDs. Available data also
demonstrate an increase in notified cases of gonorrhoea, though
less pronounced than that for syphilis. Most syphilis cases are
likely to be treated in the public sector and are therefore duly
notified. For gonorrhoea, underreporting may be greater, since
there appears to be a rapid rise in the proportion of individuals
seeking private care or treating themselves to avoid the rigid regime of the state services.

<P>
A WHO mission to Moscow in December 1995 assessed the current
situation with regard to the epidemiology, surveillance and control
of syphilis and gonorrhoea in the Russian Federation and recommended
priority action for control. The WHO team found evidence of the
occurrence of substantial epidemics of both gonorrhoea and syphilis.
Syphilis has increased forty-fold between 1988 and 1995, in particular
among younger people. The epidemic has not yet peaked, and substantial
efforts are required to reduce incidence.


<h3>Table 1. Notified cases of syphilis in selected countries, 1994</h3>

<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Country</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER><B>Incidence <BR>
per 100,000</B></CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283><CENTER><B>Increase over 1990-1994</B></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Russian Fed.</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>172<SUP>a</SUP></CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>35-fold</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Belarus</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>72</CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>25-fold</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Ukraine</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>69</CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>10-fold</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Rep. of Moldova</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>116</CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>7.5-fold</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Latvia</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>59</CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>10-fold</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=111><B>Estonia</B></TD><TD WIDTH=117><CENTER>57</CENTER>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=283>15-fold</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

a 1995 data<p>

The epidemics appear to have been triggered by factors related
to the process of rapid social change and economic transition,
in particular:
<UL>
<LI>changes in sexual behaviour (travel and migration, a growing
sex industry, and ideological changes in terms of more liberal
attitudes to sex);
<LI>reduced quality in some parts of the state health care services,
and the emergence of not yet fully developed private services;
and
<LI>the need to improve primary prevention and sexual health promotion.

</UL>




In addition to the significant morbidity and human suffering associated
with acute infection, and the sequelae of long-term infection,
the epidemics may pave the way for rapidly increasing rates of
HIV transmission, reaching levels far greater than those encountered
in western European countries. There are three reasons for this:
<UL>
<LI>the upsurge of STDs points to changes in sexual behaviour
that will facilitate HIV transmission;
<LI>the very high syphilis incidence must be associated with a
significant prevalence of genital ulcer disease (GUD), facilitating
transmission of HIV; and
<LI>contact is increasing between the Russian Federation and areas
with high HIV prevalence.
</UL>




The WHO team pointed out that the epidemics of syphilis and gonorrhoea
in the Russian Federation and parallel epidemics in other CCEE
and NIS have major implications for Europe as a whole. Western
European countries are already seeing increases in syphilis cases
related to the CCEE and NIS.

<P>
The WHO Regional Office for Europe and the United Nations Programme
on AIDS (UNAIDS) are jointly planning a series of actions to address
the problem. As a first step a meeting of experts from the most
seriously affected countries is planned. The aim of the meeting
is to develop national action plans.

<H1><a name="P02">Coming soon?</A> Polio-free Europe!</H1>

<H2>The situation </H2>


In 1995, 205 cases of poliomyelitis were reported to the WHO Regional
Office for Europe. Of the total, 146 cases occurred during the
outbreak of poliomyelitis in Chechnya, Russian Federation, from
June to November 1995. For the first time in the history of polio
in Europe, the number of countries reporting endemic cases of
polio has been reduced to only 9. Another very important development
is that the number of territories with endemic poliomyelitis was
reduced by 48% from 1994 to 1995. Consequently, only few &quot;hot
spots&quot; of polio remain in Europe.

<p>
<img src="cd1101.gif">




<H2>Operation MECACAR</H2>


In total, more than 60 million children have been immunized during
Operation MECACAR 1995 (mass vaccination with oral poliomyelitis
vaccine in the Mediterranean, Caucasian and central Asian republics).
The progress of polio eradication in Europe through Operation
MECACAR can be described as follows.
<UL>
<LI>In 1994, 201 (95%) of a total of 215 cases of poliomyelitis
reported in Europe were from countries involved in Operation MECACAR.
<LI>In 1995, only 49 (24%) of a total of 205 cases of poliomyelitis
reported in Europe were from MECACAR countries.
<LI>After the second round of MECACAR in June-August 1995, only
17 cases of poliomyelitis were reported from June to December
1995 from MECACAR countries in Europe, while 159 cases were reported
during the same period in 1994.
</UL>




The broader political and public health implications of the Operation
- in terms of alliance building at all levels, increased political
commitment and support for health, and capacity building at local
and national level - are equally significant.
<H2>Perspectives for 1996 </H2>

<P>
Strongly encouraged by the WHO Regional Office for Europe, the
health ministry of the Russian Federation has taken significant
steps to achieve the target of polio eradication. Two rounds of
national immunization days in 1996 are in preparation and the
activities will be coordinated with Operation MECACAR. Romania
is preparing local immunization days covering 22 districts, and
national Immunization Days will be organized in Albania in April
and May 1996. To achieve the target of making Europe free of polio
by the end of 1997, implementation of the mass vaccination strategy
in the Kosovo region of the territory of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) is urgently required in
1996. Activities to improve surveillance of acute flaccid paralysis
in many countries of Europe will have a high priority. This effort
will require a strengthening of the regional laboratory network
(LABNET) and its performance. Finally, the first meeting of the
European Regional Commission for the Certification of Poliomyelitis
Eradication took place in Paris, on 7-8 March 1996. The purpose
of the meeting was to define the terms of reference for the Commission,
to discuss and propose the process of certification for the Member
States of the European Region, and to formulate the main activities
to be included in the plan of action of the Commission.

<H1><a name="P03">Diphtheria in the NIS</A></H1>

<H2>The diphtheria situation</H2>


In 1995, a total of 50,464 cases of diphtheria were reported from
Member States to the WHO Regional Office for Europe, compared
to a total of 47,261 cases in 1994. It was originally estimated
that more than 100,000 cases of diphtheria would occur in 1995,
if drastic disease control measures were not applied.
<P>
The following updates from the Russian Federation
and the Republic of Moldova are given, with graphs illustrating
the monthly number of cases of diphtheria in 1994 and 1995.

<H3>Russian Federation</H3>


As a result of widespread immunization during the last year, the
incidence of diphtheria in the second half of 1995 appears to
be 100% lower than during the same period in 1994. The authorities
have made huge efforts, and over the course of the past few years,
nearly 70 million adults have been vaccinated against diphtheria
(65% of the entire adult population).
<p>
<img src="cd1102.gif">




<H3>Republic of Moldova</H3>


The national diphtheria control campaign, based on the WHO/United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) strategy, started in June 1995.
The diphtheria epidemic in the Republic of Moldova is showing
signs of retreat. Reported cases for the last three months show
a sharp reduction, despite the season of high transmission. The
highest coverage was achieved in the group aged 7 to 15 years,
corresponding closely to the age group with the highest incidence
and number of deaths due to diphtheria. The average coverage of
the population since 1 January 1994 has increased to 68.4%, even
if the campaigns only had an impact since 1 June 1995. 
<p>

<img src="cd1103.gif">

A nation-wide
campaign (versus
campaigns for geographical areas or high-risk occupational groups)
may be a factor explaining the difference in incidence between
Republic of Moldova and neighbouring Ukraine. Another factor may
be that antibiotics for the prophylactic treatment of primary
contacts were provided and used widely for the first time in November
1995. Antibiotic use is reported to have increased from 8.5% of
contacts in 1994 to 44.5% in 1995.

<p>
<h3>Belarus</h3>

<img src="cd1104.gif">

