<H2>Diphtheria control activities in the other NIS</H2>


Nine months after the launch of the Public Health Diphtheria Control
Emergency Appeal, the contributions of donors and particularly
the European Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO) and the U.S.
Agency for International Development (USAID), have enabled most
NIS to set up national diphtheria control programmes based on
the WHO/UNICEF strategy. Thanks to vaccines and other medical
supplies received, large-scale mass immunization campaigns have
been initiated. The needs of a first group of countries have almost
entirely been met: Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, the Republic
of Moldova, Ukraine and the Baltic states. A second group of countries,
including Belarus, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, have received contributions
to cover part of their needs. The last group of countries, including
Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan, have not yet received
contributions. Some countries allocated much of their own funds
for diphtheria control, particularly  Belarus, Kazakhstan and
Uzbekistan.

<P>
The first Workshop on Laboratory Diagnosis of Diphtheria was organized
jointly by WHO Regional Office for Europe and the Public Health
Laboratory Service/WHO Diphtheria Reference Centre (PHLS) in London,
on 14 to 16 November 1995. It was attended by key microbiologists
from 12 NIS. The main objectives were to introduce the diphtheria
laboratory kit, to identify key personnel, to identify problems
within laboratory diagnostics for diphtheria and to exchange experiences.
The participants are now able to hold similar workshops in their
own countries, using the components and materials of the diphtheria
laboratory kit. <BR>

<P>
The second Workshop took place in Vilnius, on 11 to 13 March 1996,
and brought together 14 participants from Belarus, Estonia, Latvia,
Lithuania and St Petersburg, with facilitators from PHLS and the
Public Health Institute in Helsinki.
<P>
The first consignment of diphtheria laboratory diagnostic kits
has now been received in Georgia, and consignments to Armenia
and Ukraine are being shipped from PHLS, in London. The dispatch
of kits to Azerbaijan and Tajikistan is next in line.

<H2>Country diphtheria activity update</H2>

<H3>Ukraine</H3>


Ukraine's mass immunization campaign was launched in April 1995
with a grant from ECHO through the Finnish Red Cross. A first
round of immunizations occurred in April; a second round in June/July;
and a third round in September/October. Regions will continue
mass campaigns or mop-up activities in 1996 with vaccines provided
by the Program for Appropriate Technology in Health (PATH)/USAID
and the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies (IFRC).

<H3>Belarus</H3>


The health ministry began more intensive immunization activities
with the arrival of additional vaccine supplies in 1995. The 1995
diphtheria control strategy focused on reaching the highest level
possible of persons under 16 years of age and target groups of
adults. It is believed that very high immunity levels now exist
in the population under 17 years of age and that high coverage
has been achieved in the 1995 target groups of adults.

<H3>Turkmenistan</H3>


A mass immunization campaign of the population 4 to 40 years of
age was conducted on 15 to 20 January 1996, made possible by a
government allocation of US$&nbsp;2 211 000.

<H3>Uzbekistan</H3>


Planning of logistics and supplies for a mass immunization campaign
is progressing. The government has allocated much of its own funds,
but has not received any external funds so far.



<H1><a name="P04">Bacterial meningitis in Europe</A></H1>

<P>
<I>The following information is an excerpt from the report</I>
Surveillance of Bacterial Meningitis in Europe 1994, <I>issued
in December 1995 by Marian Conolly and Professor Norman Noah from
the Department of Public Health and Epidemiology, King's College
School of Medicine and Dentistry in London, United Kingdom.
</I>
<P>
The incidence of meningococcal disease in Europe has remained
fairly stable over the past year although there was some variation
in trends within countries. There appears to be an increase in
incidence from south to north, although it is important to take
into consideration the completeness of case ascertainment in many
northern European countries. There is a seasonal distribution
of cases with peaks in the winter months.

<P>
Meningococcal disease mainly attacked the young. Nearly 80% of
cases were under 20 years of age, with the highest incidence in
those aged 4 years of age and under. There was a disproportionate
number of cases amongst males, with 51% overall for 1994 and 58%
under 20 years of age. Overall the case fatality rate was 7.6
with a higher rate for septicaemia (9.6). Adults were more likely
to die than children with the case fatality rate reaching over
25% in the elderly. As in 1993 an excess of cases of septicaemia
was detected in the 1 to 4 year old age group and also for over
65's in 1994.
<P>
Serogroup B predominated except in the Czech Republic where the
highest percentage of cases were group C:2a. A significant proportion
of cases in the Moscow area were group A. There appeared to be
some variation in age distribution for each serogroup. The serotype
and serosubtype information has proved to be particularly difficult
to analyse.





<h3>Reported incidence per 100,000 population of Meningococcal disease in Europe, 1994</h3>


