<P>
a Meningococcal meningitis<BR>
b Laboratory estimates; one third of cases is investigated, and the true incidence likely to be 1.92 per 100 000.
c Bacterial meningitis<br>



<P>
The genetic and evolutionary relationships between serotypes and
serosubtypes are not clear, and a coherent picture of spread within
and across Europe does not merge from the present data collected.


<P>
Nearly half of the strains tested were resistant to sulphonamides
and less than 10% were resistant to penicillin although there
was some variation between countries. The epidemic of group C:2a
disease continues in the Czech Republic. Otherwise fairly small
and minor outbreaks were reported.

<P>
The incidence of <I>Haemophilius influenzae</I> meningitis was
about a quarter of the incidence of meningococcal disease, mainly
affecting the 1 to 4 year old age group.

<P>
The incidence of pneumococcal meningitis is less than half of
<I>Neisseria meningitidis</I>. It affects mainly older adults
and the elderly and also pre-school children.

<P>
<I>In their concluding remarks, the editors stress that bacterial
meningitis continues to present a major health problem. The collection
and dissemination of information about the disease is a key element
in ensuring its early recognition and prompt treatment. This report
contributes greatly to the understanding of the disease and its
eventual control. For copies of the report, please contact the
editors at the following address:
</I>
<P>
<I>King's College School of Medicine and Dentistry</I>
<br>
<I>Department of Public Health and Epidemiology</I>
<br>
<I>Bessemer Road</I>
<br>
<I>London SE5 9PJ</I>
