<H1><a name="P05">Malaria in Europe</A></H1>

<H3>Azerbaijan</H3>


Social and economic hardship and the displacement of hundreds
of thousands of people after the hostilities between Azerbaijan
and Armenia contributed greatly to the worsening of the malaria
situation. Reported cases rose from 110 in 1991 to at least 2802
cases (<I>Plasmodiam vivax</I>) in 1995. The actual number is
considerably higher, since case detection activities have been
strongly reduced. Cases are found mainly in the southern regions
and in refugee camps around Baku. Although the political situation
has improved, the health ministry still has great problems in
mounting effective epidemic control operations. Experienced staff
are available, but there are neither drugs nor insecticides. About
4000 to 5000 cases are expected to occur in 1996.
<P>
<B>Action.</B>  A WHO assessment visit in March 1996, organized
by the WHO Regional Office for Europe, will develop an action
plan for malaria control.
<H3>Tajikistan</H3>


At least 10 000 cases occurred in 1995, mainly <I>P. vivax</I>;
11 cases of <I>P. falciparum </I>malaria were diagnosed in 1995<I>.</I>
No resistance was reported. Excessive migration, including refugees
from Afghanistan, was a contributing factor. Neither drugs nor
insecticides are available, and there is no trained staff. The
possibility of a serious malaria epidemic in the southern areas
cannot be ruled out, and it may occur in an explosive way since
a great majority of the population are non-immunes. Numerous malaria
foci may occur in other vulnerable areas, and <I>P. falciparum</I>
malaria may become endemic again.
<H3>Action. Based on new data received from the health
ministry in Tajikistan, an action plan has been elaborated.
</H3>

<H3>Turkey</H3>


An assessment mission was carried out in 1995. More than 100,000
cases (<I>P. vivax</I>) were reported, mainly in south-eastern
Anatolya,  with a lower increase in the Adana region and in the
whole country (importations). New large irrigation projects in
Anatolya will cause further increase of incidence.
<P>
<B>Action.</B> Training of entomologists, communicable disease/malaria
officers and primary health care officers will start in the Adana
Malaria Centre in 1996. A project for malaria control has been
elaborated.<BR>




