<H1><a name="P06">The sick child initiative:</A> Integrated case management</H1>


Worldwide, pneumonia, diarrhoea, malaria, measles and malnutrition
cause more than 70% of the deaths in children under 5 years of
age. There are feasible and effective ways that health workers
in clinics can care for children with these illnesses and prevent
most of the deaths. WHO and UNICEF used updated technical findings
to describe management of these illnesses in a set of combined
guidelines, instead of separate guidelines for each illness. Furthermore,
a training package has been developed to teach the integrated
case management process to health workers who treat sick children.


<P>
Health workers are experienced in treating common childhood diseases,
but are often trained only in the use of separate, disease-specific
guidelines, such as those for malaria or diarrhoea. Thus, they
may have difficulty combining different guidelines when caring
for a sick child with several problems. They may not know which
problems are most important to treat or, with limited time and
drugs, they may not be able to identify and treat all of the problems.
There are important relationships between the illnesses. Thus,
effective case management needs to consider all of a child's symptoms.


<P>
Following the integrated case management process, health workers
can quickly consider all of a child's symptoms and determine if
a child is severely ill and needs urgent referral. If not, the
health worker can follow the guidelines to treat the child's illnesses.
The guidelines also describe counselling for mothers and other
care givers.

<P>
The case management guidelines incorporate existing WHO guidelines
for diseases (such as diarrhoeal diseases, acute respiratory infections
and malaria) and for immunization, and address most but not all
of the major reasons a child is brought to a clinic for an illness.


<P>
For more information, please contact the WHO Regional Office for
Europe.

<H1><a name="P07">Rapid government response</A> stems Ebola outbreak in Gabon</H1>


As of 29 February, a total number of 27 cases with 18 deaths was
reported from Gabon. Cases ranged in age from 7 months to 65 years
(mean 24 years); 74 of 187 contacts remain under surveillance.
All of the cases were reported to have originated in the village
of Mayibout II, located in a remote area of northern Gabon. Control
measures instituted in Gabon by the Ministry of Health and an
international medical team appear to be containing the further
spread. Sporadic secondary cases, however, can still be expected.


<P>
WHO attributes the limited spread of the outbreak in Gabon to
several key factors: One was the rapid response of the Ministry
of Health in recognizing the threat at an early stage and reacting
appropriately. Control measures included the isolation of actual
and suspected cases, which reduced the odds of secondary infection.
Another important factor was a large-scale information campaign
conducted by the government to inform the public about haemorrhagic
fever, its mode of transmission and ways to avoid infection. Finally,
in contrast to last year's epidemic in Zaire, which struck in
an urban zone, the outbreak in Gabon occurred in a rural area
with low population density, a natural advantage in limiting the
further spread of infection.

<P>
Of particular concern to investigators was the possibility of
secondary infections among health workers in the provincial hospital
of Makokou, where the Ebola patients were admitted on 5 to 6 February.
The 21-day incubation period is still in effect, but no health
workers have manifested symptoms of the disease.
<H1><a name="P08">UNAIDS</A> and the WHO Regional Office for Europe</H1>


The WHO Global Programme on AIDS (GPA), including the GPA unit
at the Regional Office, closed at the end of 1995. It has been
replaced by the new joint United Nations Programme on AIDS (UNAIDS).
Currently UNAIDS operates in Europe from its headquarters in Geneva,
and two intercountry offices in Almaty, Kazakhstan and Kiev, Ukraine.
In accordance with the role of WHO as one of six cosponsoring
agencies of UNAIDS, the WHO Regional Office for Europe has established
the post of Regional Adviser, AIDS and Sexually Transmitted Diseases
programme (ASD). This programme is now part of the Communicable
Diseases unit.

<HR>


<I><B>CD News</B></I> is published four times a year by the Communicable
Diseases unit, WHO Regional Office for Europe.
<HR>






