<TITLE>Communicable diseases</TITLE>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">

<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>

<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>

<a href="cd01.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cd01.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>










<img src=hand02.gif align=left>
<center>
<H2> Communicable diseases<BR> won't stop<BR> at a border crossing</H2>
</center>
<HR>
<br clear=left>
<H2>Diphtheria, cholera, tuberculosis and other diseases threaten Europe</H2>

Borderlines may act as checkpoints for people and goods crossing from country to country.
<P>
But as new and re-emerging diseases threaten Europe, no country can seal off its borders from risks to public health.
<P>
The dangers? Diphtheria. Cholera and other diarrhoeal diseases. Tuberculosis. Acute respiratory infections. Viral hepatitis. Polio. AlDS and other sexually transmitted diseases. The solution? A comprehensive strategy to be implemented immediately across Europe, as urgently requested by the Member States of the World Health Organization (WHO) European Region. The Regional Office for Europe will lead the effort.
<center>
<img src="cd02.gif">
<P>
<img src="cd03.gif">

<P>

<table font size=-1 border=5>
<tr><td align=center>1990</td><td align=center>1991</td><td align=center>1993</td><td align=center>1994</td><td align=center>1995</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>	Romania 270	</td><td align=right>	Romania 226	</td><td align=right>	Tadjikistan 165	</td><td align=right>	Russia 1048	</td><td align=right>	Ukraine 568	</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>	USSR 49	</td><td align=right>	Ukraine 75	</td><td align=right>	Russia 23	</td><td align=right>	Ukraine 813	</td><td align=right>	Moldova 235	</td></tr>
<tr><td>		</td><td>		</td><td align=right>	Kazakhstan 74	</td><td align=right>	Albania 626	</td><td align=right>	Romania 104	</td></tr>
</table></center>
<font size=3>
<br clear=left>



<H3>The facts</H3>
<UL>
<LI>A huge diphtheria epidemic affects the newly independent states of the former USSR. An    estimated 55 000-60 000 new cases occurred in 1995. Europe now accounts for more than 80% of diphtheria cases reported worldwide.
<LI>The number of registered cholera cases in the WHO European Region increased nine times from 1993 to 1994. In 1995, 17 of the 50 Member States reported at least one imported cholera case.
<LI>In many of the countries in the eastern part of the Region, mortality due to tuberculosis is increasing. Tuberculosis strains resistant to drugs are spreading. The downward trend of tuberculosis incidence in western Europe has levelled off, owing to TB cases in immigrant populations.
<LI>In many eastern European countries, mortality due to acute respiratory infections of    children below 5 years of age is more than 100 times higher than in western Europe. Throughout the European Region, influenza epidemics cause millions of cases and thousands of deaths.
<LI>In Europe, malaria was a nearly forgotten disease in the 1980s. But the number of registered cases has exploded in recent years,    from 20 000 in 1992 to more than 100 000 in 1995. While most cases are found in Turkey, Tajikistan and Azerbaijan, there are 3000-4000 imported malaria cases in other countries of the European Region.

<LI>Hepatitis has a large health and economic impact on all European countries. Even in western European countries, such as Germany, an estimated 50 000 cases of hepatitis B occur annually, 10% of which result in chronic diseases. The annual economic loss caused by hepatitis B in Germany is an estimated DM 3 billion. The incidence of hepatitis B is up to 10 times higher in many southeastern and eastern European countries.
<LI>Worldwide, 7121 cases of polio were reported in 1994, down from 35 255 cases in 1988. Through Operation MECACAR (MEditerranean, CAucasian, and Central Asian Republic), WHO's campaign to eliminate polio in the European and the Eastern Mediterranean Regions, the elimination of this feared disease may be possible by 1997.
<LI>Worldwide, an estimated 17 million people are infected with HIV. Six million cases of AIDS    have occurred. In Europe, the number of reported AlDS cases is 150 000; the number of HIV infections is estimated to be 500 000.
<LI>Almost all countries of the former USSR have experienced a sharp increase in sexually    transmitted diseases - up to 10 times higher than 10-20 years ago. In 1994, 120 000 cases of syphilis were reported in the Russian Federation alone. As of October 1995, 200 000 cases
already had been reported.
</ul>

<H3>But isn't this a central and eastern European problem only?</H3>

When the subject is communicable diseases, there's no such thing as "somebody else's problem". In western Europe, communicable diseases are responsible for about 7% of total deaths and cause more than 60% of all acute illnesses. Elsewhere in Europe those percentages are much higher.
<P>
<img src="cdbroc01.gif" align=left>

<I>Goal 8: Improve public information and education strategies to increase the acceptance of communicable disease prevention programmes
</I>
<br clear=left>
<P>

Although major outbreaks to date have been confined mainly to central and eastern Europe and particularly the newly independent states of the former USSR, there is a significant danger of importation of communicable diseases to western Europe. In fact, imported cases of diphtheria already have been documented in Finland, Germany and Norway. And most western European adults have not kept up with diphtheria booster immunizations. This means that they are vulnerable.
<P>
Between 40% and 50% of new tuberculosis cases in many western European countries have occurred in migrant populations.
<P>
Today's mobile societies mean communicable diseases cannot be sealed off. lmports through business travellers, holiday makers, immigrants, refugees and asylum seekers have shown that communicable diseases are crossing national borders.

<H2>WHO's plan for success</H2>

The WHO Regional Office for Europe has developed a 10-point strategy to combat these public health threats. In addition to the cost of vaccines, an estimated $5 million-$6 million is needed for successful implementation of the strategy. With those funds, we will coordinate and lead efforts to:

<OL>
<LI>Control the epidemic of diphtheria in the newly independent states of the former USSR through mass immunization, appropriate case management and improved surveillance;

<LI>Interrupt transmission of wild polio viruses in Europe by the end of 1997 through     strengthened polio surveillance and coordinated mass immunization campaigns (carried out under Operation MECACAR and focusing on countries still having endemic polio);

<LI>Strengthen national immunization programmes in all European countries, including the implementation of new and improved vaccines and with special emphasis on programmes in the newly independent states;

<LI>Strengthen and support tuberculosis control in the whole European Region;

<LI>Help the countries of central and eastern Europe and the newly independent states     implement WHO-recommended strategies for the control of diarrhoeal and acute respiratory diseases;

<LI>Improve surveillance for early detection of emerging and re-emerging diseases (including resistance to antibiotics) by establishing a network of national collaborating laboratories;

<LI>Prevent the HIV/AIDS epidemic from rising above the current level, and reduce the personal and social implications of HIV infection/AIDS through the development of comprehensive care and support; stop the alarming upsurge in sexually transmitted diseases by strengthening prevention of AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases;

<LI>Improve public information and education strategies to increase the acceptance of     communicable disease prevention programmes;

<LI>Protect and restore the health service infrastructure related to the control of     communicable diseases through initiatives likely to produce immediate results; and


<li>Assist countries to improve basic hygiene and water quality in high-risk areas in order to lower the danger of outbreaks of food- and water-borne diseases.
</ol>

<H2>The cost of neglect</H2>


The high cost of neglecting this public health emergency is immeasurable, both in lives and in financial resources. Consider, however, two examples of imported polio outbreaks. In 1992/1993, the Netherlands spent US $10 million fighting 72 cases of polio. When an imported polio outbreak struck Finland a decade ago, nine people contracted the disease, but the entire population had to be immunized.


<H3>Immunization: the most cost-effective weapon</H3>

The social and economic changes sweeping central and eastern Europe have influenced the infrastructure of the programmes for disease prevention and control in these countries. As a result, many communicable diseases, once controlled by immunization, have re-emerged. Only sustained national immunization efforts can slow and finally control the epidemics that can spread from country to country.
<P>
Remember smallpox? Until recently, this often fatal disease claimed tens of thousands of lives every year. WHO launched a campaign in 1967 to eradicate smallpox, and the last case occurred in 1977 - marking the first disease ever eliminated in the history of humankind. The eradication of polio could be the next success story.
<P>
Quite simply, immunization is the single most powerful weapon to reduce disease incidence, to eliminate distinct diseases, and to prevent the re-emergence of diseases in countries having achieved reduction through immunization long ago. It is also one of the most cost-effective strategies for public health.

<P>
<img src="cdbroc02.gif" align=left>

<I>Goal 3: Strengthening national immunization programmes - Delivering polio vaccine
</I>
<br clear=left>
<H2>WHO is uniquely positioned
to combat communicable diseases
</h2>

WHO holds a unique place in the public health sector. With nearly 50 years of experience in helping Member States to implement standard programmes, we are motivated by only one force: our commitment to protecting public health.
<P>
WHO's comprehensive health networks and local staff infrastructures worldwide, combined with decades of technical expertise, allow the Organization to address public health concerns immediately. For example, when the recent Ebola fever crisis struck in Zaire, WHO rapidly headed for the scene - with the medical experts and equipment kits needed.
<P>
WHO takes a global view of public health issues. The Regional Office for Europe receives data on communicable diseases from all European countries, and analyzes and evaluates those data to help Member States plan and carry out appropriate public health strategies.

<P>
<img src="cdbroc04.gif" align=left>

<I>Goal 2: lnterrupt transmission of wild polio viruses in Europe by the end of 1997</I>
<P>
<br clear=left>
<P>
<img src="cdbroc03.gif" align=left>

<I>Goal 6: lmprove surveillance for early detection of emerging and re-emerging diseases - Training of microbiologists in diphtheria diagnosis </I>

<br clear=left>

<P>

WHO:

<UL>
<LI>Has the methodology for control.
<LI>Makes the technical recommendations.
<LI>Develops the requirements for production and control of vaccines.
<LI>Has the methodology for monitoring and surveillance.
<LI>Provides training in all these fields to assist countries in implementing national policies.
</UL>

WHO does not operate alone; on the contrary, we give great importance to coordinating activities and working in partnership with other organizations.
<P>
In 1994 an Interagency Immunization Coordinating Committee was created to support primary immunization and disease control in the newly independent states. The governments of many countries are generously supporting public health efforts in the newly independent states of the former USSR.
<P>
WHO's track record speaks for itself - from the eradication of smallpox, declared in 1980, to the impending eradication of polio and dracunculiasis (Guinea-worm infection) by the turn of the century.

<H3>How will we measure success?</H3>


Success is not some vague concept we declare after a few immunization programmes or educational campaigns. Concrete results require the measurement of concrete goals. These are just some of the ways in which we will gauge our success:

<UL>
<LI>Interruption of the transmission of wild polio viruses in the European Region by the end of 1997; worldwide eradication declared by the year 2000.
<LI>Reduction of diphtheria incidence in the newly independent states to pre-epidemic levels by the end of 1997.
<LI>Coverage of at least 90% of Europe's children with diphtheria, measles, pertussis, polio and    tetanus vaccines; the same level of coverage in countries where mumps, rubella, and hepatitis B vaccines are available by the end of 1997.
<LI>For all countries in the European Region, self-sufficiency in the provision of vaccines within approximately 10 years.
<LI>Implementation of WHO strategies on epidemic preparedness and outbreak control, aimed at emerging and re-emerging diseases.
<LI>Reduction of sexually transmitted diseases and new HIV infections through the establishment and consolidation of comprehensive programmes throughout Europe by the <LI>end of 1997.
<LI>Ensuring that WHO recommendations on tuberculosis control become operational in the
majority of countries of the European Region.
</ul>
<H2>We must act now</H2>

Financial support is urgently needed to address these specific, targeted, time-limited interventions. We must act now to protect the health of all of Europe's people. Delays can spell disaster, requiring actions that are far more costly than prevention.
<P>
In the interest of a healthy Europe, please support this initiative to combat communicable diseases.

<P>
For information regarding contributions contact
<P>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Attention: Coordination and Resource Mobilization<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8<BR>
2100 Copenhagen <BR>
Denmark
<P>
Tel. (45) 39 17 17 17<BR>

Fax. (45) 39 17 18 18
<P>
The Regional Committee of the World Health Organization's Regional Office for Europe strongly urges Member States and other donors to support this initiative to control the spread of communicable diseases in Europe.


The World Health Organization gratefully acknowledges the support of the following in the production of this brochure: Cross-Border Communications, Janet Sturis, John Bendtsen (cover photo),  European Network of Health Promoting Schools (first photo), and Public Health Laboratory Services, London (next two photos).
