<CENTER><IMG src="region.gif" align=left border=5></CENTER>
<H1><CENTER>Regions for Health </CENTER></H1>

<P>
<CENTER><BR clear=left>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A href="#P1">Regions for Health Network</A>
<LI><A href="#P2">Constitution</A>
<LI><A href="#P3">Contacts</A> 
<LI><U>&quot;Leading Edge&quot; documents</U> (LINK)
</UL>

<H1><A NAME="P1">Regions for Health Network</A> </H1>

<P>
The WHO Regions for Health Network in Europe was founded in November
1992. Already over 20 European regions have agreed to work with
each other to achieve better health for their local people, using
the <U>health for all</U> approach(LINK to HFA).
<P>
Through pooling ideas, experience and resources, the Network members
aim to sharpen the focus on health at local level.
<P>
This text aims to give you a concise view of why the Network was
set up, its structure and some of its current activities. For
those interested in knowing more, it lists the addresses of the
Network Secretariat and the focal points<B> </B>in each participating
region. If you want to join the Network or help it or a member
region with money, ideas or know-how, please approach one of the
people on the list.
<H2>Statement of intent </H2>

<P>
Following discussions in Lugano and Cardiff, representatives of
regions across Europe agreed on 17 November 1992 in Dusseldorf
to establish a Regions for Health Network. Recognizing that health
for all transcends boundaries, political, geographical and professional,
and to share knowledge, they agreed to adopt the following strategic
intent:
<P>
Through joint work the Regions for Health Network aims to strengthen
the focus at regional level on achieving health for all.
<P>
In moving forward, the founding members affirmed that progress
will be achieved through following a strategic direction emphasizing:
<UL>
<LI>dynamic alliances - working together to bring about health
gain at the regional and local level across Europe;
<LI>knowledge transfer - promoting excellence and effectiveness,
and eliminating waste and unnecessary duplication;
<LI>intersectoral action - making health for all<B> </B>the business
of everyone. 
</UL>

<P>
Those who join declare their willingness to promote the Network's
intent to the best of their capacity. They agree to exchange ideas
and experiences and, where appropriate, to work together on policy
development and projects to effect change at the regional and
local levels. The members will foster the widest collaboration,
bringing together from every sector all who can contribute to
improving health. In pursuit of the intent, the Network will encourage
links to other European groups.
<P>
Starting from this core of founding members, the Network will
in principle welcome all those who are interested in realizing
its strategic intent and who believe it matches their own approach.
In practice, the growth and development of the Network will depend
on the organizational and financial resources available and will
be guided by the results of continuous monitoring and evaluation
of its impact.
<P>
In keeping with the principles of health for all, the Network
members accept that solidarity and equity require that the burden
of running the Network may be shared unequally, but the benefits
will accrue to all.
<H2>Organization </H2>

<P>
Each member region appoints someone locally as a focal point to
act as its main link with the Network. The <U>focal points</U>
(LINK to Contacts) and other representatives of the regions attend
the Annual General Meeting of the Network, which is where progress
is evaluated and major decisions are taken on future action.
<P>
Guided by the decisions of the Annual General Meeting, a Steering
Committee composed of representatives from 6 of the regions and
the Secretariat plan and monitor joint projects and the general
running of the Network.
<P>
The members are called upon to harness their local resources (people,
know-how and expertise) and contribute support in cash and in
kind towards achieving the goals of the Network, drawing in partners
as appropriate.
<P>
To help coordinate the work of the Network, the WHO Regional Office
for Europe has established a Secretariat. It works closely with
the Steering Committee and acts as the main contact between the
WHO and the members, encouraging and supporting the Network and
strengthening links between it and other WHO programmes and activities.
The Secretariat is also responsible for the transfer of information
to member regions, other regions, WHO Member States, other parts
of WHO and other international bodies.
<H2>The Network in action </H2>

<P>
Regions joining the Regions for Health Network (RHN) accept responsibility
for working towards the strategic intent, through
<UL>
<LI>their own local initiatives
<LI>involvement in joint projects
<LI>securing financial and other support from their own region
and from sponsors
<LI>developing ways of promoting the work of the Network to others:
politicians, planners, health care providers, partners in other
sectors and the general public. 
</UL>

<P>
The purpose of RHN is to achieve tangible, serious improvements
in the protection, maintenance and promotion of health at regional
level. Besides the objectives set out in the statement of intent,
it aims at increasing equity in health, wide participation in
decision-making and promoting a balance between issues of lifestyle,
environment and health care. It encourages new approaches to policy
analysis and sharing models of good practice. Joint action involving
several countries is already in hand, especially emphasizing the
involvement of countries from central and eastern Europe.
<P>
The activities of RHN are generated by the members, each of which,
on joining, identifies its own strengths and areas where it would
appreciate help from other members.
<P>
There are a number of activities currently under way, including:
<UL>
<LI>a major exercise in developing health policy linking three
regions in western Europe with three counties in Hungary;
<LI>a number of projects looking at how information can be used
to derive improvements in health at regional level;
<LI>training seminars combining resources from a number of regions

</UL>

<P>
A major conference is organized each year in association with
the Annual General Meeting, offering the opportunity to all members
to meet and discuss a theme of significance to them all.
<P>
A newsletter published twice a year keeps members and others in
touch with the activities and future plans of RHN.
<H2>Programme design </H2>

<P>
RHN was always intended to be an open network, not a select club.
Because the vision has to be tempered with realism, the pace of
expansion must not exceed the resources available and the need
to evaluate progress.
<P>
While in principle membership should be open to all, criteria
have been established to ensure that new members have an appropriate
level of commitment.
<H3>Formal essential criteria </H3>

<UL>
<LI>The region must be identifiable as an administrative unit,
an existing group of subunits, or a region clearly recognized
for its similar socioeconomic, cultural characteristics.
<LI>The region must have a degree of autonomy to make decisions.

</UL>

<H3>Political essential criterion </H3>

<UL>
<LI>There must be a clearly stated interest in developing a policy
based on health for all, and acceptance of the strategic intent
of RHN. 
</UL>

<H3>Other criteria for full membership </H3>

<UL>
<LI>The region must have a potential and willingness to mobilize
resources for HFA (economic, intellectual, etc.).
<LI>The region must have a capacity for building up new partnership
for health (i.e. the potential for intersectoral action).
<LI>The region should have structures for monitoring and evaluating
progress. 
</UL>

<H3>Financial or in-kind contribution for membership </H3>

<P>
All members are expected to contribute to the running of RHN,
through an annual subscription and other financial or in-kind
support as set out in the fund-raising strategy. Special provisions
are made for regions that have a problem with foreign currency.
<P>
Regions unable to meet all these criteria may enter into associate
membership prior to joining as full members.
<H1><A NAME="P2">Constitution</A> </H1>

<H2>Article 1 - Composition </H2>

<P>
The Regions for Health Network of the World Health Organization
Regional Office for Europe shall consist of Members who have committed
themselves to aligning their policies for health according to
the principles of the policy of the World Health Organization
entitled &quot;Health For All&quot;.
<H2>Article 2 - Objectives </H2>

<P>
The objectives of the Regions for Health Network (hereinafter
called &quot;the Network&quot;) shall be:<BR>
(a) to create dynamic alliances with the aim of improving health
policy at regional levels within Europe in line with the policy
of the World Health Organization entitled &quot;Health For All&quot;;
<BR>
(b) to promote the transfer of knowledge and experience of health
policy development at regional and local levels within Europe,
thereby promoting equity, excellence, effectiveness and efficiency;
<BR>
(c) to encourage intersectoral action for health so that all sectors
put health objectives high on their agenda, making the policy
of the World Health Organization entitled &quot;Health For All&quot;
the business of everyone;<BR>
(d) to explore alternative approaches to developing health policy
at a regional and local level within Europe;<BR>
(e) in the framework of health policy at a regional and local
level within Europe, to examine the balance of resources that
is desirable at the regional level, giving due emphasis to health
promotion and disease prevention;<BR>
(f) to make regular assessments of progress of the implementation
of the objectives;<BR>
(g) generally to take all necessary action to attain the objectives
of the Network.
<H2>Article 3 - Membership </H2>

<P>
3.1 Membership of the Network shall be open to any region within
Europe, and shall be granted by the Steering Committee in accordance
with the criteria which shall from time to time be formulated
by it.
<P>
3.2 Applications for membership of the Network shall be made in
writing to the Secretariat which shall advise upon the same and
shall forward the same to the Steering Committee for consideration
and decision.3.3.1 Each Member shall nominate a person to:<BR>
(a) provide continuity and visibility for the Network; <BR>
(b) build support for the Network in the Member's region;<BR>
(c) act as a focal point for contact to and from the Network;
<BR>
(d) to act as a representative for the Member at meetings of the
Network and its organs.
<P>
3.3.2 The person so nominated may from time to time be replaced
by the Member. The details of the person so nominated and of any
replacements made shall be communicated in writing to the Secretariat.
<P>
3.3.3 For the purposes of this Constitution &quot;region&quot;
means a political or administrative unit of a country which possesses
its own decision-making powers; resources with which to invest
in health, create and develop partnerships for intersectoral action
to achieve health gain and a means to monitor the progress made
by it in the investment in health and the achievement of health
gain and such expression shall include a group of such units which
exists within one or more countries.
<P>
3.4 Members shall pay an annual subscription as a contribution
to the funding of the Network.
<P>
3.5.1 If any Member shall wish to withdraw its membership, it
shall be entitled to do so by giving at least 3 months' notice
in writing to the Secretariat. The Member shall then withdraw
its membership upon the expiry of that notice.
<P>
3.5.2 Any Member which, in the opinion of the Steering Committee,
fails to meet the aims, objectives and agreements of the Network,
shall be given notice to that effect by the Steering Committee.
If, after service of such a notice, the Member, in the opinion
of the Steering Committee, continues to fail to meet those aims,
objectives and agreements, it shall be requested to withdraw from
the Network. This will be subject to the approval of the Annual
General Meeting.
<P>
3.5.3 If any Member withdraws from the Network any membership
subscription paid by it shall not be refunded.
<H2>Article 4 - Organs </H2>

<P>
The organs of the Network shall be: <BR>
(a) the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(b) the Steering Committee;<BR>
(c) the Secretariat.
<H2>Article 5 - Meetings </H2>

<P>
5.1 The Secretariat shall convene the Annual General Meeting.
The Annual General Meeting shall be held at yearly intervals at
such time and place as shall be decided by the Steering Committee.

<P>
5.2 The Secretariat shall convene an Extraordinary General Meeting
within ninety days of the receipt of any request therefore made
by a majority of the Members or by the Steering Committee, at
such time and place as the Steering Committee shall determine.
<P>
5.3 Notices convening a meeting shall be made in writing. Notices
convening an Annual General Meeting shall be sent to Members not
less that thirty days, and notices convening an Extraordinary
General Meeting shall be sent to Members not less than fifteen
days before the date fixed for the opening of the meeting. The
Secretariat may invite representatives of regions which have applied
for membership of the Network to send observers to an Annual General
Meeting.
<P>
5.4.1 The Secretariat, in consultation with the Steering Committee,
shall prepare the agenda of each meeting.
<P>
5.4.2 The agenda of the Annual General Meeting shall be prepared
taking into account proposals submitted by the Steering Committee.
The Steering Committee shall include in the provisional agenda
of each Annual General Meeting <I>inter alia</I>:<BR>
(a) Approval of the budget of the Network including the amount
and terms of the annual subscription fee;<BR>
(b) Selection of members of the Steering Committee;<BR>
(c) Report on the work of the Steering Committee and joint activities;
<BR>
(d) Proposals for adoption by the Members;<BR>
(e) Other items requested by Member regions.
<P>
5.4.3 The agenda of an Extraordinary General Meeting shall reflect
the reason for the calling of the meeting.
<P>
5.4.4 The agenda or, in the case of the Annual General Meeting,
the provisional agenda shall be despatched together with the notice
of convocation referred to in paragraph 5.3 above.
<P>
5.5 Each Member shall have one vote in a meeting. For the purposes
of this Constitution the phrase &quot;Members present and voting&quot;
means Members casting a valid affirmative or negative vote. Members
abstaining from voting are considered as not voting.
<P>
5.6.1 This article is subject to the provisions of articles 11
and 12.
<P>
5.6.2 Decisions in an Annual General Meeting shall be made by
a majority of the Members present and voting.
<P>
5.6.3 Decisions in an Extraordinary General Meeting shall be made
by three quarters of the members present and voting.
<P>
5.6.4 Decisions shall normally be taken by a process of consensus.
If a formal vote is considered necessary by a majority of members
present, this vote shall normally be by a show of hands. Voting
may be taken by secret ballot if it has previously been so decided
by a majority of the Members present and voting. If the votes
cast are equally divided on a matter other than an election, the
proposal shall be regarded as not adopted.
<P>
5.7 One third of the Members shall constitute a quorum.
<P>
5.8 If a representative of a Member is unable to attend a meeting
an alternate from the same Member region may replace that representative.
The alternate shall have full rights to speak, vote and otherwise
participate in the meeting.
<P>
5.9 The working language of the Network and its organs shall be
English.
<H2>Article 6 - Steering Committee </H2>

<P>
6.1 The Steering Committee shall consist of seven members comprising
the representatives of six member regions (one of which shall
be a WHO Collaborating Centre for Regional Level Policy Development)
and the Regional Adviser of the Country Health Policy Unit of
the World Health Organization Regional Office for Europe. One
of the representatives shall be the editor-in-chief of the newsletter,
if any, produced by or on behalf of the Network. The six member
region representatives, subject to article 6.3, shall serve for
three years each.
<P>
6.2 The six member region representatives of the Steering Committee
shall be selected at the Annual General Meeting. Each year one
third of the members of the Steering Committee shall retire in
rotation. Such retiring members of the Steering Committee may
offer themselves for re-election.
<P>
6.3 The members of the transitional steering committee shall be
the first members of the Steering Committee. Of their number,
one third shall retire after one year, one third shall retire
after two years and the remainder shall retire after three years.
Before the end of the first year, the members of the Steering
Committee shall decide amongst themselves which of their number
shall retire at the end of each period. If no agreement can be
reached then the matter shall be decided by the drawing of lots.
<P>
6.4 Meetings shall be held at least twice a year at such time
and in such place as the members of the Steering Committee shall
decide. At each meeting the Steering Committee shall decide upon
the place of the next meeting and shall elect a Chairperson for
that meeting.
<P>
6.5 Each member of the Steering Committee shall have one vote.
For the purposes of this Constitution the phrase &quot;members
of the Steering Committee present and voting&quot; means members
casting an affirmative or negative vote. Members of the Steering
Committee abstaining from voting are considered as not voting.
Decisions shall be unanimous.
<P>
6.6 Four of the members of the Steering Committee shall constitute
a quorum.
<P>
6.7 If a member of the Steering Committee is unable to attend
a meeting, an alternate from the same region may replace that
member. The alternate shall have full rights to speak, vote and
otherwise participate in the meeting.
<P>
6.8 If a member of the Steering Committee does not attend two
consecutive meetings without showing good cause to the Chairperson
of the Steering Committee, the Chairperson, with the approval
of the Steering Committee, shall declare the seat vacant.
<P>
6.9 The Steering Committee shall request the Country Health Policies
Unit of the World Health Organization Regional Office for Europe
to act as general Technical Adviser to the Steering Committee,
and may call upon any units within the World Health Organization
Regional Office for Europe for such additional technical advice
as it may from time to time consider to be appropriate.
<H2>Article 7 - Responsibilities of the Steering Committee </H2>

<P>
7.1 The Steering Committee shall: <BR>
(a) be the organ responsible for developing the general policy
of the Network in accordance with the objectives of the Network;
it shall take into account the opinions expressed by the Members
in the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(b) encourage cooperation between the Members and, in particular,
exchanges of experiences of pilot activities in the fields of
public health and health care, in the promotion of equity in health,
and wide participation in decision-making;<BR>
(c) define the overall orientation of the Network's action;<BR>
(d) put forward proposals for the future general direction of
development of the Network and proposals for specific projects
and activities for the Network;<BR>
(e) outline broad guidelines for the funding and use of the Network's
budget and make proposals including the amount and terms of the
annual subscription to the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(f) where it considers it necessary so to do and in order to take
advantage of the intellectual and other resources available through
the Members, request Members to prepare such proposals and technical
documents as it thinks fit for consideration by the Members at
the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(g) jointly with the Members' representatives, encourage the establishment
of cooperative links with any governmental or non-governmental
organization which has an interest in health at a national or
regional level in its country;<BR>
(h) consider and decide upon all applications for membership of
the Network and to obtain and consider technical advice from the
Secretariat on such applications prior to deciding upon the same;
<P>
(i) monitor progress of all activities carried out by the Network
and to ensure the establishment of mechanisms and procedures for
evaluation of those activities; <BR>
(j) undertake responsibility for seeking financial support for
the Network and its activities;<BR>
(k) act as the editorial organ of such newsletter, if any, produced
by or on behalf of the Network;<BR>
(l) generally on behalf of the Members take all necessary action
to obtain the objectives of the Network;<BR>
(m) provide a Chairperson for the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(n) develop procedural notes to amplify on matters covered by
the Constitution.
<P>
7.2 The Steering Committee shall carry out its responsibilities
in close cooperation with the World Health Organization Regional
Office for Europe through the Secretariat.
<H2>Article 8 - The Secretariat </H2>

<P>
8.1 The Secretariat of the Network shall be located within the
Country Health Policies Unit at the World Health Organization
Regional Office for Europe and shall be headed by the officer
responsible for that Unit.
<P>
8.2 The Secretariat shall:<BR>
(a) be responsible for the administrative and financial management
of the Network;<BR>
(b) coordinate and monitor programmes of work;<BR>
(c) provide links between the Network and units within the World
Health Organization Regional Office for Europe;<BR>
(d) organize and take minutes at the Annual General Meeting and
the meetings of the Steering Committee;<BR>
(e) communicate to the Members all information which the Steering
Committee requires to be communicated to the Members, including
the proposals and decisions of the Steering Committee and the
decisions of the Members at the Annual General Meeting;<BR>
(f) provide a link for communication between Members;<BR>
(g) when required to do so, request support from or propose collaboration
with a Unit or Department within, and any programme or project
being carried out by, the World Health Organization Regional Office
for Europe;<BR>
(h) ensure that all relevant information on the work of the Network
is communicated to the Members, to the various committees within
and the Member States of the World Health Organization, to other
international organizations and to institutions and bodies which
provide the Network with financial support.
<H2>Article 9 - Role of the World Health Organization Regional
Office for Europe </H2>

<P>
The World Health Organization Regional Office for Europe through
its Country Health Policies Unit shall: <BR>
(a) provide the Secretariat for the Network;<BR>
(b) provide a technical adviser to the Network to advise regarding
the implementation of the policy of the World Health Organization
entitled &quot;Health For All&quot;;<BR>
(c) advise the Steering Committee regarding applications for Membership
of the Network;<BR>
(d) propose to and receive from the Steering Committee details
of potential activities to be undertaken by the Network;<BR>
(e) encourage the establishment of cooperative links with any
governmental or non-governmental organizations at an international
level.
<H2>Article 10 - Finance </H2>

<P>
The financial rules and regulations of the World Health Organization
shall apply to the administration, accounting and auditing of
the funds of the Network. Any voluntary donations made to the
Network shall be held in a fund at the World Health Organization
Regional Office for Europe and shall be specifically designated
for the use of the Network.
<H2>Article 11 - Amendment of the Constitution </H2>

<P>
Texts of proposed amendments to this Constitution shall be communicated
by the Secretariat to the Members at least six months in advance
of their consideration by the Members at the Annual General Meeting.
Amendments shall come into force for all Members when adopted
by a two-thirds vote at the Annual General Meeting.
<H2>Article 12 - Dissolution </H2>

<P>
12.1 The Network may be dissolved by a decision taken by the Members
in an Extraordinary General Meeting called for that purpose or
by a decision adopted by a two-thirds vote at the Annual General
Meeting.
<P>
12.2 Upon dissolution of the Network all funds held by the Network
shall become and form part of the funds of the Country Health
Policies Unit of the World Health Organization Regional Office
for Europe.
<H2>Article 13 - Date of Constitution </H2>

<P>
The Constitution shall take effect from 20 October 1994.
<H1><A NAME="P3">Contacts</A> </H1>

<P>
The focal points represent the key link in each region. They are
responsible for information transfer and are in touch with most
regional project collaborators. They are the first point of contact
if you want to be informed about a region's activities.
