<center>

<h1>Health for all</H1>


<HR>
</center>

The work of WHO/Europe is based on the regional policy for health for all, which includes 38 targets. They fall into five groups: targets for better health, lifestyles conducive to health, healthy environments, appropriate health care services and the support needed to attain them.<p>
The regional health for all (HFA) policy, strategy and targets were
approved by the thirty-fifth session of the Regional Committee in 1984. The policy and targets were updated in 1989-1991 and the updated version was approved by
the forty-first session of the Regional Committee in 1991. Progress towards achieving the targets has been evaluated regularly. (See the results of the most recent monitoring in <a href="../country/euro/part0h.htm"> <b><i>Health in Europe</i></b> </A>and check progress on health for all indicators on the <a href="ftp://ftp.who.dk/in"><b>HFA database.</b></A>) The regional policy and targets will be further updated in 1998, following a review of the progress towards health for all in 1997.<P>

<H2>The broad perspective</H2>
The health policy for Europe consists of 38 targets. They can be divided into <a href="hfagroup.htm">groups,</A> addressing:


<UL>
<LI>the improvements in health status expected by the year 2000;
<LI>the developments in prevention, treatment, care and rehabilitation, changes in lifestyles and
improvements in environment that will make it possible to attain the targets;
<LI>policy formulation and sustained implementation on the basis of political, managerial and institutional
support and coordination.
</UL>
The health outcomes that the HFA movement in the European Region is striving to achieve have four
dimensions:<P>
<UL>
<B><LI>ensuring equity in health</B> by reducing disparities in health status between countries and
between groups within countries;
<B><LI>adding life to years</B> by helping people achieve and use their full physical, mental and social
potential;
<B><LI>adding health to life</B> by reducing disease and disability;
<B><LI>adding years to life</B> by increasing life expectancy.
</UL>
Six major themes run through the health for all targets.<P>
<UL>
<LI>Equity is the essence of health for all. All people should have a fair opportunity to realize their full
health potential.
<LI>The prevention of disease and promotion of health are important strategic issues to give people a
positive sense of health so that they can make full use of their physical, mental and social capacities.
<LI>Well informed and motivated people and communities will participate actively in setting their
priorities, and in making and carrying out decisions.
<LI>Many sectors of society must collaborate in order to achieve health for all. Intersectoral participation is
needed to ensure health and protection from risks in the physical, economic and social environment.
<LI>A harmonious health service system meets the basic needs of each community by focusing on primary
health care with adequate referral services and provides affordable, quality care.
<LI>An increasing number of health problems transcend national frontiers.
</UL>


<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 9 August 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>


