<center>

<H1>Health for all</H1>

<H2>Statistical Database (Windows version)</H2>

<H3>Updated February 1997</H3>
<hr>
</center>

This software contains data on selected health statistics for
European countries, called Health for All Indicators.  It includes
user-friendly software to display these data as tabular and graphical
output, which  helps users to interpret the statistical data.
 The World Health Organization, Regional Office for Euorpe, collects
data from various sources, primarily from national counterparts
on health statistics.
<P>
The main sources of information are listed in the file SOURCES.HFA.

<P>
The database is periodically updated, as more recent data become
available. This package is for the WINDOW's environment.  It is
also available for the MS DOS environment.

<P>
This README.1ST file contains important information and should
be read first.
<P>
The topics are as follows:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Installation
<LI>Disclaimer / &quot;about&quot; menu item
<LI>Useful files
<LI>Definitions
<LI>Hints and other useful information
<LI>Who to contact
</UL>




The HFA/PC can be downloaded from Internet by:<BR>

<H3>1)  Using FTP:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Connect to gopher.who.dk
<LI>Use ANONYMOUS as userid and your own Internet ID as password
<LI>Choose files from the library /IN or /HFA
<LI>The files SETHFAD.EXE and README.DOS contain the DOS version
<LI>The files SETHFAW.EXE and README.WIN contain the Windows'
version
<LI>Switch to binary mode before receiving the .EXE files.
</UL>

<H3>2)  Via WWW</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Connect to home page of WHO's World-Wide Web Server (http://www.who.dk)
<LI>Select &quot;Country Information&quot;
<LI>Download appropriate &quot;README and SETHFA &quot; files.
</UL>




Requests for copies of the HFA/PC diskette (both DOS and WINDOWS
versions) can also be forwarded to:

<P>
ADR/DIS unit<BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen<BR>
Telefax:   (45) 39 17 18 18<BR>

<P>
Copies can also be obtained from the WHO documentation centres
that have been established in a number of countries.  Please note
that the Regional office may charge a certain amount to
<P>
cover the cost of the diskette and handling expenses.

<P>
The HFA/PC package may be copied for use by other individual users
or organizations, under the condition that it is not used for
commercial purposes and that this README.1st file is
also copied without change.

<P>
Your comments on the usefulness of this HFA/PC program and suggestions
for improvement would be very appreciated.


<H3>Installation<BR>
</H3>


To run the HFA/PC, your PC will require about 4 Mbyte RAM and
3 Mbyte of harddisk space to work with the HFA/PC program, depending
on what other programs you are running.  The PC should be at least
386SX.software.

<P>
1)  Create a directory on your hard disk and copy all files from
the distribution diskette (or ones downloaded from Internet) into
the new directory. You can do this with the following MS DOS-commands:


<P>
C:&gt;MD HFAWIN97
<P>
C:&gt;CD HFAWIN97
<P>
C:\HFAWIN97&gt;COPY A:\*.*

<P>
OR    COPY B:\*.*
<P>
2)  Then run the SETHFAW.EXE file to decompress data files:
<P>
C:\HFAWIN97\&gt;SETHFAW
<P>
3)  After the installation, your directory now contains approximately
220 files.
<P>
4)  You can then delete the SETHFAW.EXE in order to save space.
<P>
5)  Log on to Windows (3.0 or 3.1) and use the normal Windows
procedure to define the HFA.EXE from the newly created directory
as an icon in one of your windows.
<P>
6)  When you first run this program you must establish the Data
Path.  Do this by starting the program, click on the File menu,
then click on Data Path, select Primary, then click OK to confirm
that the data files will be kept in the same directory as the
software.
<H3>Disclaimer / &quot;about&quot; menu item</H3>


When you first access this program, you will be presented with
a disclaimer screen which contains very important information
and which should be read carefully.  After you have entered the
Country Selection List, selected and STORED some country names,
a WHO.INI file is created which inhibits the program from showing
the disclaimer text each time you start the HFA/PC program.  This
text will however still be accessible by entering the ABOUT menu
item, or by reading the DISCLAIM.ER file.  The DISCLAIM.BAT file
will print the DISCLAIM.ER file on your screen or you may use
your usual full-screen editor to print or browse this file.
<H3>Useful files</H3>


1)  The SOURCES.HFA file is a listing of all indicators with their
source(s) and definition.  Users should note that the data for
some indicators have been obtained from various sources, and that
the intercountry comparability for these indicators is limited
due to varying definitions and measurement practices used in different
countries and/or time periods.  The SOURCES.BAT file will print
the SOURCES.HFA file on your screen or you may use your usual
full-screen editor to print or browse this file.
<P>
2)  The COUNTRY.HFA contains all the country names with abbreviations
which this software uses.  These country abbreviations and names
are for computer processing of data and are not necessarily the
ones recognised officially, nor do they express any opinion whatsoever
on the part of the Secretariat of the World Health Organization
concerning the legal status of any country or territory.  The
COUNTRY.BAT file will print the COUNTRY.HFA file on your screen
or you may use your usual full-screen editor to print or browse
this file.
<H3>Definitions</H3>


1)  The EUROPEAN AVERAGE (EUR) and the other regional averages
(CEE, EU, NIS, NRD) are population-weighted averages.  They are
normally calculated when a minimum of 50% of the countries (except
for the CEE average) have data for a given indicator for a selected
time period.  The number of countries included in the average
calculations for different indicators will therefore vary.  Also,
as new data is received, more countries will meet the criteria
for inclusion in the appropriate average calculations, with the
result that averages for the same indicator and year may vary
between versions of the HFA/PC.  To ensure that a time series
includes the same countries throughout, data are checked by country
and year and missing values are calculated.  The program uses
linear interpolation for the calculation of the missing values.
 The same calculations are made for the EU AVERAGE (15 European
Union countries), the CENTRAL AND EASTERN EUROPEAN AVERAGE (12
countries not including the ex-USSR), the NEWLY INDEPENDENT STATES
AVERAGE (15 countries of the former USSR) and the NORDIC AVERAGE
(5 countries).

<P>
It should be noted that the averages for NIS and CEE can show
inconsistent trends.  This is due to the combination of data from
ex-countries and from the present countries, e.g., ex-Czechoslovakia
is now 2 countries, ex-USSR is now 15 countries, ex-Yugoslavia
is now 5 countries.  Data definitions or completeness can differ
and in a few cases give unstable trends in the NIS or CEE averages.

<P>
2)  The STANDARDIZED DEATH RATE (SDR) is the age-standardized
death rate calculated using the direct method, i.e., the age specific
rates are averaged, using as weights the distribution of the European
standard population as defined in the World Health Statistics
Annual.  This standardized rate represents what the crude rate
would have been in the population if that population had the same
age distribution as the standard population.

<P>
3)  Each INDICATOR has a 6 character numerical code.  The first
two numbers indicate to which HFA target the indicator belongs.
 Codes starting with 99 are used for supplementary indicators
and are not the indicators approved by the WHO European Regional
Committee.  Also, some indicators have not been included in this
package as the data is considered of insufficient availability
and/or quality.

<P>
4)  Full-time equivalent (FTE) is calculated by adding full- and
the appropriate proportion of part-time occupied posts.

<H3>Hints and other useful information
</H3>


1) A DATA AVAILABILITY chart can be accessed by entering the Indicators
Selection Menu, selecting an indicator and then clicking twice
on the circle indicating the relevant population group, i.e. Total,
Male or Female.  In addition, the Tables A or B can be consulted.
 When in the Map display or one of the Bar Charts, one can point
and click to learn data details of that country.
<P>
2) The PROJECTIONS to the year 2000 shown in this software are
simple linear approximations of curves and, therefore, only a
rough estimate of a trend.  You should treat the projections with
caution.  To display a projection, enter one of the line graphs
and point the cursor to the year from which the projection should
be calculated and press the left mouse button.

<P>
3) The option to select the FIRST AVAILABLE YEAR or the LAST AVAILABLE
YEAR must be used with caution.  Comparison of countries may be
misleading because the years for which data are available can
vary significantly between countries. Check the Data Availability
facility or Table B for details on data years.

<P>
4) The TWO INDICATOR COMPARISON CHART facilitates comparison between
indicators and/or between sexes. As on the other presentation
graphs you decide on indicators and sex by pulling down the INDICATOR
and SEX menus. You will be asked to indicate whether you are changing
the left/right indicator/sex. Note that two different indicators
might provoke different scaling on the two Y-axis. For comparing
MALE and FEMALE for the same indicator, choose the same indicator
for left/right.

<P>
5) The BOXPLOT shows where a given country (indicated by an asterisk)
is placed as compared to other countries.  The brackets indicate
the middle part of the distribution, by default containing 80%
of all countries (to change, pull down the RANGE menu bar).  The
BOXPLOT allows one to observe the position of a country for several
indicators simultaneously.  By comparing boxplots for different
years, one can quickly assess whether the country is relatively
progressing or regressing as compared to other countries.  The
minimum and maximum values of the indicator for the countries,
appear on the sides of each box and the value of the selected
country (which corresponds to the asterisk) is shown below the
boxes.

<P>
6) If you encounter an APPLICATION OR SYSTEM ERROR, it can relate
to the actual installation of Windows and not to this program.


<P>
7) If the PRINTOUTS look strange (if the text is to small or overlaps),
it is most likely a problem in the printer driver.  If possible,
try to print via another printer driver or try another PC with
a different printer attached.
<H3>Who to contact</H3>

<P>
Please report any problems or noticed inaccuracies in data to:
<P>
Epidemiology, Statistics and Health Information unit<BR>
Attn. Dr R. Prokhorskas<BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen
<P>
TEL: (45) 39 17 14 82 or (45) 39 17 14 39<BR>
FAX   (45) 39 17 18 95<BR>
E-mail(Internet): <a href=mailto:RPR@WHO.DK>RPR@WHO.DK</A>

<P>
Any comments and suggestions for improvements of this package
would also be very much appreciated.<BR>

