<TITLE>BBC World Service
</TITLE>

<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>
<P>
Press release EURO/01/97<BR>
Copenhagen, January 1997<BR>
<BR>

<H2>BBC World Service and the World Health Organization promote
healthy living in Romania and Uzbekistan
</H2>


BBC World Service and the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional
Office for Europe have jointly been awarded a grant from the British
Government Know How Fund to pioneer a mass media health education
initiative in Romania and Uzbekistan. Radio broadcasts and educational
booklets in Uzbek and Romanian will be used to inform people about
the health risks associated with smoking, lack of exercise, poor
diet and alcohol abuse, and health care professionals will receive
special training in their localities.

<P>
Dr Franklin Apfel, WHO Regional Adviser for Communication and
Public Affairs, said: &quot;There has been a sharp increase in
rates of premature death among adults in eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union over the past few years. Much of this increase
is the result of a fall in living standards and lifestyle-related
factors such as smoking, poor diet and high alcohol consumption.&quot;


<P>
Jenny Stevens, coordinator of the BBC World Service part of the
project, said: &quot;This project aims to increase public awareness
of the risks and develop the professional competence of local
health education agencies in Romania and Uzbekistan.&quot;

<P>
The WHO Regional Office for Europe aims to improve the level of
health in <B>all</B> European countries and to reduce the
disparity between levels of health in eastern and western Europe.
Figures for life expectancy in eastern European countries and
the former Soviet Union are several years lower than the WHO target
of 75 years; most European Union countries have already achieved
this target. In the former Soviet Union, life expectancy for men
dropped to 59 years in the early 1990s; this level is below the
official retirement age and as low as levels in the 1950s.


<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>For further information on this matter, please
contact:
<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs, WHO Regional
Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,
<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.
<BR>
You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer
<BR>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44 or
fax on (45) 39 17 18 80.
<BR>
All WHO Europe press releases can be found
on the WHO Internet home page http://www.who.dk


</FONT></CENTER>
<center>
