<TITLE>Pharmacists help smokers to quit</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>


<P>
Press release EURO/02/97<BR>
Copenhagen, January 1997<P>

<H2>Pharmacists help smokers to quit</H2>


Pharmacists in Europe have joined forces to help smokers quit.
The EuroPharm Forum, which includes 31 national European pharmaceutical
associations and the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional
Office for Europe, has adopted a new Pharmacists' Charter on Action
against Smoking (see box) which aims at involving pharmacists
in smoking cessation programmes in the communities they serve.


<P>
Tobacco is the number one killer in Europe. Last year tobacco
killed 1.2 million people in the WHO European Region alone. This
amounted to 14% of all deaths. Just under one half of all adult
men and one quarter of women in the WHO European Region are daily
smokers. The number of young people who are starting to smoke
is rising throughout the Region. Because nicotine is so addictive,
once these young people start to smoke, they will continue for
an average of 20 years.

<P>
&quot;In the face of this enormous health risk and alarming trend,&quot;
states Dr Peter Anderson, WHO Regional Adviser for the Tobacco
or Health programme, &quot;much firmer action needs to be taken
to prevent young people from starting to smoke and to ensure that
professionals are knowledgeable and available to assist all people
to break their nicotine addiction.&quot;

<P>
By displaying posters and providing literature and advice to smokers
who request prescription and non-prescription medicines for smoking-related
problems, pharmacists throughout Europe have been very successful
in raising awareness of the health risks of smoking and helping
smokers to quit. The EuroPharm Forum is building on these successes
by incorporating relevant learning into practical training materials.
The Forum's new manual, <I>The role of the pharmacist in smoking
cessation</I>, will be issued as a booklet in the WHO Smoke-free
Europe Series.

<P>
&quot;Every smoker should have an opportunity to take in the message
that he or she can stop smoking and that support is available,&quot;
states Dr Jo Asvall, WHO Regional Director for Europe. &quot;Pharmacists,
as highly trained and easily accessible members of the primary
health care team, are ideally positioned to convey this message
and to provide support.&quot;

<HR>

<P>
The Pharmacists' Charter on Action against
Smoking
<P>
Calls for pharmacists to contribute to a smoke-free Europe by:

<UL>
<LI>providing a role model;
<LI>forbidding all smoking in the pharmacy to guard against the
risks of passive smoking, particularly to those who are most vulnerable,
including young children and asthmatics;
<LI>highlighting the health risks of smoking;
<LI>encouraging smokers to quit;
<LI>providing advice, help and support to smokers who want to
quit; and
<LI>urging governments to ban the advertising of tobacco products.
</UL>

<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>For further information on this matter, please
contact:<BR>Communication and Public Affairs, WHO Regional
Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,<BR> DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.<BR> You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer <BR>on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44
or fax on (45) 39 17 18 80.<BR> All WHO Europe press releases can be found
on the WHO Internet home page http://www.who.dk
</FONT></CENTER>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 31 January 1997 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>

