<TITLE>Mostar</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>
<P>


Press release EURO/03/97<BR>
January 1997
<P>
<I>Simultaneously issued from Copenhagen and Sarajevo
</I>
<H2> Expired drugs in Mostar to be recovered and made safe
</H2>


Hazardous waste and pharmaceutical experts, coordinated by the
World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office for Europe, have
begun sorting through 200 tonnes of out-dated and unusable drugs
stockpiled in Mostar. Over the next two months, teams of local
and international specialists will segregate, re-package, label
and safely store potentially harmful items while acceptable disposal
routes are identified.

<P>
&quot;During the war, large quantities of drugs and medical supplies
were donated by companies, [nongovernmental organizations] and
individuals from many well meaning groups to the people of Bosnia
and Herzegovina,&quot; explains Tim Grayling, Public Health Engineer,
WHO Office for Humanitarian Assistance - Bosnia and Herzegovina.
&quot;Unfortunately, some of these donations arrived unannounced,
unlabeled, with different types of medicines in the same boxes,
some out-of-date, some half used, and often without any supporting
documentation. Overworked national pharmacists in Mostar simply
could not process the huge volume of donations. Some of the drugs
destined for elsewhere in central Bosnia and Herzegovina were
held up in Mostar by the regular interruption of humanitarian
convoys. As a result, large volumes of pharmaceutical materials
accumulated in warehouses in and around East and West Mostar.&quot;


<P>
In early 1996, Pharmaciens sans fronti&egrave;res (PSF) and WHO
initiated a drugs management programme in Mostar, which resulted
in all new donations being strictly processed and correctly utilized.
WHO international guidelines for drug donations were adopted by
major donors and aid organizations in May 1996. The ever-increasing
growth of stockpiles has since been stopped.

<P>
&quot;Indiscriminate disposal of current stockpiles could pose
a very real risk to local public health and to the environment,&quot;
states Ren&eacute; Kersauze, Director, Nancy Project Office (France),
WHO European Centre for Environment and health. &quot;If not properly
disposed of, hazardous materials could contaminate water resources
and soil.&quot;

<P>
The Mostar programme, funded by the European Community Humanitarian
Office (ECHO) and the Overseas Development Administration of the
United Kingdom, will make safe, prior to disposal, any hazardous
waste that is found.

<P>
In addition, WHO has prepared guidelines for the disposal of pharmaceuticals
in Bosnia and Herzegovina. Adoption of these guidelines is currently
being considered by the health ministries in both the Federation
and Republika Srpska.

<P>
At present, no specialized facilities for chemical waste treatment
or incineration exist in Bosnia and Herzegovina. The guidelines
provide advice on potentially feasible methods of sorting and
disposing of the estimated total of 800 tonnes of expired drugs,
using resources that could be made available in the country. This
quantity represents primarily the remainder of the many thousands
of tonnes of drugs that were donated and used to save many lives
during the war.
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>For further information on this matter, please
contact:<BR>Communication and Public Affairs, WHO Regional
Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,<BR>DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.<BR> You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer <BR>on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44 or
fax on (45) 39 17 18 80.

<P>
For technical information contact <BR>Mr Ren&eacute; Kersauze, Director, or Dr
Philip Rushbrook, WHO, Nancy, France<BR> Tel: +33 3 83158770 Fax: +33 3 83158773
email: ecn@who.dk; <BR>or Tim Grayling, WHO Office for Humanitarian
Assistance - Bosnia and Herzegovina, Tel 38771 670838 Fax 387
71 444439<BR>All WHO/Europe press releases can be found
on the Internet WHO home page http://www.who.dk/Communication
and Public Affairs</FONT>
