<HTML>


<TITLE>Press release 01/1996</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<img src="techhead.gif">

<br><a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="tech.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="tobac.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="tech.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<br clear=left>

Press release EURO/01/96<BR>
Copenhagen, May 1996

<H1>Tobacco confirmed as the number one killer in Europe
</H1>


New data from the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office
for Europe confirm that tobacco is the number one killer in Europe.
Last year, tobacco killed 1.2 million people in the WHO European
Region (population: 850 million) alone. This is 14% or 1 in 7
of all deaths.  But the figures mask a huge difference between
the western and eastern halves of the Region.  In eastern Europe,
tobacco will kill 1 in 5 men aged 35 before they reach the age
of 69 - this figure is twice as high as that for western Europe.
But tobacco is not just a problem for eastern Europe. Tobacco
kills the highest number of women in the western part of the Region.
For example, of all the Danish women who currently die between
35 and 69 years of age, it is estimated that one third of the
deaths are attributable to smoking.

<P>
In the WHO European Region, just under one half of all adult men
and one quarter of women are daily smokers. These figures are
higher in the eastern half of the Region, where rates of smoking
are increasing for both men and women. Although the number of
adult smokers is falling in the western countries, the number
of young people who are starting to smoke is rising throughout
the Region. One in five 15-year-old boys and girls are cigarette
smokers. Because nicotine is so addictive, once these young people
start to smoke, they will continue for an average of 20 years
before they quit.

<P>
In the face of this enormous health crisis, much firmer action
needs to be taken to prevent young people from starting to smoke
and to ensure that public opinion demands stronger measures against
tobacco.

<P>
It is no longer acceptable to allow the marketing of tobacco products
through any form of advertising or sponsorship.  Other ways of
controlling the epidemic are to ensure that cigarettes are expensive
and to make as many public places as possible smoke free.


<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><H3>World No-Tobacco Day</H3></CENTER>

Every year the World Health Organization invites people all over the world to focus on issues related to tobacco or health on 31 May, which has been designated by the World Health Assembly as World No-Tobacco Day. The celebration of World No-Tobacco Day aims at encouraging governments, communities, groups and individuals to become aware of the problems caused by the use of tobacco, especially among young people, and to take appropriate action to combat this harmful behaviour.  This year, the theme "Sport and the arts without tobacco" offers an opportunity to mobilize athletes, artists and the media in support of WHOs objective of promoting a society and a way of life where tobacco use is no longer an accepted norm.
<P>

For further information on this matter, please contact:<P>

WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen <BR>
Denmark.
<P>You may telephone directly to
Franklin Apfel and Annette Andkjaer in Communication and Public Affairs
on
<BR>(45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44
<P>or fax on (45) 39 17 18  80

