<TITLE>Euro press release 02/1996</TITLE>

<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>



<H4>Press release EURO/02/96
<BR>
Copenhagen, June 1996
</H4>
<H2>First and foremost, health care reform must lead to better
health for people

</H2>


Cost containment alone provides an inadequate basis for sustainable
health care reform, advises the World Health Organization (WHO)
Regional Office for Europe. An expert report to be released at
the<B> WHO Conference on European Health Care Reforms </B> in
Ljubljana, Slovenia, on 17 June emphasizes the  importance of
 measuring the success of reform against long-term gains in health
status.

<P>
The WHO study found little evidence of positive economic effects
from encouraging citizens to choose among insurers or to make
co-payments. On the contrary, unless these demand-reducing approaches
are accompanied by &quot;protective&quot; regulation, they may
substantially reduce access  to necessary health services and
thus threaten the overall health of the population. <BR>

<P>
The WHO report concludes that the health care reforms most likely
to achieve social and economic success are those that focus on
changing behaviour on the <I>supply side: </I>that is, the behaviour
of hospitals and physicians. Health reforms that use strategies
such as global hospital budgeting and performance-based payments
for providers appear to be more successful in achieving economic
and social goals.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
One demand-side reform that the WHO study saw as positive was
efforts to enhance the role of citizens and patients. These measures
include legislation to protect the rights of patients, to enable
citizens' voices to be heard in the policy process, and to ensure
that patients have reliable information to use in making informed
choices of their  health care providers.

<P>
&quot;Reform measures will be judged not only by short-term savings
to public budgets, but also by their ability to promote health
and to generate health gain for the entire population,&quot; states
Jo E. Asvall, WHO Regional Director for Europe.
<P>
&quot;First and foremost health care must lead to better health
for people. This is  equally important in all countries of the
Region.&quot;

<P>
The study sets the stage for an intensified initiative by WHO
to assist policy-makers in surmounting the challenges facing European
health care systems.

<P>
The issues in the expert report will be taken up when ministerial-level
delegations from the 50 Member States of the WHO European Region
meet in Ljubljana, Slovenia, from 17 to 20 June 1996 at the <B>WHO
Conference on</B> <B>European Health Care Reforms</B>.   Ministers
will exchange experience, analyse actions to date and adopt a
charter that articulates a common set of principles and strategies.
<BR>

<P>
&quot;Health care systems throughout Europe are bustling with
change,&quot; notes Dr Bozidar Voljc, Minister of Health of the
Republic of Slovenia. &quot; It is important to communicate and
exchange experiences so that common problems can be tackled uniformly,
since no country has yet found an ideal solution.&quot;<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>For further information on this matter,
please contact:</b>
<P>WHO

<BR>Regional Office for Europe<BR>Scherfigsvej
8<BR>DK-2100
>Copenhagen &Oslash;<BR>Denmark. <P>You may
telephone directly to:
<P>
Franklin Apfel and Annette Andkjaer in
Communication and Public Affairs
<P>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44<BR>
 or fax on (45) 39 17 80 80

