<H3>Press release EURO/04/96</H3>

Copenhagen, 18 September 1996
<P>
Released simultaneously in Geneva and Copenhagen
<center>
<H1>Wild poliomyelitis outbreak in Albania</H1>
<hr>
</center>

 A mysterious outbreak of paralytic disease which started in Albania
in April is poliomyelitis, according to the World Health Organization.
Wild poliovirus was identified by WHO reference laboratories in
Rome, Italy and Bilthoven, Holland.
<P>
 The outbreak started in the countryside in the northwestern part
of Albania, later spreading to Tirana and the rest of the country.
As of today, there are 66 cases and 7 deaths. Initial press reports
linked the outbreak to a recent mass immunization campaign carried
out in Albania in April and May 1996 when 350,000 children under
five years were immunized. &quot;With these new laboratory results,
we can now firmly say that there is no link between the campaign
and the outbreak&quot;, comments Dr Harry Hull of the WHO Expanded
Programme on Immunization. &quot;In fact, the spring campaign
clearly protected children. Only five of the 66 cases were in
children less than five years of age. The vast majority of cases
occurred in teenagers and adults&quot;. There are seven cases
in the 0 to 9 years category and the remaining 59 cases range
from 10 to 47 years of age.
<P>
 The assessment is echoed by Dr Bruno Martin, UNICEF's Regional
Adviser on Health: &quot;The spring campaign has protected children
under five. The outbreak which claimed an unusually high number
of adults shows that mass vaccination is effective and necessary
in order to protect children from a life-threatening or disabling
disease&quot;.
<P>
 WHO and UNICEF, partners in the global polio eradication initiative,
are seeking international support for another mass immunization
campaign in Albania. &quot;We have to move fast&quot;, says Dr
George Oblapenko of the WHO Regional Office for Europe. &quot;The
immunization campaign will have to cover mostly the adult population,
simply because that's where the majority of cases are. Provisionally,
this effort will require 3,2 million doses of polio vaccine which
will cost about US$300,000 for one round. Currently, we have only
a donation of 300,000 doses of vaccine from the Red Cross of Monaco.
In the meantime, visitors to Albania should ensure that they are
adequately immunized against polio before they depart.&quot;.
<P>
 The WHO Regional Office for Europe is holding a one-day consultation
in Copenhagen on the outbreak of paralytic disease in Albania
on 20 September 1996 with representatives of all major partners
and donor community in the global polio eradication campaign.
It is expected that representatives of the Albanian Health Ministry
will also attend the consultation. The main purpose is not only
to sum up available epidemiological information gathered by WHO
experts working with Albania authorities but also to work out
details of the immunization campaign and to prepare a social mobilization
plan.
<P>
 WHO, UNICEF and Rotary International are helping to organize
mass polio immunization campaigns in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,
Moldova, Romania and the Ukraine in the next month. The organizations
believe that it is crucial for the success of polio eradication
to conduct such large scale operations in neighbouring countries
at the same time, thus denying the virus an opportunity to circulate
freely in the environment.
<P>
 Prior to this outbreak, there had been 11 confirmed cases of
polio reported in the European Region of WHO in 1996, with 10
cases in Turkey and one in Ukraine. For comparison, there were
206 registered cases of confirmed polio in the European Region
in 1995.  WHO, UNICEF, Rotary International, Centers for Disease
Control (USA) and other international partners, remain firmly
committed to polio eradication by the year 2000. It will be the
second virus, after smallpox, to disappear completely from the
face of the Earth.
<HR>




For further information, please contact Valery Abramov, Health
Communications and Public Relations, WHO, Geneva. Tel. No. (+41
22) 791 2543, Fax No. (+41 22) 791 4858; Mrs Margherita Amodeo,
Information Officer, UNICEF, Geneva. Tel. No. (+41 22) 909 5511.
Fax No. (+41 22) 909 5907; Dr Franklin Apfel, WHO Regional Office
for Europe, Copenhagen. Tel. (+45) 39 17 1336  or  1344, Fax No.
(+45) 39 17 1880
<HR>




