<TITLE>Press release EURO/05/96
</TITLE>

<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>



<H3>Press release EURO/05/96</H3>
Copenhagen, 22 October 1996
<H2>Mysterious illness reported in school children<BR>
in the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia</H2>


A WHO expert team is investigating an outbreak of a mysterious
illness which has affected 1000 school children and resulted in
over 600 hospitalizations in the Tetovo municipality in the Former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM).
<P>
Since 26 September 1996, hundreds of primary and secondary school
students aged 11 to 17, all of Albanian descent, have been admitted
to the Tetovo Medical Centre with an unknown cause syndrome as
it was characterized by headache, abdominal pains, breathlessness,
dizziness, weakness, muscle pains and other less frequent symptoms.
All the patients received symptomatic treatment and improved rapidly.
After one to three days they were discharged from the hospital
and returned home. No deaths have been reported.
<P>
The syndrome which is affecting only Albanian children, has raised
serious concerns amongst both the local population and government
authorities.
<P>
On 14 October, Dr I. Filipce, Minister of Health, requested the
WHO Regional Office for Europe to provide an expert team to assist
in determining the cause of this outbreak. The WHO team, including
epidemiological, toxicological, and paediatric specialists, arrived
in Tetovo on 16 October.
<P>
The preliminary findings of the WHO expert team have revealed
no evidence of an infectious or toxicological cause for the syndrome.
The investigations are, however, not yet complete. WHO personnel
will remain in the country to continue the investigations, at
the end of which a report will be released.
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>For further information on this matter, please contact:
<P>
WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR> Scherfigsvej 8,
<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen<BR>Denmark.
<P>
You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel and Annette
Andkjaer in Communication and Public Affairs
<BR>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44  or  fax on (45)
39 17 18 80.</CENTER>
<HR>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 25 October 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>

