<TITLE>Press release 06</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>


Press release EURO/06/96<BR>
Copenhagen, November 1996



<H1>Albanian Poliomyelitis Epidemic Coming under Control </H1>



A significant decrease in new cases of poliomyelitis has been noted since the first round of the emergency national immunization campaign in Albania, announced WHO and United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) experts at a meeting with vaccination coordinators from 11 central and eastern European countries in Rome, Italy, 24-26 October 1996. <BR>
<center>

<IMG SRC="pr0696-1.GIF">



</center>


<P>
Beginning in April, the outbreak in Albania, due to imported poliovirus,
grew to affect a large number of people in August and September.
To date, 129 cases have been reported, and 13 deaths. With outside
assistance, Albania conducted its first round of an emergency
mass immunization campaign from 7 to 14 October, reaching over
90% of all residents up to 50 years of age. Since the completion
of the first round of immunization, only 10 new cases have been
reported. A second round will be conducted in November. WHO and
UNICEF are making a joint emergency appeal to donor governments
to help Albania complete these control efforts, and care for the
victims of the outbreak.
<P>
Laboratory tests have shown that the same virus has caused of
poliomyelitis in neighbouring countries. In the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia, 20 cases have been discovered in young children
in the Kosovo and Metohija region, adjacent to Albania. In an
urgent mass campaign carried out from 27 to 29 September, 98%
of children under age 5 years were immunized in the Kosovo and
Metohija region and bordering districts in Serbia.
<P>
In August and September, 6 cases of poliomyelitis were discovered
in unvaccinated young children in an ethnic subgroup in various
areas of Greece. Special immunization efforts are underway to
reach these populations.
<P>
While health authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina and The Former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia have not observed cases of paralytic
poliomyelitis to date, surveillance activities have been strengthened
and mass vaccination campaigns are being carried out with WHO
and UNICEF assistance.
<P>
&quot;Polio eradiction is still on target,&quot; declared Dr Sieghart
Dittman, Coordinator, Communicable Diseases, WHO Regional Office
for Europe, &quot;but all countries will need to step up efforts
aimed at complete vaccination coverage, which includes transient
and 'hard to reach' populations.&quot;

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=3>For further information on this matter, please
contact:
<P>
Communication and Public Affairs, <BR>WHO Regional
Office for Europe, <BR>Scherfigsvej 8,
<BR>DK-2100 Copenhagen, Denmark.<P>You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer
<BR>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44 or
fax on (45) 39 17 18 80.

<P>
All WHO Europe press releases, press notes,
and press backgrounders
<BR>
can be found on the WHO Internet home page
http://www.who.dk</FONT> </CENTER>


<HR>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 8 November 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>






