<P>
Press release EURO/07/96<BR>
Copenhagen, November  1996

<H2>European Forum of Nursing and Midwifery Associations and WHO
Established </H2>

<H3>&quot;A Formidable Force for Change&quot;</H3>


To strengthen nursing leadership in the promotion of health and
health care in Europe, representatives of 26 national nursing
associations and the WHO Regional Office for Europe established
the European Forum of Nursing and Midwifery Associations and WHO
in Madrid, Spain on 9 November 1996.
<P>
&quot;Europe's nurses represent a formidable force that can impact
all peoples health,&quot; declared
<P>
 Dr J.E. Asvall, WHO Regional Director for Europe, in his address
to the founding meeting.
<P>
 &quot;If we can  together release the health promoting potential
that exists in the millions of skilled nurses that are the backbone
of our health systems, we can help all countries to deal more
effectively with their health problems.&quot;
<P>
Europe's 4.5 million nurses and midwives constitute the largest
group of health care workers in almost every country. They will
be represented in the Forum by their professional associations.
Founding member associations welcomed the opportunity to be more
formally linked to each other and WHO as a way of strengthening
the voice of all nurses in both international policy and strategy
development.
<P>
The Forum will build upon the experience of European fora for
medical and pharmaceutical associations, which have been working
with WHO to promote public health in Europe since 1991. Their
activities have included consensus statements on important public
health concerns (such as tobacco policies), public and professional
education, and the development and dissemination of models of
good practice in health education and promotion.
<P>
 &quot;The Forum provides European nurses and midwives with a
pragmatic structure that ensures that planned developments really
take effect,&quot; noted Ainna Fawcett Henesy, Acting Regional
Adviser for Nursing and Midwifery. &quot;The Forum will have a
strong voice and will be a force for change, for better health
and quality of life for the hundreds of millions of people in
our Region into the 21<SUP>st</SUP> century.&quot;
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>For further information on this matter, please
contact:</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>Communication and Public Affairs, WHO Regional
Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1> DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1> You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer </FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44
or fax on (45) 39 17 18 80</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1> All WHO Europe press releases can be found
on the WHO Internet home page http://www.who.dk<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<H2>European Forum of Nursing and Midwifery Associations and WHO
</H2>

<H3>Declaration of Intent</H3>

<P>
Recognizing the value of dialogue between them and the potential
strength of joint action to promote health and health care in
Europe, the European Nursing and Midwifery Associations and the
World Health Organization (WHO) Regional Office for Europe agree
to the establishment of the <I>European Forum of Nursing and Midwifery
Associations and WHO</I>, in accordance with the terms set out<B>
</B>below:
<H3>AIMS</H3>

<P>
The aims are:
<P>
(a)  to contribute and inform the debate of improving health and
the quality of health care in Europe;
<P>
(b) to promote the exchange of information, ideas and policies
between nursing/midwifery associations and WHO;
<P>
(c)  to support the integration of appropriate policies for health
for all into nursing practice as well as into basic, postgraduate
and continuing nursing and midwifery education;
<P>
(d) to formulate consensus/policy statements and recommendations
on health and nursing/midwifery related issues, developed on consensus.
<P>
This meeting agrees to elect a steering committee to draw up operating
principles which will be presented for consideration at the next
plenary meeting.
<P>
<CENTER><I><B>Signed by representatives of 26 European Nursing
Associations and WHO</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><I><B> Madrid Spain 9 November 1996</B></I></CENTER>
<HR>

