<TITLE>Press release EURO/08/96</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<P>

Press release EURO/08/96<BR>
Copenhagen,  December  1996
<H2>Expert team reports on cause of mysterious illness in schoolchildren
of Albanian descent in The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia
</H2>


Between 26 September and 12 October 1996, about 1000 schoolchildren
(aged 11-17) in the municipality of Tetovo in The Former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia, all of them of Albanian descent, were treated
by the local health service for a symptom complex of unidentified
origin characterized by abdominal pain, headache, difficulty in
breathing, anxiety and other, less frequent symptoms. Most of
the children were hospitalized for 2-3 days in the Tetovo Medical
Centre. All recovered quickly with symptomatic treatment only.
No deaths were reported.
<P>
The outbreak has been a source of considerable stress on the country
as a whole , since some members of the ethnic Albanian community
have claimed that the children might have been poisoned.
<P>
On October 14, Dr I. Filipce, Minister of Health of The Former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, requested assistance from the
WHO Regional Office for Europe in evaluating the cause of the
outbreak. On October 16, a WHO team of experts - including a toxicologist,
epidemiologist, paediatrician, psychologist and psychiatrist -
arrived in Tetovo to begin their work. The team spent three weeks
in the country, reviewing clinical and epidemiological evidence.
The team had access to all existing files and worked with complete
freedom. Some children were clinically examined and a sample of
parents and teachers was interviewed and underwent a psychological
questionnaire. A substantial amount of medical records was reviewed
and an epidemiological case-control study with a self-administered
questionnaire was conducted in a supervised environment. Toxicological
studies were also carried out. Based on these investigations,
the following conclusions were drawn.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><B>Report on the Emergency Mission to the Tetovo Region
-</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Expert Team Conclusions</B></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI>The onset of symptoms was sudden, the duration short, and
no measurable side effects or long-term effects, apart from the
symptoms tending to recur in some children, were found.
<LI>It seems reasonably clear that an infectious agent was not
the cause of the symptom complex; the outbreak pattern and symptom
complex are not consistent with any known infectious processes.
<LI>Although not all environmental aspects could be investigated,
since specific environmental sampling did not take place, it appears
unlikely that the outbreak was due to general environmental poisoning,
since cases were confined to children of Albanian descent. Other
children and adults in the same environments were not affected.
<LI>A school-focused poisoning does not appear to be the cause
in that, if an agent had been administered on a selective class-by-class
basis, a more balanced sex ratio of affected people (rather than
the observed 66% female to 34% male) would have been observed.
<LI>The recurrent cases and relapses seen by members of the team
seem to be psychologically induced. The members of the WHO team,
however, did not see the 1000 children in the main outbreak; they
only studied their medical files and used data from a retrospective
epidemiological survey.
<LI>Although no specific evidence points to the conclusion, it
is possible that other factors, such as a minor viral or bacterial
infection or food intoxication, could have been involved in the
initial cases. One possible hypothesis is that such an event might
have started the whole outbreak. The schoolchildren saw symptoms
in their fellows and jumped to the conclusion that there had been
a &quot;poisoning&quot;. This could have resulted in case recruitment
around the first cases, possibly fostered by a stress situation,
anxiety or tension that exists between and within ethnic groups
in certain areas of the Tetovo municipality.
<LI>The number of people involved effectively excludes a mass
simulation and indicates psychologically induced events linked
to stress and anxiety.
<LI>While the team recognizes the important health service dimensions
of this outbreak, it feels that too little attention has been
paid to other contributing factors, such as the educational setting,
public order and social peace monitoring, and ethnic relations.
This carries the risk of putting the health care system under
an inappropriate spotlight and making it bear a disproportionate
responsibility for the present situation. Unless this approach
is improved, a similar problem could occur in the future.
</UL>

<P>
&quot;All evidence points to human suffering and tension in the
affected children and their families, in the schools, hospitals,
and municipal life related to this outbreak as the most crucial
findings of these missions&quot;, noted Zsuzsanna Jakab, WHO team
leader. &quot;Regardless of whether tension may have played an
instrumental role in the origin of the outbreak, the resulting
human suffering and tension should now be considered the main
health problem.&quot;
<P>
The expert team recommended the establishment of a community support
group - including national and local politicians, representatives
of affected citizen groups and individuals (children, adults and
teachers), health and other government agencies, health professionals
and the media - to share information, rebuild confidence and prevent
the occurrence of similar events in the future or at least minimize
their impact.
<P>
&quot;While we are relieved to know that no infectious or toxic
agents have been identified,&quot; noted Dr&nbsp;I. Filipce, at
the conclusion of his discussions with Dr&nbsp;J.E. Asvall, WHO
Regional Director for Europe, and Ms Jakab in Copenhagen on 4-6
December, &quot;our sympathies extend to the children and their
families who have been suffering these symptoms. We will take
action on the recommendations made by the WHO team and work hard
to prevent such episodes from recurring.&quot;
<P>
Dr Filipce and WHO will hold a  press conference in Skopje on
Friday 13 December to discuss the findings of the expert report.
<P>
&quot;This outbreak is a poignant example of how health is determined
by many different physical, social, cultural and political factors,&quot;
noted Dr&nbsp;Asvall. &quot;By actively involving the many people
and institutions who influence the creation of health in this
setting, not just those in the official health care system, health
can provide a common ground for conflict resolution and thus,
eventually, also to healing and better social development.&quot;
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>For further information on this matter, please
contact:
<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs, <BR>
WHO Regional Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,
<BR>
DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.
<BR>
You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer
<BR>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44
or fax on (45) 39 17 18 80
<BR>
All WHO Europe press releases can be found<BR>
on the WHO Internet home page http://www.who.dk<BR>
</FONT>

<hr>

