<P>
Press release EURO/09/96<BR>
 Copenhagen, December  1996
<P>
<H2>WHO selects a new Director for Programme Management<BR>
for WHO / Europe<BR>
</H2>


Dr Serguei Litvinov has been selected for the post of Director,
Programme Management of the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional
Office for Europe, effective 1 January 1997.
<P>
Dr Litvinov will succeed Dr David Macfadyen who is retiring from
the Organization.

<P>
Dr Litvinov started his work in WHO in the Regional Office for
Africa as a medical officer in the Ministry of Health, Ghana (1973-1979).
He next served as Assistant, Director-General in the Division
of Communicable Diseases at WHO headquarters in Geneva (1983-1987).
 In 1993, he joined the Regional Office for Europe to lead the
(then) new EUROHEALTH programme, focused on assisting in the public
health development of the newly independent states of the former
Soviet Union. During 1996, Dr Litvinov has been the (acting) Director
of the Country Health Department.

<P>
Prior to, and between WHO assignments, Dr Litvinov has worked
in the Ministry of Health and the Central Research Institute of
Epidemiology in Moscow. He received his medical degree from the
Second Medical Institute in Moscow in 1962. He has special training
in Tropical Medicine and the Epidemiology of Communicable Diseases.


<P>
 &quot;Dr Litvinov has earned the respect not only of his colleagues
in the Regional Office for Europe but also of the representatives
of the Member States,&quot; stated Dr Jo E. Asvall, Regional Director.
 &quot;We are very fortunate to have someone with his experience
and background to take over the demanding responsibility of Director,
Programme Management.  Dr Litvinov's wide knowledge of WHO, public
health and the needs of the European Member States combine to
make him an exceptional person in whom we can easily place our
confidence to lead the programmes of the Organization at this
important time in WHO.&quot;

<P>
Dr Litvinov lives in Copenhagen, Denmark with his wife and daughter.

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>For further information on this matter, please
contact:
<P>
Communication and Public Affairs, WHO Regional
Office for Europe, Scherfigsvej 8,
<P>
DK-2100 Copenhagen &Oslash;, Denmark.
<P>
You may telephone directly to Franklin Apfel
and Annette Andkjaer 
<P>
on (45) 39 17 13 36 or (45) 39 17 13 44
or fax on (45) 39 17 18 80.
<P>
All WHO Europe press releases can be found
on the WHO Internet home page http://www.who.dk
</FONT></CENTER>
