<H1>Press note no. 1</H1>

<P>
<B>updated 5.9.96</B>
<H3>WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8, 2100 Copenhagen</H3>

<H3>Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80</H3>

<P>
Press notes
summarize recent and upcoming newsworthy WHO activities, products
and services.  For each entry, a contact person is identified
for more details and technical information. The Communication
and Public Affairs (CPA) Unit is ready to help you with your coverage
of these subjects by providing graphics, pictures, video material
(where available) and by identifying regional and national experts
for interviews.
<P>
We would like to hear from you. Let
us know if these <B>Press notes</B> are useful and how they may
be improved to serve your needs.
<HR>

<H1>Lead story</H1>

<P>
<B>1. WHO Europe launches Freedom
of Movement (FOM) initiative for health in Bosnia</B>
<B>and  Herzegovina. Contact Dr Johanna Larusdottir, Coordination
and Humanitarian  Assistance Unit, Tel. (45) 39 17 15 73 </B>(story
embargoed until 6 September (press conference  in WHO).
<P>
 The WHO Bosnia and Herzegovina office
in Sarajevo, in coordination with the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR), has launched a media and educational campaign
to eliminate restrictions on freedom of movement between entities
in Bosnia and Herzegovina that are impeding access to health facilities
for patients and health workers alike.
<P>
<I><B> Additional details available.
Press conference details, photographs available from the CPA Unit,
(45) 39 17 13 36  or  39 17 13 44 / direct fax (45) 39 17 18 80. </B></I>
<H1>Other news stories</H1>

<P>
<B> 2. The Regional Office sets up
a task force on transmissible spongiform encephalopathy  (TSE).
Contact Dr Gunter Klein, Director, Environment and Health Department, </B>
<P>
<B>  Tel. (45) 39 17 13 46. </B>
<P>
 A Regional Office task force on TSE
proposes to support the development of a WHO surveillance system
for TSE, to advise Member States on appropriate TSE-related public
health actions, and to strengthen food safety capacity in the
Region. These recommendations will be taken up at the 46<SUP>th</SUP>
session of the WHO Regional Committee (see below).
<OL>
<LI><B> Health in Prisons project
launched in collaboration with the Department of Health, United
Kingdom.  Contact Cees Goos, Lifestyles and Health Unit, Tel.
(45) 39 17 15 01. </B>
</OL>

<P>
 Prisons have been identified as an
important setting for health promotion. Of particular concern
is the growing threat of outbreaks of communicable disease in
prisons, from tuberculosis to HIV, which carries serious implications
for the health of all Europeans.
<P>
<B> 4. Nursing Collaborating Centre
in Maribor Slovenia celebrates 10th anniversary. </B>
<P>
<B>  Contact Ainna Fawcett Henesy,
Acting Regional Adviser Nursing and Midwifery Unit, </B>
<P>
<B>  Tel. (45) 39 17 13 55. </B>
<P>
 &quot;Our centre has accomplished
much in ten years, and has influenced the practice of nursing
and consequently the health of all Slovenian people. This centre
is exemplary of many others  in providing a mechanism for making
contacts within and across our borders and, most importantly,
across disciplines and sectors.  It has also enabled us to move
beyond the normal narrow professional frameworks and see nursing
as a proper profession, not just a service  group,&quot; said
Majda Slajmer-Japelj, International Manager of the Centre<I>.</I>
<P>
<B> 5. Subregional Healthy Cities
Centre </B>  <B>established
in Maribor, Slovenia. Contact Dr Agis  Tsouros, Healthy Cities
Project, Tel. (45) 39 17 15 09.</B>
<P>
 Announcing the establishment of this
first subregional  Healthy Cities centre, Dr Jo E. Asvall, WHO
Regional Director for Europe, said, &quot;Maribor was selected
because it has consistently demonstrated sterling leadership in
initiating projects and in coordinating projects throughout this
Region. The tremendous support the Ministry of Health and the
City of Maribor are giving to the project reflects their belief
in the Healthy Cities concept and their interest in enhancing
the health of all Europe's peoples.&quot;
<P>
<B> 6. Seminar on national drug policy
development in the newly independent states (NIS) </B>
<P>
<B> of the former USSR, Hiller&oslash;d,
Denmark, 14 to 16 October 1996.  Contact: Dr Kees de Joncheere,
Quality of Care and Pharmaceuticals Unit, Tel. (45) 39 17 14 32. </B>
<P>
 Deputy ministers of health in charge
of pharmaceuticals and heads of drug regulatory agencies in the
NIS will meet to discuss progress and problems in developing and
implementing national drug policies. The policies represent a
guide for action and the governments' commitment to the goal of
population-wide access to, and the rational use of, essential
drugs.  Special attention will be given to drug regulatory issues.

<P>
<B> 7. The epidemic diphtheria situation
in the newly independent states (NIS) of the </B>
<P>
<B>  former USSR improves.  Contact
Dr Sighart Dittman, Communicable Diseases Unit, </B>
<P>
<B> Tel. (45) 39 17 13 98. </B>
<P>
 The epidemiological situation of
the diphtheria epidemic in the NIS has begun to show signs of
improvement. After rapid increases every year from 1990 to 1994,
reported cases in NIS increased only 5% in 1995. All countries
concerned in the region have made significant strides towards
fully immunizing their child and adult populations.
<P>
<B> 8. Forty-sixth session of WHO
Regional Committee for Europe (RC/46) convenes in  Copenhagen,
9-12 September 1996. Contact Helge Larsen, Executive Management
Unit,  Tel. (45) 39 17 12 74.<BR>
 </B>
<P>
 Ministerial delegations from 50 Member
States of the WHO European Region will gather at this 46<SUP>th</SUP>
annual &quot;parliamentary&quot; session of the Regional Committee.
Policies, priorities and the programme budget for 1997-1998 will
be discussed.
<H1>New products, services and  activities</H1>

<P>
<B> 9. WHO study released - <I><B>European
health care reform: an analysis</B></I><B> (summary available),
Contact Dr Josep Figueras, Health Care Services Department, Tel.
(45) 39 17 12 17</B> .</B>
<P>
 This report, incorporating the contributions
of over 75 academicians, professionals and health policy experts
from Europe, Canada, the World Bank and WHO, provides a comprehensive
review of European health reform activities, identifies what is
working well and what is not, and makes specific recommendations
to help policy makers surmount the challenges facing European
health care systems. <B>More information enclosed (graphics available).</B>
<P>
<B> 10. &quot;The Ljubljana Charter
on Reforming Health Care&quot; - ethical and managerial principles </B>
<P>
<B>  for change. Contact Dr Sedar
Savas, Health Care Services Department, Tel. (45) 39 17 12  25. </B>
<P>
 All ministers of health or their
representatives from the European Member States of WHO (participants
at the WHO Conference on European Health Care Reforms, Ljubljana,
Slovenia) pledged themselves to provide, and called upon all citizens
and urged all governments, institutions and communities to join
in promoting, these common ethical and managerial principles in
reforming health care systems <B>(article available)</B>.
<P>
<B>11.  Health care systems in transition:
 profiles. Contact Dr Josep Figueras,  </B>
<P>
<B> Health Care Services Department,
Tel. (45) 39 17 12 17. </B>
<P>
 The health care systems in transition
(HiT) profiles provide analytic descriptions of the health care
systems in countries and of any reform programmes under development.
The aim of the HiT initiative is to provide relevant comparative
information to support the development of health care systems
and reforms in countries in the WHO European Region <B>(HiT order
form available).</B>
<P>
<I><B> 12. Promotion of the rights
of patients in Europe.  </B></I><B>
Contact Dr Mikko Viennonen, Health  Services Department, Tel.
 (45) 39 17 12 03. </B>
<P>
 This new book describes the principles
and strategies for promoting the rights of patients within the
health care reform process. It emphasizes on options that could
be selected and adapted to fit different countries.
<P>
<B>13</B>. <B> Regional Office opens
World Wide Web site.  Contact Ms Mary-Stewart Burgher,  Library,
Tel. (45) 39 17 14 48. </B>
<P>
 WHO Regional Director for Europe,
Dr Jo E. Asvall comments, &quot;The World Wide Web is a new and
important tool that will help us communicate with both technical
and non-technical audiences. It offers a fast, efficient means
through which WHO/Europe can share information and contacts, and
thus widen and strengthen local actions aimed at improving public
health.&quot;<I> </I><B>The URL for the site is:   http://www.who.dk.</B>
<P>
<B>14.  European health promotion
audit service. Contact Dr Erio Ziglio, Investment in  Health Unit,
Tel. (45) 39 17 15 24. </B>
<P>
 This new health promotion audit service
provides national and regional decision-makers,
<P>
 such as parliamentarians, with an
expert review of health promotion policies, legislation, programmes
and outcomes in countries. Strengths and weaknesses are identified
and specific recommendations are made for developmental action .
<P>
<B> 15. European Information Service
on Medical Supplies (ISMS) helps guide donations to the  newly
independent states (NIS). Contact  Dr Jean Nicolas Ormsby, Eurohealth
 programme, Tel. (45) 39 17 13 94. </B>
<P>
 The WHO European Information Service
on Medical Supplies - known as ISMS - is a clearinghouse that
collects, processes and distributes health-related information
and data about the current resources and needs of the populations
of the newly independent states of the former USSR.  The information
covers three vital areas: Life-saving drugs, vaccines and basic
medical equipment<I>.</I>
<H1>Key products</H1>

<P>
<B>Health reform:   WHO report forms basis
for new European health care reforms</B>
<P>
<B>An expert report released at the WHO Conference on European
Health Care Reforms in Ljubljana, Slovenia, set the stage for
an intensified initiative by WHO to help policy-makers to surmount
the challenges facing European health care systems.</B>
<P>
The issues in the report were taken up when ministerial-level
delegations from 49 Member States of the WHO European Region met
in Ljubljana, Slovenia, from 17 to 20 June 1996 at the WHO Conference
on European Health Care Reforms. Ministers exchanged experiences,
analysed action to date and adopted the Ljubljana Charter on Health
Care Reforms, which articulates a common set of principles and
strategies.
<P>
The report emphasized the importance of measuring the success
of reform against long-term gains in health status. Cost containment
alone provides an inadequate basis for sustainable health care
reform, the report stated.
<P>
This sentiment was strongly underlined by WHO Regional Director
for Europe, Dr Jo E. Asvall, in his opening address to the Conference:
&quot;The problem in most countries today is that haphazard and
often drastic cuts are made in health care budgets without sufficient
understanding of what the functional consequences of the cuts
will be for the health care that people will receive. Until now,
health care administrations have attached little importance to
analysing the cost-effectiveness of different strategies ... such
a situation is clearly no longer acceptable!&quot;
<P>
The WHO study found little evidence of positive economic effects
from encouraging citizens to choose among insurers or to make
co-payments. On the contrary, the report expressed concern that
unless these demand-reducing approaches are accompanied by protective
regulation, they may substantially reduce access to necessary
health services and thus threaten the overall health of the population.
<P>
Against this background of shared concern, the newly adopted Ljubljana
Charter is centred on the principle that health care reform is
first and foremost about attaining better health for people. This
implies both a concern for having clear outcome targets for interventions
and clear mechanisms that ensure people's participation in the
process of reform. The Charter also lists the key action strategies
that can guarantee that reforms are geared towards achieving shared
goals.
<P>
In light of the pressing needs and expectations of the people
of Europe, the impact of the Ljubljana Charter on European policy-makers
is expected to be considerable.
<P>
&quot;Health care systems throughout Europe are bustling with
change,&quot; noted Dr Bozidar Voljc, Minister of Health of the
Republic of Slovenia. &quot;It is important to communicate and
exchange experiences so that common problems can be tackled uniformly,
since no country has yet found an ideal solution.&quot;
<H1>The Ljubljana Charter on Health Care Reforms</H1>

<P>
<B> (for French, German and Russian
translations: http://who.dk/policy/policy statements) </B>
<P>
<B> The six fundamental principles </B>
<UL>
<LI> Driven by values
<LI> Targeted on health
<LI> Centred on people
<LI> Oriented towards primary health
care
<LI> Focused on quality
<LI> Based on sound financing
</UL>

<P>
<B> The six principles for managing
change </B>
<UL>
<LI> Health Policy development
<LI> Citizens' voice and choice
<LI> Reshaping health care delivery
<LI> Human resources for health care
<LI> Strengthening management
<LI> Learning from experience
</UL>

<H2>Health care systems in transition profiles</H2>

<P>
The Health Care Systems in Transition (HiT) profiles provide analytical
descriptions of the health care systems in countries and of any
reform programmes under development. HiTs form the basis of the
information system on health systems and reforms at the WHO Regional
Office for Europe.
<P>
The HiT profiles are produced by country experts in collaboration
with staff in the Regional Office health systems analysis programme.
To maximize comparability between countries, a template and a
questionnaire have been developed. These provide detailed guidelines
and specific questions, definitions and examples to assist in
the process of developing the HiT profile. Quantitative data on
health services are based on the WHO health for all database,
OECD health data and World Bank data.
<P>
The current series of HiT profiles includes over half of the countries
in the Region. This is a continuing initiative with plans to extend
coverage to all countries in the Region and to up-date the material
at regular intervals and to monitor reforms over the longer term.

