<H2>Lead Stories</H2>

<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR><TD><B>1.</B></TD><TD><B>Forty-sixth session of WHO Regional Committee for Europe (RC/46) was held in Copenhagen, 9-12 September 1996. Contact Helge Larsen, Executive Management Unit,Tel. (45) 39 17 12 74.</B>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
Ministerial delegations from 47 Member States of the WHO European
Region gathered at the 46<SUP>th</SUP> annual &quot;parliamentary&quot;
session of the Regional Committee. Policies, priorities and the
programme budget for 1997-1998 were discussed. Key resolutions
were adopted related to:<BR>

<TABLE border=1>

<TR><TD>

<B>2.</B></TD><TD><B>A surveillance system for transmissible spongiform encephalopathy(TSE). Contact Dr Gunter Klein, Director, Environment and Health Department, Tel. (45)&nbsp;39&nbsp;17&nbsp;13&nbsp;46.</B>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>



<P>
Noting the serious public health threat represented by the newly
discovered variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) the RC/46
has asked the Regional Office to assist Member States in the development
of surveillance systems for TSE and to advise on appropriate TSE-related
public health actions. (see below).<BR>

<TABLE border =1>

<TR><TD><B>3.</B></TD><TD><B>Strengthen support to NIS in developing new drug policies. Contact: Dr Kees de Joncheere, Quality of Care and Pharmaceuticals Unit, Tel. (45) 39 17 14 32.</B>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
Noting  problems with access and affordability, acute shortages,
price  explosions, and increased irrational use of drugs,  the
RC requested that the Regional office enhance its support of national
drug policy development, national drug lists, drug regulation
and legislation,
<P>
reimbursement systems and financing. <B>New NIS  drug policies
should emphasize rational use and cost containment, not privatization.
</B>
<H2>Background material </H2>


The forty-sixth session of the Regional Committee for Europe was
held in Copenhagen from 9 to 13 September 1996. Representatives
of 47 countries of the Region took part. Also present were  representatives
of the Commission of the European Communities (EC), the Council
of Europe (CE) and nongovernmental organizations.
<P>
The Committee elected the following officers:
<UL>
<LI>Dr N. Kasiev (Kyrgyzstan) President
<LI>Professor J.-F. Girard (France) Executive President
<LI>Dr Marta di Gennaro (Italy) Deputy Executive President
<LI>Mrs B. Bitner (Poland) Rapporteur
</UL>

<H3>1. Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies (TSE)</H3>

<img src="cow.gif" align=left border=5>

Noting the serious public health threat represented by the newly
discovered variant of Ccreutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) the RC
has asked Member States to make voluntary donations where possible
to assist the WHO Regional Office for Europe to:

<br clear=left>
<UL>
<LI><B>Help establish surveillance in countries not yet included
in existing EU system</B>
</UL>


Surveillance will
<UL>
<LI> assess the dimension of the problem
<LI> monitor the situation by country
<LI>assess the impact of interventions
<LI>keep government and public informed
<LI>allow for epidemiological research
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><B>Advise countries on control measures to protect human health</B>
</UL>


Control measures recommended include:
<P>
No part or product of any animal with sign of TSE should enter
the animal or human food chain
<UL>
<LI>ensure their killing and safe disposal
<LI>review rendering procedures
<LI>ban use of ruminant tissues from ruminant feed
</UL>


Establishing surveillance and compulsory notification of BSE.
In absence of surveillance data, status of country is
unknown
<P>
Milk and its products considered safe, gelatin and tallow is safe
if appropriately treated
<P>
Medicinal products should be only made of animals from countries
with effective surveillance and/or sporadic cases of BSE
<UL>
<LI><B>Make best use of and not duplicate work carried out by
other agencies</B>
</UL>
<center>
<img src="cowstat.gif" border=5>

