<H2>2.Pharmaceuticals  </H2>


<B>Focus new NIS  drug policies on rational use and cost containment,
not on privatization. </B>
<P>
Background Bullets:
<UL>
<LI>Drugs represent an increasing percentage of health care costs
from around 10% in western European countries to an estimated
30% in several NIS countries
<LI>Drugs are the foremost used medical technology and they often
determine the face and credibility of the health care system
<LI>Access to drugs may still be a citizen's right in all European
countries, but it is unfortunately not a daily life reality anymore,
particularly in NIS.
<LI>The pharmaceutical industry panorama in Europe is changing
fast due to changes in regulation, drug financing and technological
progress
<LI>Role of government in pharmaceuticals sector is changing
<LI>Consumer awareness and empowerment is changing demands
</UL>



<P>
Pharmaceutical problems in NIS are due to
<UL>
<LI>breakdown central production and supply
<LI>reduction in budgets
<LI>breakdown of regulatory system
<LI>non-operational reimbursement schemes
</UL>


All these have led to problems with access and affordability,
acute shortages, price explosions, and increased irrational use
of drugs

<P>
<B>WHO/EUROPE action</B>
<P>
<B>Pharmaceutical sector reform assistance to CCEE and NIS is
a priority.</B>
<P>
Strategies include :
<UL>
<LI><B>Strengthen public sector capacity to manage</B>
<LI><B>Adjust policies to available funds and new market situation</B>
<LI><B>Focus policy on rational use and cost containment, not
on privitization.</B>
</UL>


Specific actions include developing:
<UL>
<LI><B>national drug policies and national drug lists</B>
<LI><B>drug regulation and legislation</B>
<LI><B>reimbursement system and financing</B>
<LI><B>improve prescribing and appropriate use of drugs</B>
<LI><B>training</B>
<LI><B>strengthen role of pharmacists in health promotion and
disease prevention.</B>
</UL>


RC Resolution calls for
<P>
Member States to draw up drug policies that provide access for
the whole population to needed medicines at an affordable cost
to the society and the individual;
<P>
To strengthen regulation and quality assurance of pharmaceuticals
as appropriate, including control of their marketing and of spontaneous
and intensive monitoring of adverse drug reactions;
<P>
To apply the interagency Guidelines for Drug Donations;
<P>
To evaluate the roles of public and private sectors;
<P>
It further appeals to those involved in the production and sale
of drugs as well as health personnel involved in their presentation
to use ethical criteria as appropriate to their spheres of competence,
activity and responsibility.
<H1>Highlights of the year </H1>

<H3>J.E. Asvall, Regional Director for Europe </H3>

<H2>Humanitarian assistance </H2>

<H3>Bosnia and Herzegovina</H3>

<img src="..\tech\ch\ar08.gif" border=5 align=left>
The devastation caused by armed conflicts in the Region reached
levels not experienced for the last fifty years. So while the
end to the war in Bosnia and Herzegovina was welcomed, there was
no doubt that the task of reconstruction would require the combined
efforts of the whole international community for many years ahead.
The Regional Office has been involved in that task from an early
stage and has given much input into drafting a framework document
for efforts to rebuild the health system in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
WHO chairs the sectoral task force on health, which is one of
the task groups established subsequent to the presentation of
the reconstruction framework.
<H3>Croatia</H3>


In Croatia, the Regional Office has been working very closely
with the Government in its efforts to develop a master plan for
reconstruction of its health care facilities following damage
from war.
<H3>Chechynia</H3>


WHO (like other United Nations organizations) has been operating
in the area around Chechnya itself. Two staff members have set
up an office in North Ossetia to help implement a project which
included the provision of vitally needed laboratory kits, drugs,
vaccines and medical equipment. Humanitarian assistance has also
been provided to Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia and Tajikistan.
<H3>Economic development in the Region</H3>


Economic development has been extremely varied in the Region.
In western European countries, slow economic grow of about 2-4%
per annum has continued. The countries of central and eastern
Europe (CCEE) as a whole have managed to reverse the previous
trend, achieving average growth rates of about 4%, although there
were considerable variations between individual countries. For
most of the newly independent states (NIS) the situation continued
to be bleak, with further reductions in gross domestic product
in 1995.
<center>
<img src="gdp.gif"border=5>

</center>


<H3>General health trends</H3>


Overall health improvements have been noted for many western European
countries, notably a reduction (for the first time) in reported
number of new cases of AIDS. Trends in life expectancy and infant
mortality showed signs of improvement in CCEE and, although the
situation for the NIS in general was poor, there was for the first
time since the late 1980s a slight increase in life expectancy
in the Baltic states and the Russian Federation. In contrast to
those modestly positive trends, the situation of noncommunicable
diseases showed severe deterioration in NIS, with mortality from
diseases of the circulatory system rising sharply.

<center>
<img src="life.gif" border=5><P>
<img src="infant.gif" border=5>
</center>



<H3>Homicide and suicide</H3>


Equally alarming were the figures for mortality from external
causes such as injury and poisoning, homicide and suicide, where
steep increases were seen in the NIS, while the trend in CCEE
and western Europe was fairly stable or slightly downward.
<center>
<img src="suicide.gif" border=5>
<P>
<img src="homicide.gif" border=5>
</center>

<H2>Communicable diseases </H2>


The diphtheria epidemic that emerged in the Russian Federation
in 1990 has since affected all 15 NIS, with over 50&nbsp;000 cases
by 1995, yet it was an instance where a major public health intervention
has proved successful. On the basis of the difference between
projected and reported cases, an estimated  100&nbsp;000 cases
have been prevented due to the combined efforts of the Member
States involved, with international assistance. However, continued
support is still needed.

<P>
<center><img src="diph.gif" border=5></center><P>

The MECACAR initiative to eradicate poliomyelitis involved 22
Member States, 14 from the European and 8 from the Eastern Mediterranean
regions. Several rounds of mass vaccination had been carried out
and only 12 cases of poliomyelitis had been reported in the European
Region from January to June 1996.
<P>
<center><img src="polio.gif" border=5></center><p>

The increased incidence of malaria was a new problem. The Regional
Office had been collaborating intensively with WHO headquarters
on that issue, and plans for malaria control in Azerbaijan, Tajikistan
and Turkey had been drawn up and submitted to the international
donor community for support.
<P>
Particularly disturbing was the recent very rapid increase in
the incidence of syphilis in NIS and, albeit to a lesser extent,
in some CCEE. That development represented a great danger of the
spread of AIDS - the most recent figures on HIV  incidence from
Ukraine, for example, unfortunately mirrored the rise seen for
syphilis.nsive action, yet unfortunately it came at a time when
the WHO programme on AIDS had been disbanded. The advent of the
UNAIDS programme in January 1996 had led to a two-thirds reduction
in the number of Regional Office staff active in that field.<P>
<center><img src="hiv.gif" border=5></center>

<H2>Mad Cow Disease </H2>


The sudden discovery of a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease
gave rise to much concern. WHO headquarters responded to that
new threat by organizing several technical meetings, and guidelines
for the establishment of a surveillance system will shortly be
forthcoming. The Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
(SCRC) advised that a regional surveillance system should be organized
(see resolutions above).
<H2>Health care reform </H2>

<img src="reform.gif" align=left border=5>
The Ljubljana Conference on health care reform had confirmed that
blindly applying market principles to the health sector would
have severe repercussions for health care in Region. The charter
endorsed at the Conference placed strong emphasis on developing
health care systems that were governed by principles of human
dignity, equity, solidarity and professional ethics, and it clearly
mapped out six strategies for action. The extensive material produced
for the Conference will be a great asset for follow-up action
by health care reform networks in countries.
<H2>Quality of care </H2>

<img src="quality.gif" border=5 align=left>
A major achievement in this area has been the formulation of national
policies in Denmark and Belgium, with 11 more countries starting
such work. The development of specific clinical quality indicators,
which had started in the area of diabetes, was now being expanded
to include selected mental health conditions, low back pain, oral
health, vascular surgical interventions, delivery and stroke.
<P>
In November 1995 a pan-European consensus conference on stroke
management was organized by the Regional Office in collaboration
with a large number of international organizations active in that
field. Agreement was reached on goals for stroke management by
the year 2005.
<H2>Lifestyles and health </H2>


<img src="alcohol.gif" align=left border=5>
Of the many and varied activities in the area of lifestyles and
health, the Conference on Health, Society and Alcohol deserves
special mention. In spite of the sensitive nature of the issue,
remarkable agreement was reached on the underlying values that
should be applied in order to reduce the health problems caused
by alcohol consumption. It is now up to each Member State to review
its national strategies in the light of the information generated
by that Conference.
<br clear=left>
<P>
<img src="tobacco.gif" align=left border=5>
The Regional Office has consolidated its collaboration with the
European Forum of Medical Associations (EFMA) on the problem of
tobacco: at the EFMA meeting in 1996 there was support for much
stronger action on tobacco and health in the European Region.
<br clear=left>
<H2>Environment and health </H2>

<img src="uk.gif" align=left border=5>
Particularly encouraging developments took place with regard to
the development of national environment and health action plans.
The first completed national plan was that of the United Kingdom,
and at least 16 other Member States have begun a similar development.
<br clear=left>
<P>
The year 1996 was the tenth anniversary of the Chernobyl accident
and the lessons learned from that disaster have been reviewed.
The Regional Office, WHO headquarters and IARC have finalized
a programme of work covering the next five-year period.
<H2>Health for All policy </H2>

<img src="hfabook.gif" align=left border=5>
The Bratislava meeting on future trends sparked
ideas for the update of the European Health for All (HFA) policy,
the first draft of which will be presented to the Regional Committee
at its next session.


<P>
Several Member States have national policy documents under development,
and Malta has recently finalized its new HFA policy. There has
also been substantial activities in that field at subnational
level.
<br clear=left>

<H2>Networking the networks
</H2>
<center>
<img src="network.gif" border=5></center><p>
In recent years, the Regional Office has made increasing use of
its many networks (CINDI, Health-promoting hospitals, Healthy
Cities, the Regions for Health Network, Health-promoting schools).
While each of those networks has its own character, partners,
target groups and methods of working, they share the common goal
of promoting a common understanding of European HFA policy. Efforts
have therefore been made to integrate these networks more effectively,
both within the Regional Office and in Member States.
<H2>International collaboration
</H2>


Cooperation with the World Bank has been intensified and a joint
seminar took place. Many different collaborative actions have
been carried out with the European Commission. Of particular note
was the report prepared by the Regional Office on the &quot;State
of health in the European Union&quot;, which was used as the basis
for a Commision communication in September 1995.

<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 30 September 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>


</HTML>
</DOC>
