<HTML>


<TITLE>Press Backgrounder </TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>


<center>

<H1>Press background</H1>
</center>
<hr>


<H3>WHO Regional Office for Europe</H3>

<P>
<B>Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8<BR>
2100 Copenhagen</B>
<P>
<B>Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80</B>
<H1>WHO and UNHRC campaigns for<BR>
 freedom of movement in Bosnia and Herzegovina</H1>

<H2>Restrictions on freedom of movement between the two entities
of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina threaten health and
peace </H2>

<H3>What is freedom of movement (FOM) in the context of health
in Bosnia and Herezegovina?</H3>


Simply put, people - patients and health care workers alike -
 should have access to all health facilities within the borders
of their country regardless of their ethnicity or place of residence.

<P>
Patients should be able to obtain appropriate services at the
closest health facility. Health workers should be able to work
in communities in which they are a minority.
<P>
In Bosnia and Herzegovina, these principles have been formally
adopted through the signing of the Dayton peace accord.
<P>
In reality, restriction of movement is far more prevalent than
freedom of movement.
<H2>How big a problem is this?</H2>


There is relatively little freedom of movement for
patients and health workers alike. Incidents of cross-border referrals
and service provision are exceptional. Opportunities for displaced
health workers to return to their original place of work are not
materializing.
<HR>

<P>
Vinac is a small town in western Bosnia and Herzegovina about
10 kms from Jajce. Vinac has one small <I>ambulata</I> (medical
centre). The Vinac <I>ambulata</I> has had problems in referring
patients to the closest hospital (in Jajce), because of current
restrictions of movement.
<P>
<CENTER><I>Vinac doctor speaks:</I></CENTER>
<P>
<I>&quot;There is no freedom of movement. When people
go to Jajce, they are stopped by the police and sent back. We
cannot take that risk with our patients.&quot;</I>
<HR>

<H2>What are the health consequences of restricted freedom of
movement?</H2>

<P>
Restricted freedom of movement has far-reaching negative
consequences for health.
<P>
 On a broad scale, living with prolonged fear and
a sense of entrapment can only serve to erode the health and happiness
of any community. Financially, the duplication of resources in
the development of two or three parallel and independent health
systems in Bosnia and Herzegovina is costly, impractical and unsustainable.
<P>
 On a personal level, the restriction of movement
denies patients proper treatment and services.  Restricted movement
also means that supplies and equipment cannot get to the people
who need them.
<H2>What can be done?</H2>


 All is not negative, however. National and international
agencies have begun actively to work on technical and other solutions.
<P>
 Police check points have been reduced in number and
are now operating more professionally.
<P>
 UNHCR has been coordinating efforts to reopen bus
lines across the interentity boundary line. Bus lines have begun
operating again with international supervision thus allowing public
transportation across borders / boundaries.
<P>
 Health professionals on many levels have begun to
communicate again.
<P>
 The ministers of health of the two entities (the
Federation and the Republika Srpska) meet regularly to discuss
important issues and try to harmonize health service reconstruction.
<HR>


<CENTER><I> Minister of Health, Tuzla Canton, speaks: </I></CENTER>
<P>
<I> &quot;First of all, the health professionals can
receive a patient and provide a good service and try to make patients
understand that they are not enemies. Patients cannot be enemies
and health professionals cannot be enemies; they have to cooperate.&quot; </I>
<HR>

<P>
 Virtually all health professionals express the willingness
to treat any patient, regardless of ethnicity or place of residence.
<H2>WHO initiatives</H2>


 WHO is addressing these issues in several ways.
<P>
 For the general population, a mass distribution of
pamphlets, supported by a local media campaign, is being organized
jointly by the WHO Bosnia and Herzegovina office in Sarajevo and
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
<P>
 The pamphlet, entitled <I>The right to medical care
and freedom of movement for patients and medical staff</I>, draws
people's attention to the principles enshrined in medical ethics
and international conventions. It is being produced in local languages
for distribution from the WHO and UNHCR field offices.
<P>
 Opening and facilitating dialogue between health
professionals is another step.
<P>
 On the federal level, WHO Team Leader and Senior
Adviser on Health Reforms, J. Michael McGinnis, M.D., has been
chairing sectoral task force meetings in Bosnia and Herzegovina
sponsored by the World Bank. These meetings have provided the
forum for the ministers of health of the two entities to meet
regularly and discuss major health care issues.
<P>
 Public health initiatives are at the heart of WHO's
work; for example, infectious disease control requires cross-border
participation of professionals from all sides.
<P>
 On the canton level, the WHO field office in Tuzla
has been bringing health professionals together to discuss cross-referral
systems, the sharing of resources and freedom of movement for
patients and health workers.
<P>
 The WHO office in Banja Luka is supporting pharmaceutical
safety net initiatives aimed at ensuring that all people have
access to medicines and supplies.
<P>
 The WHO field office in Mostar has been very active
is promoting cross-border links. Joint seminars in physical rehabilitation
are frequently held. While the flow of patients from one side
to the other is still minimal, health workers are now meeting
and WHO has organized a systematic exchange of surplus supplies
to &quot;the other side&quot; as needed.
<P>
 The WHO regional models for mental health regularly
bring together health professionals from all sides to develop
comprehensive community-based care.
<HR>


<CENTER><I> An east Mostar psychiatrist speaks: </I></CENTER>
<P>
<I> &quot;We did not like what your people did to
us during the war, but at least we understand now that it was
not you, our colleagues, who were shooting at us. You were trying
to take care of those in need, as we did.&quot; </I>
<HR>

<P>
 &quot;Health can and must be a bridge to peace,&quot;
says Dr Jo E. Asvall, WHO Regional Director for Europe. &quot;
These critical efforts to address very  difficult problems related
to freedom of movement are crucial to the health and stability
of the whole of Europe.&quot;
<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 9 September 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>


