<HTML>


<TITLE>Health in West Saxony, Germany</TITLE>

<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<H3>Press Background</H3>


26 September 1996
<P>
<B>WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8, <BR>
2100 Copenhagen
<P>
Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80<BR>
</B>
<center>
<H1>The WHO/West Saxony Investment for Health Initiative  </H1>

<H2>Health as the Common Ground </H2>
</center>

West Saxony, like many other regions in the former eastern Germany,
is confronting special difficulties which threaten people's health.
 Closure of  state-owned enterprises has contributed to high unemployment.
 Uranium mining has had significant negative effects on the environment.
Limited budgets and large needs are forcing policy makers to make
tough choices.
<P>
The WHO / West Saxony <I><B>Investment for Health</B></I> project
will help decision makers choose policy options that achieve better
health for people in the region; choices that also contribute
to the social and economic development of the area.  &quot;While
providing disease care will always be a necessary expenditure,
health promotion should be seen as an important developmental
investment<I>, </I>&quot; states Dr Erio Ziglio, WHO Regional
Adviser for Health Promotion and Investment.  &quot;This project
aims to maximize the health benefit derived from each Deutsch
Mark spent on social development programmes.&quot;
<P>
Major projects have been launched by the Region and private enterprise
aimed at improving the economy, employment possibilities, environmental
conditions, physical and social well being of the people of West
Saxony.  &quot;All of these projects are investments in health,&quot;
notes Professor Lowell Levin, Yale University School of Public
Health (USA) and one of the WHO experts assigned to the project.
&quot; The WHO team will facilitate learning and exchange across
projects, advise on the comparative effectiveness of different
policy options and approaches, and develop the skills of a local
network of people who can successfully lead and manage the change
process.&quot;
<P>
Utilizing this approach the WHO Investment for Health team has
assisted decision makers in municipalities and Regions in Italy
and Spain to choose health creating policies and in so doing has
helped economic development and resolve priority conflicts between
competing sectors, e.g., agriculture and tourism.
<P>
&quot;The WHO Regional Office for Europe is very pleased to be
invited to participate in this  <I>Investment for Health</I> project
in West Saxony,&quot; declared Marc Danzon, M.D., Director of
Health Promotion and Disease Prevention.  &quot;Our team looks
forward to working with local policy makers over the next eighteen
months and demonstrating the value of utilising health as the
common ground upon which to build developmental policies.&quot;
<HR>




<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 3 October 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>

