<HEAD>

<TITLE>PRESS background 3</TITLE>

<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">
<img src="publhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="cpa01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>



<H3>Press background 03</H3>


updated 11.10.96
<P>
<B>WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
Scherfigsvej 8, 2100 Copenhagen<BR>
Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and 39 17 13 36<BR>
Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80</B>
<H1>Drug policy and donation in the Baltics and NIS </H1>


Progress and problems related to drug regulations
and donations will be the focus of discussion as health ministers
in charge of pharmaceuticals and chief drug regulators from the
newly independent states (NIS) and the three Baltic countries
meet for the first time in Hiller&oslash;d, Denmark14-16 October
1996.
<P>
Worrisome trends challenge drug policy makers in these eastern
parts of the European region.
<UL>
<LI>Drugs represent an increasing percentage of health care costs
with an estimated 30% in several NIS countries compared to around
10% in western European.
<LI>Access to drugs is not a daily life reality , particularly
in NIS.
<LI>The influence of private pharmaceutical interests on prescribing
patterns is growing.
<LI>The role of government in the pharmaceuticals sector is changing.
<LI>Consumer awareness and empowerment is making new demands on
governments.
<LI>International drug donations need sharper management and co-ordination.
</UL>

<P>
&quot; The problems these drug policy makers face are real and
immediate,&quot; states Kees de Joncheere, WHO Regional Adviser,
Pharmaceutical Programmes, Europe. &quot;The health of their populations
is deteriorating,  they are running out of money, and drugs continue
to be used in increasingly irrational ways. The aim of this meeting
is to assist these key decision makers in creating policies which
accurately reflect available funds, the new market situation and
focus on rational drug use and cost containment.&quot;
<P>
The WHO European Office has been actively involved in the development
of national essential drugs programmes and pharmaceutical sector
reforms in the NIS and the countries of central and eastern Europe
since 1992. Intensive project work is currently underway in the
Central Asian Republics, the Caucasian Republics and the Russian
Federation.
<P>
For further information <B>Contact: Kees de Joncheere, Quality
of Care and Pharmaceuticals Unit, Tel. (45) 39 17 14 32.<BR>




<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td> &copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 30 October 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>

