<HEAD>

<TITLE>Press background 4</TITLE>

<BODY background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<P>
<IMG src="publhead.gif"> <BR>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../homeknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<A href="../Welcome.htm"><IMG src="../prevknap.gif"></A> <A href="cpa01.htm"><IMG src="../nextknap.gif"></A>

<H3>Press background /04 </H3>

<P>
<B>updated 14.10.96</B>
<P>
<B>WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<B>Communication and Public Affairs<BR>
<B>Scherfigsvej 8, 2100 Copenhagen<BR>
<B>Tel. (45) 39 17 13 44 and (45) 39 17 13 36<BR>
<B>Fax. (45) 39 17 18 80</B></B></B></B></B>
<H1>EuroPharm Forum catalyses good pharmacy practice in a changing
world </H1>

<P>
New ways pharmacists can help people with asthma and chronic illnesses
will be the focus of the 5<SUP>th</SUP> annual meeting of the
award winning EuroPharm Forum to be held at the WHO Regional Office
for Europe in Copenhagen, Denmark 17-18 October 1996.
<P>
The EuroPharm Forum aims to improve health through catalysing
the development of health generating pharmacy practice projects
at national level.
<P>
&quot;The Forum has had a global influence on the way pharmacists
practise,&quot; noted Kees de Joncheere, WHO Regional Adviser
for Pharmaceuticals. &quot;The projects developed by the Forum
have shown the world how much pharmacists as primary care professionals
can contribute to improving peoples health.&quot;
<P>
EuroPharm Forum projects have assisted pharmacists help people
stop smoking, control diabetes and use medicines better. In recognition
of the innovative and far-reaching effect of these projects the
Forum received the 1996 Pharmaceutical Practitioner of the Year
Award<B> </B>from the International Pharmaceutical Federation
(IFP).
<P>
This year the Forum will be proposing to its Members asthma and
chronic disease projects which aim to improve the capacities of
pharmacists to assist people with asthma and chronic diseases.
An asthma project &quot;package&quot; developed by the WHO Collaborating
Centre for Pharmacy in Hiller&oslash;d, Denmark will be presented
for discussion.
<P>
Pharmaceutical associations from 30 of the 50 WHO European Member
States are expected to attend this year's meeting.
<P>
For further information, contact: Kees de Joncheere, Quality of
Care and Pharmaceuticals Unit; Tel: (45) 39 17 14 32, E-mail:
<a href=mailto:cjo@who.dk><b>cjo@who.dk</B></A>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD><B><IMG src="../whoblk.gif"></B></TD><TD>&copy; WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/<BR>
<I>Updated 17 January 1997 - jfr@who.dk</I></FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>

