<HTML>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Introduction</H1>

<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>
<H2>From chaos to structure</H2>

<P>
In September 1992 the World Health Organization (WHO), through
its Regional Office for Europe, initiated a programme of humanitarian
assistance to Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro). At the onset of
the conflicts, the Regional Office had little experience of war
situations.
<P>
<img src="ar03.gif" border=5 align=right>

After more than three years of work under war conditions, many
lessons have been learned. WHO has developed and implemented a
field-based strategic approach. Exposed to a similar conflict
today, WHO would make a different immediate response. The health
consequences of war could be more systematically targeted. Action
strategies built on the accumulated experience of field staff
would be implemented more quickly.
<H2>Changing profile</H2>

<P>
Little by little, the profile of WHO has changed from our traditional
image as an organization setting technical standards to a more
active defender of health of populations. Today WHO works not
only symbolically but directly at the front lines of human health.
<P>
In this mission area, WHO has been linking a field presence on
the ground with our strength of international expertise. WHO has
taken the lead in coordinating the health efforts of the international
donors, intergovernmental organizations (IGOs) and nongovernmental
organizations (NGOs) with our traditional partners in health,
the health authorities and professionals in countries. This has
enhanced the effectiveness of the humanitarian assistance, and
helped identify gaps and avoid duplication.
<P>

<img src="ar04.gif" border=5 align=right>
WHO's presence of core staff in a network of field offices offered
the opportunity to carry out systematic assessments of needs and
resources on the spot. These were used to guide the emergency
response from the perspectives of modern knowledge of public health.
Later, this approach offered us the chance to move gradually and
naturally from direct emergency assistance, through a transitional
state, into the mid- and longer-term perspectives of health development
and reform.
<P>
A significant element in this process has been capacity building
among local health professionals at all levels. No health care
system could be prepared for such a disaster. War&Otilde;s unnatural
drain on local expertise made it even more important to offer
support to the health workers that remained.
<img src="ar05.gif" align=right border=5>

<H2>Three kinds of problems</H2>
<P>
War generates three kinds of public health problems.
<P>
The first kind comprises the problems related to the breakdown
of existing health care systems and normal preventive actions.
War leads directly to the destruction of the health system, including
hospitals and other health institutions. The socioeconomic consequences
of war, with the lack of medical essentials and medicines, as
well as the breakdown of family and social networks, lead indirectly
to a deterioration in health. The chronically ill and the elderly
become particularly vulnerable.
<P>
For example, the lack of food, clean water, heating, electricity
and systematic rubbish collection, plus the disruption of vaccination
programmes, increases the risks of infectious diseases.
<P>
<img src="ar06.gif" align=right>

The second type comprises emergency and rehabilitation problems
arising from war-related physical injuries. Huge numbers of wounded
people, with lost limbs, spinal cord lesions, traumatic brain
damage and other injuries, change health profiles dramatically.
<P>
Third are mental health problems due to the traumatization of
the whole population by the
<P>
violations of human rights committed in the war. The result is
not an epidemic of mental illness; it is more the reactions of
normal people to a sick situation. As alcoholism, drug abuse,
violence, suicides and psychosomatic diseases increase, these
reactions have major consequences for health.
<P>
WHO has addressed all three problem areas. Actions include technical
advice (including capacity building), delivering medical supplies,
and carrying out model projects and programmes to demonstrate
comprehensive WHO guidelines in practice.
<br clear=left>
<img src="ar07.gif" align=right>

<H2>Proactive public health</H2>

<P>
Although WHO is a neutral and professional organization, we have
insisted on and worked proactively to promote optimal public health
interventions. In the dialogue with our varied partners, we have
stressed the necessity of a focus on primary health care and community-oriented
approaches (for example, in mental health and rehabilitation).
<P>

Another principle has been to work on all sides of the front lines
using documented humanitarian and other health needs to guide
our steps. This perspective has not always been popular among
the warring factions.
<img src="ar08.gif" align=right>

Ethical dilemmas have arisen from efforts to balance the mandate of working with the national authorities as natural partners with interventions based on humanitarian needs. To work on both sides of the front line does not mean an acceptance of a particular political view. Rather, WHO has taken an approach of "ethical neutrality", emphasizing respect for human rights. There is no doubt that human rights violations undermine health.


<H2>The next phase
</H2>In November 1995, the Dayton peace agreement changed the scenario.
<P>
Nevertheless, in the next phase of WHOs work in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro), we will continue to work on all sides. The Implementation Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina (IFOR) mandate has been to stop the war and separate military forces. Our work focuses on uniting people again. WHO works for reconciliation and the substantiation of the peace. Work to improve the health situation in the post-war phase can form bridges to re-establish personal, professional and political connections and networks. Activities to build health and peace are critical to prevent new wars.
<P>
With these remarks let me invite you to read a more detailed description of the lessons learned through this work in 1995, as summarized in our annual report.
<P>
<I>S&oslash;ren Buus Jensen
</I>
<BR>Special Representative of
the Regional Director<BR>
WHO Area Office for
Humanitarian Assistance








<hr>
<center>
