<HTML>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>What does WHO do?</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>

<H2>A gruesome year of war</H2>

<P>
The Dayton peace agreement ended 1995 on a note of hope. But it
had been another gruesome year of war. More than 12 000 deaths
were reported by the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina alone.
Some of these people actually died earlier, and their bodies were
exhumed from mass graves. Thousands presumed killed in Srebrenica
have not yet been included in the figures.
<P>
This brings the death toll since the beginning of the conflict
in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia to an estimated 200 000.
There were approximately 200 000 wounded and disabled. More than
3.8 million people have been driven from their homes.

<img src="ar09.gif" align=left>

<H2>Linking global to local</H2>

<P>
WHO takes a world view. It is the one global public health authority
capable of surveying the total health situation.
<P>
Following our health for all mandate, we have helped preserve
and promote public health impartially in Bosnia and Herzegovina,
Croatia, and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro).
<P>
WHO is the only health alliance working officially with each government.
We carry out our work through local health authorities.
<P>
This often makes our presence less  visible to many. None the
less, WHO serves as the knowledge chip inside the public health
computer. We process vital information, drawing on worldwide health
databases and networks of scientific experts to assist with local
action.
<P>
In the longest and bitterest conflict on the continent since the
Second World War, we have learned the importance of making our
knowledge chip more visible. Nearly four years of experience in
a war zone have taught us that effective coordination demands
more than knowledge. It requires a field presence that can:
<UL>
<LI>work with all agencies involved in public health projects
(health ministries, national, regional and local health authorities,
other United Nations agencies, the International Federation of
Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC), the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), the European Community, NGOs
and donors);
<LI>function on the local, regional, national and international
levels;
<LI>assess needs and do preparedness planning;
<LI>do its job as closely as possible to where needs exist;
<LI>provide supplies and technical help with their use;
<LI>act rapidly to fill gaps; and
<LI>be a strong, independent advocate for health.
</UL>
<img src="ar10.gif" align=right>

<H2>The field presence</H2>
<P>
The WHO field presence is a network of international and local
health professionals and support personnel, staffing central and
satellite offices throughout Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia,
and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro).
Currently these offices are located in Banja Luka, Belgrade, Bihac,
Mostar, Eastern Slavonia, Sarajevo, Tuzla, Zagreb and Zenica.
<br clear=left>
<img src="ar11.gif" align=right>

<P>
This field deployment allows rapid response to health emergencies
such as epidemics and refugee influxes. In the longer term, the
links with local health authorities lay the groundwork for better
health planning, reconstruction and reform.
<P>
In line with a continuing management improvement strategy recommended
by independent evaluators in 1994, decision-making has been increasingly
decentralized to the head offices in each region. Now those closest
to the situation can respond faster to emergencies.
<P>
The WHO Coordination and Humanitarian Assistance Unit in Copenhagen
guides overall policy, mobilizes resources (personnel, funds and
supplies) and ties field activities to a global network of experts.
These activities are supported by the Division of Emergency and
Humanitarian Action at WHO headquarters in Geneva.
<H2>Scores of agencies</H2>

<P>
All WHO offices are engaged in coordination. Creating and running
meetings and other networking mechanisms have drawn agencies working
in the mission area into a more effective whole. Multi-agency
networks have been formed around each field office. These facilitate
mutual learning and support leading to a dynamic response system
across the board.

<img src="ar12.gif" align=left>

<H2>NGO clearing-house</H2>

<P>
WHO offices in the mission region assumed an NGO clearinghouse
function. Throughout the nearly four-year conflict, NGOs have
swiftly and efficiently provided critically needed supplies and
training.
<P>
Operating outside the United Nations banner, NGOs fill specialized
niches. But some lack an overview of the total health situation.
This is WHO&Otilde;s forte. We have served a coordinating function
from the outset, advising many NGOs on using their resources according
to need and orienting new NGOs wanting to become involved in the
region.
<P>
With so many operating in the region, this has proved a challenging
task. Everyone is for coordination but few really want to be coordinated.
We have done our best to identify the gaps and steer the right
agencies towards filling them. And when this was not possible
we tried to fill the gap ourselves.
<P>
The provision of basic microbiology and biochemistry supplies,
chlorine tablets, antibiotics, spare parts for equipment in health
units, and thermal underwear for freezing refugees are all examples
of our efforts to fill gaps in 1995.
<H2>Passing the word</H2>

<P>
Throughout the war, WHO has collected and circulated information.
News was passed along in several forms. From the Sarajevo office,
an update on communicable diseases in Bosnia and Herzegovina was
published monthly.
<P>
<img src="ar13.gif" align=right>

Besides the latest epidemiological figures, the bulletin highlighted
the implications of these diseases for international humanitarian
assistance and stressed appropriate action.
<P>
Monthly reports from the Zagreb field office were issued and widely
circulated. These were integral in drawing information together
about WHO programmes for donors and other regional organizations.

<P>
Not only were WHO activities reported, but significant changes
in the regional situations of all relevant agencies got attention.
<H2>A health directory</H2>

<P>
Health coordination in Belgrade is a joint activity with the Institute
of Public Health of Serbia, where twice-a-week conferences are
held. Topics cover the entire Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia
and Montenegro) and, when necessary, the health activities of
the Republika Srpska.
<P>
Satellite meetings in Kosovo, run by IFRC, and in Vojvodina, run
by the European Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO), are pulled
together with central meetings. Attendance has been consistently
high. A joint directory, Partners in health, published three times
a year, lists the health programmes of each agency.
<H2>&quot;Pending crisis&quot; bulletins</H2>

<img src="ar15.gif" align=left border=5>

<P>
Pulling things together and suggesting plans of action, the Sarajevo
office produced its own ad hoc weekly bulletins on the health
status of the population of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
<P>
In the summer of 1995, the numbers of civilians killed or injured
in Bosnia and Herzegovina sharply increased. Getting any medical
supplies through the siege to the towns was almost impossible.
Shelling was directed against hospitals and wounded or sick people.
Water, food, gas and electricity were again turned into weapons
of war.
<P>
Such awful abuses of health-related human rights obviously provoked
heated discussion among WHO field staff over how to deal with
it. What does a health organization do in such a situation?
<P>
The bulletins stressed the harm being done to health. They shed
the words of diplomacy to point to flagrant human rights violations.
Snipers were seen shooting patients in hospital beds. There is
no nice way to report such incidents. Nor is WHO a peacekeeper
or police officer; we could not stop it. What we could do was
blow the horn. This we did.<BR>

<P>


The <I>Pending health crisis bulletin</I> (issued from May to
September) provided NGOs and the international community with
critical data on disease outbreaks and war wounded, as well as
issues related to health and human rights.
<HR>

<H2>The fall of Srebrenica</H2>

<P>
During the fall of Srebrenica in June 1995, thousands of people
fled the city and set up camps in the Tuzla area of Bosnia and
Herzegovina. The threats to health were huge. Tents were scarce
and too hot. Clothing and bedclothes were filthy and sparse. Poorly
designed latrines were neither treated nor covered. Unchlorinated
drinking water and the lack of waste disposal made a dangerous
situation worse.
<P>
A preparedness plan drawn up by WHO was activated within hours.
The WHO field office in Tuzla set up a crisis centre in the camp
and appraised health conditions.
<P>
The centre provided logistical support for other organizations,
with a meeting place, communications services and temporary supply
depot. Here health coordination meetings were held twice daily
during the worst crises.
<P>
To serve the homeless thousands, WHO and local public health workers
developed evaluation forms used by all agencies during the emergency.
These allowed all concerned to get a true picture of conditions
as a basis for accurate reporting and referral. Important diseases
and health problems could now be rapidly sized up. Each agency
could offer special services in a networked effort.
<P>
With tasks geographically and technically divided, various groups
addressed urgent needs. Crisis coordination meetings revealed
gaps, and these were filled as fast as possible.
<HR>

<H3>Number of projects of the 91 international health agencies
in Bosnia AND Herzegovina (BiH) mid-1995</H3>

<TABLE BORDER=1>

