</TABLE>

<P>

<hr>
<H2>Krajina exodus</H2>
<img src="ar14.gif" align=right>

<P>
How well have all the many health agencies worked together? A
major test came in August 1995 when some 200 000 people from the
Krajina region fled into the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia
and Montenegro). Vital drugs and other aid were distributed to
these refugees through existing health structures. Their most
basic needs were met as the relevant agencies quickly divided
their tasks.
<P>
M&eacute;decins sans fronti&egrave;res (MSF), for example, set
up way station aid posts in Bosnia and Herzegovina. The Yugoslav
Red Cross and Institute of Public Health fielded mobile medical
teams. NGOs distributed medical supplies collected as a joint
operation.
<P>
The United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) undertook health assessment
among the expelled. And WHO sorted and distributed medical supplies
from the emergency airlift and chaired networking meetings every
second day to update the emergency response.
<P>
This extraordinary display of teamwork was limited only by a shortage
of medical supplies, owing to insufficient donor interest. So
refugee needs in some areas still remain unmet.
<HR>


<H2>Sanctions</H2>

<P>
The temptation to take sides can be enormous. But that is not
our business as health field workers. It is worth remembering,
too, that not all acts detrimental to public health are direct
consequences of war actions.
<P>

<P>
The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro), for
example, had sanctions imposed by the Security Council since May
1992. So WHO could provide only limited amounts of technical and
material assistance. Although medical supplies were specifically
exempt, in practice the sanctions created great difficulty in
purchasing and distributing humanitarian aid.
<P>
WHO field staff were always alert to the impact of sanctions on
public health. Basic medical equipment and supplies became less
available. The death rate mounted, especially in emergencies where
intensive care was needed. And in perinatal care, the death rate
shot up by 20% to 50%, depending upon the area and hospital.
<P>
Public health in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and
Montenegro) suffered as a direct consequence of the conflict and
the sanctions. WHO throughout the war intervened with the sanctions
committee whenever the supply of materials for health care was
delayed.
<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
