<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Public health</H1>

<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>
<H2>Keeping health services going</H2>

<P>
We are linkers. WHO connects and coordinates. But what do we do
at the grass-roots level in a land of carnage?
<P>
War disrupts systems for information, personnel, supply and deployment.
It strains and drains health services through war-related injuries,
communicable diseases, death and destruction.
<P>
Overcoming such obstacles takes courage, creativity, commitment
and persistence. Local doctors and nurses throughout the war have
worked without pay. Where health centres were destroyed, they
worked in makeshift premises. There was a constant shortage of
medical supplies.
<P>
Yet somehow, with international support, they kept the health
service going.


<img src="ar16.gif" align=left>
 

<H2>Six assistance targets</H2>

<P>
Experience showed that the local health services in Bosnia and
Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia
and Montenegro) needed help in several areas.
<P>
A broad, on-site health operation ought to have six primary assistance
targets. It should:
<OL>
<LI>monitor health, nutrition, food security, and environmental
conditions;
<LI>provide essential health supplies to meet health emergencies,
to prepare for cold weather and upsurges in fighting;
<LI>circulate information on priority health issues;
<LI>prevent and control epidemics of, for example, typhus, haemorrhagic
fever, tuberculosis, influenza, relapsing fever, meningitis, typhoid
fever, diphtheria, shigellosis, cholera and other diarrhoeal diseases;
<LI>develop skills and procedures that can be transferred to public
health care in peacetime; and
<LI>set priorities for system reconstruction and reform, and develop
options for the rebuilding process, including the role of key
public health institutions such as health ministries and polyclinics.
</OL>
<img src="ar17.gif" align=right>
<H2>War injuries</H2>

<P>
According to Bosnia and Herzegovina authorities, the death rate
directly due to war injuries in 1995 was 5.8 per 1000 inhabitants.
That is roughly
<P>
equal to the natural death rate (6.8 per 1000) in the same region.

<P>
War injuries posed a terrible public health threat throughout
the mission area. WHO supported vital emergency and rehabilitation
services with supplies and training.
<P>
About half of all supplies provided by WHO in 1995 went to clinics
and hospitals treating the war injured. The rest was used in public
health kits and customized kits for the treatment of communicable
diseases and for reproductive and mental health. Field offices
organized training on treating the physical and psychological
effects of war injuries.
<P>
The physical rehabilitation programme was expanded throughout
the mission area. Many more prosthetic devices were produced locally
in WHO-established orthopaedic workshops, subsidized by the Finnish
and Swedish governments. The needs of vulnerable groups such as
the chronically ill, children, elderly and soldiers coming home
were highlighted. Model communitybased programmes for rehabilitation
and mental health were established and expanded.
<HR>

<H2>Cluster bombing</H2>

<P>
In early May 1995, Zagreb was hit by cluster bombs, injuring hundreds
of civilians and killing some. Street scenes of the aftermath
were televized worldwide, telling their own story. WHO moved to
assist at hospitals caring for victims of the shelling. Among
those needing emergency aid was the Children's Hospital, which
had taken a direct hit. WHO shunted supplies to it to help ease
the burden.
<HR>

<H3>Ten leading communicable diseases in Bosnia and Herzegovina
in 1995</H3>

<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399></TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>Total number </CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Disease</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>of cases</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Influenza</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>28 790</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Enterocolitis</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>12 805</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Hepatitis A</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>3712</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Scabies</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>3411</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Varicella</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>2213</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Tuberculosis</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>1463</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Pharyngitis Strep.</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>464</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Haemorrhagic Fever </TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>422</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Meningitis</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>262</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=399>Tox. Alimentaria</TD><TD WIDTH=399><CENTER>228</CENTER>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<H2></H2>

<HR>

<H2>Outbreaks of communicable diseases</H2>

<P>
Common diseases are common everywhere. So it's part of our job
to say that, when you hear hoofbeats approaching, chances are
it&Otilde;s horses, not zebras. That is a common cold, we might
say, not tularaemia. WHO helped distinguish the common from the
exotic. We helped quell panic and arranged for scarce resources
to be put to the best use.<BR>

<P>
Last year, rumours circulated that one side was engaged in biological
warfare. WHO confirmed that a respiratory outbreak was caused
by nonvirulent microbes normally present in the environment, not
some exotic contagion. Social scientists set about calming the
edgy community.
<H2>Influenza</H2>

<P>
Influenza season hit rather late last year and rather hard, although
there were no more deaths than usual. The number of reported influenza
cases peaked in early March and the rate continued high into April.
<P>
WHO attempted to deliver flu vaccine to high-risk groups. But
this was stopped when it became apparent that the vaccine was
being diverted for military use.
<P>
More than 23,700 cases of flu were reported in Bosnia (excluding
Herzegovina) in 1995, as compared with 3,864 the year before.
Undoubtedly war influences reporting and statistics, but the total
was many times higher than in 1994.

<img src="ar18a.gif" align=right>

<H2>Tuberculosis</H2>

<P>
Since December 1993, WHO has directly supported tuberculosis (TB)
control in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro).
<P>
Accessible high-priority hospitals and general practitioners&Otilde;
surgeries were supplied with anti-TB drugs and prepackaged kits.
These TB kits encourage diagnosis by sputum analysis rather than
expensive X-ray. The recommended treatment regimens were shorter,
with fewer drugs, so there was better patient compliance.
<P>
Before the kits were delivered, TB workers were briefed on current
WHO recommendations for effective TB control. The TB control and
education programme is now in place, endorsed by field offices
and supported by workshops and visiting consultants.
<H2>Rat poison</H2>

<P>
When sanitation collapsed, the rat population soared. That led
to a sudden upswing in rodent-borne diseases, especially the highly
infectious haemorrhagic fever and tularaemia. To halt the contagion,
WHO tried to distribute rat poison.
<P>
But the project caused our logistics unit a lot of trouble. The
warring factions, fearing that the chemicals would be used by
their enemies, insisted upon multiple checks before issuing clearance
to enter their territories. We were hamstrung by legal red tape.

<P>
In the end, WHO&Otilde;s neutral image, cooperation with local
authorities, and a hand from sister agencies such as the Office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and
the United Kingdom Overseas Development Administration (ODA) allowed
us to set up a reliable supply chain. Rodenticides were delivered
to the neediest spots with the shortest possible delay.
<H2>Tularaemia</H2>

<P>
In late April 1995 three soldiers from Novitravnik in the Zenica
regional hospital were diagnosed with tularemia. Resembling plague,
this bacterial disease is transmitted from rats and other rodents
to humans by insect vectors or by handling infected animals. Lymph
glands are enlarged and the patient runs a high temperature. The
pneumonic form is highly contagious. Antibiotics are used in treatment.
<P>
The diagnoses were confirmed by bacterial cultures transported
by WHO to technicians at a lab in Zagreb. During May another 18
cases were confirmed in the Zenica region&ETH;13 from one municipality
and the others from various places. Over the same period, 47 others
were reported from the Tuzla area. There were allegedly more than
100 other cases around Banja Luka, but details could not be confirmed.
<P>
Fortunately there have been no tularaemia deaths. Response measures
included the distribution of rodent poisons and informing the
public about hygienic measures and possible sources of infection.
<H2>Haemorrhagic fevers</H2>

<P>
Viral haemorrhagic fevers are another story. These acute infections
cause high fever, internal bleeding and shock, and sometimes death.

<P>
Haemorrhagic fever was a real problem in the region. Between December
1994 and May 1995, more than 140 cases were
<P>
reported in the Tuzla area, with a few deaths and several sufferers
needing haemodialysis.
<P>
In Serb-held parts of Bosnia and Herzegovina, more than 80 cases
were reported in the first three months of 1995. Serb soldiers
in Banja Luka told of another one or two sufferers being evacuated
every day in that region during the same period.
<P>
Altogether 347 cases of Puumala and Hantaan haemorrhagic fevers
were documented in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1995. There were
confirmed reports from Croatia of 25 cases, mostly in the Rijeka
region, with 3 deaths.
<P>
In response, WHO assisted the local labs in diagnosis. Our field
offices distributed rodenticides to all regions in February.
<hr>

<H2>Lab assistance
</H2>The Bosnia and Herzegovina public health system by tradition is centralized. Remote clinics and physicians had to have communicable disease diagnoses confirmed in the central laboratories of Sarajevo before they could take action.
<P>
But with the city under siege for so long, this wasnt possible. By the time the answer came back, people could be dead.
<P>
Last year WHO took a direct hand in the action. While we couldnt stop the blockade, we could fly over it. When a haemorrhagic fever outbreak was suspected, and local authorities were unable to move promptly, WHO arranged for patient specimens to be flown by United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) to the Swedish Institute for Infectious Disease Control in Stockholm. Answers returned within 24 hours and responses were activated.<P>
In wartime, needs must drive actions. When the system was strained, WHO tried to adapt a flexible problem-solving approach. Flexibility focused on strengthening the skills of local health professionals. This will prove crucial in peacetime.

<HR>
<img src="ar19.gif" align=right>

<H2>Crimean Congo Haemorrhagic fever</H2>

<P>
Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever (CCHF) is found in Europe only
in Crim and Kosovo. Up to half the people who contract CCHF die
of it, so the strain is far more virulent than the Puumala and
Hantaan strains found in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia. Rodents
are among the wildlife hosts; ticks are the vectors. Traditional
preventive measures are not very effective. In April of 1995 the
disease broke out in Kosovo; several cases were detected. By July
the official number had increased to 60. The public health workers
in Kosovo asked for WHO&Otilde;s expertise in controlling the
contagion.
<P>
Our response was orchestrated at WHO headquarters. The Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in the United States prepared
an expert mission with free-of-charge drugs for all patients,
as well as scientific and technical partnership, for the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro).
<P>
Unfortunately, the burst of publicity over the outbreak created
problems with refugee relocation, and the Federal government canceled
the mission when the epidemic seemed to be receding naturally.
In the end there were 116 confirmed CCHF cases; 16 people died.

<H2>Water quality assurance</H2>

<P>
In the winter of 1995, during an intense period of the siege of
Sarajevo, drinking-water became polluted. WHO moved to import
and hand out chlorine tablets to households in some at-risk parts
of the city. Regrettably, other parts were totally inaccessible.

<P>
Health monitoring later revealed big differences in waterborne
diseases between the areas supplied with tablets and the others.
While it is a shame that all households could not be reached,
without a constant field presence and monitoring network, WHO
would not have been able to meet the urgent needs of those neighborhoods
that did get the water purification tablets.
<P>
From the very beginning, water quality has been a top issue. Ensuring
clean water sources to many parts of Bosnia and Herzegovina was
out of the question, so WHO distributed chlorine tablets and testing
kits to the most needy areas. Until safe water supplies can be
guaranteed, we will go on distributing the tablets.
<P>
The WHO European Centre for Environment and Health unit in Nancy,
France, is working with 60 towns in Bosnia and Herzegovina on
the development of water and sanitation systems.
<H2>Information for action</H2>

<P>
Accurate, updated information is as important to WHO as it is
to the military. Knowing exactly when to intervene for health
depends upon what&Otilde;s going on with health right now.
<P>
Perhaps war's greatest inconvenience for public health programmes
is the disruption of information collection. Skirmishes in Bosnia
and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
(Serbia and Montenegro) often severed communications with our
own offices and area health centres.
<P>
Even when the lines were open, the people there who were acting
as information gatherers had left for somewhere else, or were
otherwise occupied with the sick and wounded. Or the computers
and typewriters were broken, or the clinic was out of paper.
<P>
War zones may be impenetrable as a result of battle or just a
lack of fuel to get there.
<P>
Most frustrating, health data are often arbitrarily classified
by one side or the other as military secrets and therefore kept
from release. These are some of the obstacles that WHO met in
its monitoring work.

<img src="ar20.gif" align=right>


<H2>Reporting valuable data</H2>

<P>
In 1995 WHO field staff reinforced their ties with public health
authorities in the nations in conflict. In Mostar, Tuzla and Zenica,
our field offices held frequent meetings with authorities in their
region. Every month the authorities reported valuable information
to our satellite offices.
<P>
From the very beginning of the humanitarian assistance operation,
WHO has stressed the need to bolster national health reporting
systems, particularly for communicable and chronic disease surveillance.
In 1995 we provided 44 computers to the public health institutes
of Bosnia and Herzegovina, following up with training and more
supplies. This project showed immediate rewards and will yield
long-term benefits. An investment in existing systems, no matter
how disrupted, is an investment in their long-term stability.
<P>
In Sarajevo, staff of the WHO field office have met weekly since
1993 with the Bosnia and Herzegovina authorities. Last year, separate
weekly meetings were held with Sarajevo city officials.
<P>
There were ad hoc meetings with local authorities in Serb-controlled
sections of Sarajevo. And WHO field personnel from Belgrade, Sarajevo
and Zagreb all had contacts last year with the Republic agencies
of the Serbian entity of Bosnia and Herzegovina based in Banja
Luka.


<img src="ar21.gif" align=right>

<H2>Surveys</H2>

<P>
When the health information system could not provide enough data,
WHO stepped in to conduct community health surveys for a clearer
picture of conditions.
<P>
In 1995 we made a follow-up nutritional status survey, a poll
of public health in collective refugee shelters, and a study of
smoking among health professionals in Tuzla.
<H2>Public health in collective shelters </H2>

<P>
Mass population dislodgment was typical of 1995. Half the population
of Bosnia and Herzegovina was uprooted. The added number and size
of collective shelters for displaced persons meant extra attention
to their sanitary facilities. The field offices in Tuzla and Zenica
made detailed surveys of refugee health status in the region.

<P>
The data derived were used to formulate management action plans
to:
<UL>
<LI>conduct regular water testing;
<LI>improve sanitation by ensuring at least 1 toilet per 20 people;
<LI>organize outreach teams to provide adequate nursing and psychological
support;
<LI>dispense rodent control supplies;
<LI>furnish all refugee centres with at least one working rubbish
container;
<LI>donate flu vaccine to the elderly; and
<LI>distribute basic hygiene kits.
</UL>
<img src="ar22.gif" align=right>

<H2>Nutrition monitoring</H2>

<P>
In December 1994, WHO made nutrition and food security surveys
in Sarajevo, Tuzla and Zenica. Follow-ups were done in February
1995 to find out what had happened during the severe winter of
1994/1995 and to identify special groups at risk.
<H2>Nutrition survey findings</H2>

<P>
Overall, the nutritional status of children, adults and the elderly
remained fairly satisfactory during the winter of 1994/1995. In
fact, compared to the winter before, younger and older adults
were better nourished:
<UL>
<LI>chronic disease was the most commonly reported cause of illness,
especially in the elderly;
<LI>household food stocks were 2 &ETH; 4 times greater in February
1995 than in February 1994;
<LI>food prices dropped dramatically over the same period;
<LI>food aid distribution improved;
<LI>obesity is an increasing problem;
<LI>in the brief interval between December 1994 and February 1995,
access to heating, electricity and water improved; and
<LI>the majority of households in Sarajevo and Zenica had received
water purification tablets by February 1995.
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<HR>
<img src="ar23.gif" align=right>

<H2>Health on the road</H2>

<P>
On 7 August 1995, a group of some 25,000 followers of the businessman
Fikret Abdic fled from Velika Kladusa in the Bihac pocket of Bosnia
and Herzegovina and headed towards Croatia. Seeking asylum, they
crossed the border but were not permitted to proceed beyond a
valley about 17 km north of Velika Kladusa. Unable to go ahead
and afraid to turn back, they set up camp on the spot with what
little they had.
<P>
A few farmhouses in the valley were quickly occupied. Other, less
fortunate people turned to cars, trucks and shelters made of branches,
leaves and corn stalks. The entire 5-km stretch of valley was
packed with people, since most opted to stay close to the road
for security. Conditions quickly deteriorated as people defecated
on the nearby ground, and water sources were polluted.
<P>
As soon as humanitarian agencies were allowed into the camp, the
top priorities were food, water, shelter and sanitation. The aid
mission needed coordination both in the field and in Zagreb to
ensure an optimal response from all parties involved. WHO took
the lead through conferences with NGOs, local refugee workers
and the Croatian health authorities.
<P>
Progress in water purification and basic sanitation was slow and
difficult. Pit latrines dug in the valley flooded over as soon
as the rains came, leaving stretches of the valley like open sewers.
The only stream was heavily contaminated, as were the few wells.
One or two springs were safe for drinking.
<P>
Not surprisingly, the potential for diarrhoeal diseases to spread
like wildfire was great. But outbreaks of shigellosis, dysentery
and hepatitis A were quickly spotted and controlled by water treatment.
<P>
Many young refugees in the camp were wounded during the years
of fighting. In the camp clinic there were 11 paraplegics and
7 hemiplegics plus many amputees and others with external bone
fixators to stabilize fractures. WHO&Otilde;s rehabilitation team
took stock of the situation and started basic training for paramedics
who could do on-site primary physical rehabilitation.
<P>
Two paramedics already involved in the care of this group were
given rehabilitation training. Basic equipment for limb mobilization
and physiotherapy kits helped with exercise
<P>
training.
<P>
WHO also worked behind the scenes, lobbying for improvement in
access to hospital care. When this did not happen, efforts were
made to improve conditions in the Kupljensko camp.
<P>
Today the camp is still there, though the number of occupants
has dropped from the initial 25,000 to about 6,000. Women, children
and the elderly were the first to leave and return to Velika Kladusa
as winter came.The Pending health crisis bulletin (issued from
May to September) provided NGOs and the international community
with critical data on disease outbreaks and war wounded, as well
as issues related to health and human rights.


<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
