<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Into the fray <BR>with supplies</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>

<H2>Beyond advice</H2>

<P>
Delivering the right supplies to the right people at the right
place at the right time is one of the cornerstones of humanitarian
aid. WHO's ability to coordinate, deliver directly, and
fill gaps in supply needs enhanced the effectiveness of all public
health programmes during the war.
<P>
When the health care system in Bosnia and Herzegovina collapsed,
one of the worst results was the cut-off of supplies to hospitals
and clinics. That is where outside humanitarian aid counted. What
happened, however, was that well meaning groups sent in many of
the wrong medical supplies, glutting storage depots and actually
doing more harm than good.
<P>
Too many donations were damaged by poor packing, or comprised
mixed or unlabelled medication, expired drugs, and the like. Handling
such donations consumed the resources of humanitarian agencies
and professionals who were working in the field under difficult
and dangerous conditions.
<P>
WHO therefore went all out to coordinate supply activities. It
wasn't easy. WHO still chairs regular coordination conferences
on drug distribution in each field office. Local health authorities
and the humanitarian organizations concerned take an active part.
Priorities are set and drug supply plans laid for each agency
involved.

<img src="ar24.gif" align=left>

<H2>Setting donor guidelines</H2>

<P>
The chaotic supply situation was corrected by donor guidelines
and an essential drug list drawn up by WHO. The guidelines ex-plain
supply procedures and offer simple suggestions for making donations
useful, easy and safe to handle.
<P>
Implementation of WHO's essential drugs policy has led
to a supply of high-quality medicines at affordable prices.
<H2>Mostar and Sarajevo: cases in point</H2>

<P>
In Sarajevo, WHO's donor guidelines have been rigorously
followed since the initiation of the airlift. UNHCR refused to
transport medical supplies that did not comply with our guidelines.
The result has been an efficient delivery of supplies with few
unusable leftovers.
<P>
In Mostar, the situation was reversed. Lack of any policy for
donations, plus multiple supply channels, led to random deliveries
to end-user hospitals, which were ill prepared to receive the
aid. Management of drug supply and storage, logistics and monitoring
was haphazard. The result: stockpiling of some 300 tons of unusable
drugs, many outdated, created critical shortages of space for
essential medicines.
<P>
Today, the Mostar situation is being corrected. Along with Pharmaciens
sans fronti&egrave;res (PSF), WHO has set up a programme to bring
order out of chaos. It is funded by the European Union Administration
of Mostar (EUAM).
<P>
Procurement, storage, distribution, use and disposal are the main
aims. Key storehouses have been renovated, the drug manual updated,
computerized stock monitoring installed, and personnel trained
with the help of local health authorities.

<img src="ar25.gif" align=right>

<H2>WHO kits: meeting the needs of many</H2>

<P>
During 1995, WHO supplies continued to take a "kit approach".
Kits are prepackaged boxes of basic instruments and drugs. They
contain all that's needed for a defined patient population
over a set period of time.
<P>
Some, such as the emergency health kit, the surgical kit and anaesthetic
kit, were designed to meet the needs of the civil population in
this war. The kits helped health workers cope with local supply
problems. 1995 saw several improvements in the kit programme.
Instruction manuals were developed. Training courses on the use
of the kits were expanded. The kit approach was successful. It
is becoming the standard way to deal with humanitarian emergencies
anywhere in the world.
<img src="ar26.gif" align=right>

<H3>WHO kits for public health include:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>chronic disease kit
<LI>clinical chemical laboratory kit
<LI>clinical microbiological laboratory kit
<LI>epidemic response kit
<LI>general practitioner kit
<LI>hygiene kit
<LI>insulin kit
<LI>mental health kit
<LI>new emergency kit
<LI>pneumonia kit
<LI>reproductive health kit
<LI>tuberculosis kit
<LI>vitamin kit.
</UL>

<H3>WHO kits for war injuries include:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>anaesthetic kit;
<LI>anaesthetic supplementary kit;
<LI>bandage supplementary kit;
<LI>clean intermittent catheterization kit;
<LI>major rehabilitation equipment kit;
<LI>parenteral fluids (IV fluids) kit;
<LI>physiotherapy kit;
<LI>splint kit;
<LI>splint tool kit;
<LI>surgical kit;
<LI>transfusion kit.
</UL>

<P>
Ironically, the most popular pack of all contains no medicine.
The hygiene kit holds basic supplies such as soap, toothpaste
and brushes, toilet paper and the like. WHO supplied this kit
in response to a largely unrecognized demand. Not many agencies
were willing to donate such simple items, since they were not
considered to be medical or emergency supplies. Yet WHO decided
to send in the hygiene kits because the items inside were indeed
essential to the basic public health needs of the population.
<H2>Filling the gaps</H2>

<P>
Blood supplies augmented the kits, and our field officers identified
the various needs of traumatized populations. In the days of the
heaviest siege of Sarajevo, when the army of Bosnia and Herzegovina
tried unsuccessfully to raise the siege, we delivered bulk quantities
of water purification tablets; clean drinking-water was a top
priority.
<P>
WHO was recognized as the major, if not the only, health supply
provider in some parts of the mission region. Our reputation as
a fair and neutral agency often helped us gain access to people.
Delivering kits designed by Denmark, we are the sole regular providers
of disposable laboratory materials and anti-TB drugs.
<H2>Spare parts for hospitals</H2>

<P>
Direct shelling, power failures and general aging added to the
degeneration of a great deal of hospital equipment, handicapping
local health workers. After a WHO consultant was assigned to survey
the situation, specific pieces of equipment were
<P>
ordered for delivery to specified hospitals and clinics.
<P>
Once again, the nonconsumable nature of these shipments caused
delivery problems. Once again, the trouble, as the warring factions
saw it, was that these were not medical supplies, so they fell
under different regulations.
<P>
Authorities were suspicious of the destination of this hardware.
The amount and cost of items such as computers and paper understandably
provoked suspicions.
<P>
The very specific health destination of every single item called
for extraordinary precision in the delivery process, placing far
more strain than usual on our Logistics Unit.
<P>
Finally, after lengthy negotiation and perseverance, WHO managed
to deliver all the goods to all the appropriate institutions.
And, again, we could not have done it alone. Our reputation and
cooperation with other agencies were crucial in getting the supplies
into the right hands.
<H2>Child immunization</H2>

<P>
WHO experts tagged measles- mumps-rubella vaccines as a top health
priority item in 1995. We provided these vaccines to the entire
mission region, immunizing children in a joint project with UNICEF,
the International Medical Group (an NGO) and local doctors.

<img src="ar28.gif" align=left>

<H2>Logistics</H2>

<P>
During the war, WHO built up a small but effective distribution
apparatus. A Bedford truck and several four-wheel-drive vans and
armored vehicles speeded the delivery of medical and related supplies.

<P>
Shifts in the war influenced WHO's logistical operations.
Constant access to besieged Sarajevo was ensured by the WHO presence
in Ancona: the hub of the UNHCR airlift operation, the longest
airlift in history.
<P>
We opened our logistics office in Ancona in January 1995. The
unit went right to work, doing a good job of supplying Sarajevo.
<P>
Unfortunately, the threats and attacks of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), the Serbian offensive in the east and the
unsuccessful counteroffensive in Sarajevo halted the airlift for
much of the time. That disrupted our ability to deliver the vital
goods. But working closely with UNHCR, UNPROFOR and other agencies
put us in a position to resume our mission the moment the airlift
resumed.
<P>
Besides curtailing the supplies allowed in, the war activities
and sanctions made it very difficult to obtain fuel and vehicle
spare parts. That led to a shortage of transport.
<H2>Changes in 1995</H2>

<P>
Important data had to be made more visible. So the WHO logistics
and medical supply units asked suppliers to list batch numbers
and expiry dates on the front of each of the packed boxes.
<P>
During the second quarter of 1995, UNHCR decided to move its major
supply point from Split to Metkovic, a small town in the Neretva
delta of Croatia. WHO followed and opened a supply centre in Metkovic.

<P>
<img src="ar29.gif" align=right>

Our facilities and workers were moved to a new location in the
Razvitak warehouse complex, providing crucial access to the UNHCR
supply chain.
<P>
The presence of our people in Metkovic enabled us to cope with
the ever-changing customs regulations of local authorities. WHO
has maintained good relations with health officials throughout
the mission area, allowing us to move our shipments quickly and
effectively.
<HR>
<img src="ar27.gif" align=left border=5>

<H2>Emergency bloodlift: responding to crisis</H2>

<P>
One shining example last year of WHO supply efforts was the delivery
of more than 800 units of blood, flown in from Scotland to Sarajevo
hospitals.
<P>
Intensive shelling of Sarajevo stopped routine WHO blood supply
airlifts in April. The need for externally supplied blood became
critical in June and July. The donor public was suffering increased
anaemia. Local Sarajevo blood centres could not fill the need.
<P>
The Sarajevo office organized an emergency airlift of blood, brought
by Royal Air Force (RAF) aircraft from the United Kingdom into
Split, Croatia. ODA financed the coordination of a special appeal
to Scottish and English transfusion centres. They responded generously
and quickly.
<P>
RAF planes brought in the blood. WHO field staff arranged for
refrigerated van transport to Metkovic, where the blood was held
overnight. Sarajevo field staff drove two vehicles across Mt Igman
to pick it up. They came under fire on the way out, but returned
without incident. In Sarajevo the blood was used to save lives
after the August market-place massacre.
<P>
Such speedy delivery allows no room for error. Three years of
experience in the region have proved the WHO supply chain to be
smooth and dependable.
<P>
WHO cannot do it alone. Particularly in transport, UNHCR and ODA
have been notable partners. Excellent cooperation with the ODA
convoy team continued throughout 1995. Large parts of the Metkovic
warehouse supply were moved in by the ODA team, which also handled
some field distribution. ODA has also most generously serviced
WHO vehicles without charge at its depots.
<hr>





<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
