<HTML>

<HEAD>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Capacity building</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>

<P>
How can war-related humanitarian aid bolster local capacities
to deal with the added health burdens of war?
<P>
<img src="ar29.gif" align=left border=5>

War demands different health interventions for which technical
skills are not readily available. No country in the world has
a health system adequately pre-pared for war. Even highly skilled
and educated workers are simply overwhelmed by the massive problems
of armed conflict.
<P>
Resources are strained to the breaking point. Working conditions
are abominable. The needs of entire populations exceed the capabilities
of even a fully func-tioning health care system. In addition to
the enormous burden on health services, health workers themselves
must survive the carnage. They suffer the same traumas as everyone
else, plus the daily tragedies of their patients.
<P>
Continuous education for health professionals is a prerequisite
for dealing with unforeseen emergencies and to provide moral and
psychological support.
<P>
Through field offices and external consultants, WHO has held seminars
and sponsored other programmes for the continuing education of
health professionals and auxiliaries in many areas.

<img src="ar31.gif" align=right>

<H2>Physical rehabilitation</H2>

<P>
WHO's project for the rehabilitation of war victims aims
to help people with physical disabilities regain their sense of
personal dignity. It works for the restoration of optimal health,
self-support, ability realization and social integration.
<P>
The strategy is to work through health ministries and draw upon
existing health care resources. This entails working hand in hand
with the local community and health professionals.
<P>
The project has focused on people with the most severe disabilities
- amputations, spinal cord injuries and traumatic brain injuries - who
account for more than 20% of all disabled war victims in need
of rehabilitation.
<P>
The magnitude of these rehabilitation needs is very large. As
a rule there would be beds enough at existing centres if standard
patient discharge procedures were followed. But many of these
places are overcrowded because they are unable to discharge disabled
persons into society. Normal social and family support networks
have broken down.
<P>
So new rehabilitation approaches are needed, as well as more modern
equipment and better trained personnel. The approaches should
support and motivate communities to accept and integrate these
people. They should teach professionals new ways to provide care
and de-emphasize care in institutions.
<H2>Regional rehabilitation model</H2>

<P>
WHO introduced community-based rehabilitation (CBR) as the primary
model. CBR is a strategy for physical reconditioning and social
reintegration of physically challenged people into their communities.
A combined biological, psychological and social approach encourages
effective and efficient rehabilitation.
<P>
In addition to providing muchneeded rehabilitation assistance,
this project fosters community participation in the structure
and functioning of the CBR centre, so the international support
may be phased out after the first year of operation.
<P>
In 1995, WHO's physical rehabilitation unit developed a
regional model (see box p. 33) around community-based principles
and the United Nations standard rules for people with disabilities.
The CBR regional model is being applied in Mostar and Bihac, and
is planned in Tuzla, Zenica, Sarajevo, Banja Luka, western Vojvodina,
Eastern Slavonia and Zagreb.
<P>
WHO devised rehabilitation teaching packets, distributing them
last year to all our field offices and to rehabilitation centres
and relevant NGOs. The packets include patient information and
self-care materials, assessment forms, home exercises and selected
scientific articles. All documents were translated into local
languages.

<img src="ar32.gif" align=right>

<H2>Prosthesis production and supply</H2>

<P>
Prostheses are needed everywhere in the region and will be needed
for many years to come. The current capacity for local production
is far below current needs.
<P>
Thousands of amputees are on the waiting lists and the backlog
will grow as temporary prostheses wear out and as land mines continue
to do their inevitable damage to this war-torn region.
<P>
In WHO's physical rehabilitation project, kits have been particularly
useful. WHO designed and distributed several kinds of these kits
throughout the region, including:
<UL>
<LI>a major rehabilitation kit containing essential items for
assessment and exercise therapy for field rehabilitation clinics;
<LI>a physiotherapy kit with minor equipment for assessment and
therapy;
<LI>a splint kit with thermoplastic materials for hand and foot
splinting for patients with brain and peripheral nerve injuries;
and
<LI>a splint tool kit for fabrication of splints.
</UL>
<img src="ar33.gif" align=right>

<P>
Even so, field kits will not meet future demands. Accordingly,
a major part of the rehabilitation project has been to prepare

<P>
communities in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia to meet local
demands with local resources.
<P>
WHO, in collaboration with the Finnish Red Cross, installed machines
for making permanent prostheses last year in Splitske Toplice
and Topusko. A local team, under the guidance of a WHO orthopaedic
engineer, has already started production. Two international consultants
surpervised the prosthesis fitting, manufacturing and procurement.
<P>
In Splitske Toplice, 87 amputees were fitted with a permanent
lower limb prosthese and 41 with temporary devices. A WHO mobile
team supplied patients in their home cities. We also delivered
material to manufacture 250 training and permanent lower limb
prostheses to the Bihac Regional Prosthesis Workshop.
<P>
In November 1995, WHO established an orthopaedic workshop at the
Velmos hospital in East Mostar. Devices will be produced for an
estimated 800 amputees on both sides of the city and the entire
surrounding region. Two local technicians were recruited; one
was a shoemaker and the other, a carpenter before joining WHO.
Today these men produce lower limb prostheses under supervision
of a WHO consultant from Splitske Toplice.

<img src="ar34.gif" align=right>

<H2>Psychosocial rehabilitation: Meeting today's needs, building
for tomorrow</H2>

<P>
War scars people. Entire populations face a massive threat to
their mental health. The shock to the population has many repercussions
for individuals, families and society as a whole. Disorders related
to traumatic stress emerge. Normal people begin to suffer from
anxiety, depression, nightmares, flashbacks and severe mood and
attention difficulties. These can occur immediately or be delayed
for months or even years. New traumas can provoke the return of
old symptoms.
<P>
An immediate clue to this in the mission region has been the tremendous
increase in people seeking help from mental health services for
trauma-related disorders.
<P>
Reports from local and international aid workers confirm a sharp
increases in substance abuse, suicide and homicide, and other
problems.
<P>
WHO has already published figures indicating that over 1 million
people in the mission area were in urgent need of psychological
help. The continued fighting right up to the peace agreement,
the severe human rights abuses, and the masses of homeless people
on the move may well have pushed up these estimates.
<P>
Current helping capacity is
<P>
estimated to cover only 1&ETH;2% of needs. The factors that aid
in recovery from traumatic experiences, especially caring support
from families and social institutions, are completely disrupted.
<P>
To help meet this urgent demand, WHO has continued applying a
system of regional models for mental health.
<P>
Mental health regional models have so far been applied in Mostar,
Sarajevo and Tuzla (Bosnia and Herzegovina), Kotor (Montenegro,
in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia) and Split (Croatia).
<H2>Local professionals lead</H2>

<P>
Local professionals are carrying out the different elements of
the regional models. Their work is supported by international
teachers and up-to-date educational materials. A basic book, <I>Trauma
and healing under war conditions</I>, is being translated.
<P>
Training programmes for mental health and primary care health
workers have focused on war-related trauma and their sequelae.
Two hundred professionals are participating in unique post-trauma
therapy (PTT) training programmes.
<P>
These PTT programmes are one-year postgraduate courses for psychologists
and psychiarists. They combine training with space for self-care.
They provide support for professionals confronting both their
private traumas and the traumas of their patients. PTT is the
first systematic training programme of its kind in the world.
<P>
Training is also being provided in conjunction with UNICEF, and
MSF (Holland) for general practitioners, psychological aides and
social workers.
<H2>Meeting the needs</H2>

<P>
In 1995, WHO continued to provide crucial mental health supplies
of all kinds in kits. The kits for mental hospitals contain enough
key psychopharmacological drugs and medical essentials to treat
50 psychiatric inpatients a month.
<P>
In 1995 we distributed 373 kits in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia
and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro).
<H2>Next steps</H2>

<P>
Model community-oriented mental health centres will be developed
within each regional model area. WHO plans to assist the efforts
of local NGOs, specializing in psychosocial programmes to introduce
more social and occupational activities into existing mental health
systems.
<HR>

<H2>Mostar Kayak Club</H2>

<P>
A model CBR centre was completed in Eastern Mostar at the end
of 1995 (official opening on 1 February 1996). This project has
been the result of a dynamic collaboration between the Regional
Medical Centre (RMC) of Mostar, EUAM, and WHO. The Mostar Kayak
Club was reconstructed by EUAM and now houses the Mostar CBR centre,
which will be used by the RMC free of charge for the next five
years. WHO provided rehabilitation equipment and extensive training
for local health professionals.
<HR>

<H2>Regional models</H2>

<P>
The regional model approach is a coordinated set of health activities
for a defined geographic area with a population of 300 000-400
000. These models are being applied in WHO projects for both mental
health and physical rehabilitation.
<P>
A model works as follows.
<OL>
<LI>WHO staff bring together all relevant IGOs, NGOs, national
authorities and professionals serving the targeted region. This
group develops a strategic action plan.
<LI>Needs and resources are assessed.
<LI>Training is provided for health professionals in community-oriented
approaches.
<LI>Model projects are initiated.
<LI>Projects are supplied with appropriate kits and other equipment
and supplies.
<LI>Linkages are established between local, regional and international
activities.
</OL>

<P>

<HR>
<img src="ar35.gif" align=left>

<H2>Advocacy and human rights</H2>

<P>
The human rights concept and recovery after traumatization are
linked in many ways. To put this message across, WHO produced
teaching material for public use. <I>Every day is a human rights
day</I> points up these connections.
<P>
The United Nations Declaration on Human Rights has been signed
by nations all over the world. Respect for human rights is also
part of everyday life for all human beings. In peace time, under
democratic conditions, most people take their human rights for
granted. Human rights are integrated in society as part of culture
and behaviour. Under war conditions human rights are often violated.
It may happen systematically, on purpose on the collective level.
It may also happen more occasionally on the individual level.
Violations may be carried out by the enemy or by one&Otilde;s
own compatriots. Violations may be carried out by one&Otilde;s
neighbours or by oneself. The human rights perspective condemns
all violations, no matter who the violators are. It is a universal
ethical and moral stand.
<P>
All WHO psychosocial seminars emphasize the relationship between
mental health and the need to respect human rights. <BR>
<BR>

<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 30 August 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>

