<HTML>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Crossing over</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
</center>

<img src="ar37.gif" align=left border=5>

<P>
How can WHO activities shift from short-term humanitarian assistance
to a long-term focus on development?
<P>
With the signing of the Dayton peace agreement, Bosnia and Herzegovina,
Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)
now face the challenges of making a stable peace. What the actors
do in this transition period will determine what the future holds
for their countries.
<P>
If humanitarian aid is not linked to rehabilitation and recovery
programmes, peace will be threatened.
<P>
WHO humanitarian assistance is at the root of health rehabilitation.
We have taken the lead in health reform and are applying the lessons
of nearly four years of emergency relief to the reconstruction
process.
<P>
Humanitarian assistance in the war has always been aimed at providing
emergency relief while preparing for peace through capacity building,
planning and working with national health authorities, and coordinating
with partner organizations.
<P>
Several projects were started last year aimed at smoothing the
transition to peace. The Mostar mental health seminars and the
restoration of essential services in Sarajevo are prime examples
of the cross-over from emergency aid to a sustainable health system.
<H2>Mostar: the neediest of cities</H2>

<P>
Mostar is a particularly sad testament to the war. At different
times all three factions in Bosnia and Herzegovina were fighting
in this area. Clashes between them from 1992 through 1994 simply
destroyed the city. Today it remains fragmented along ethnic lines.
<P>
In 1995, WHO arranged 33 gatherings and training sessions with
health professionals of both East and West Mostar; 9 dealt with
general public health, 14 with drugs and supply, and 10 with mental
health.
<P>
As part of the drug supply management project in Mostar, we arranged
for the exchange of substantial quantities of drugs, of which
there was a surplus on one side of town and a shortage on the
other.
<P>
The mental health seminars held in Mostar and in Sarajevo helped
bring war-separated doctors back together. After getting an exceptional
clearance from their respective sides in January, the delegates
arrived in white United Nations cars at the Hotel Ero in Mostar.

<P>
For the first time in more than two years, they sat down in the
same room and talked.
<P>
At the end of the first work session, one doctor turned to a colleague
across the table and summed up the feeling in the room. &quot;We
did not like what your people did to us during the war,&quot;
he said, &quot;but at least we understand now that it was not
you, our colleagues, who were shooting at us. You were trying
to take care of those in need, as we did.&quot;

<img src="ar38.gif" align=left>

<H2>Restoring essential services</H2>

<P>
The health structure in Bosnia and Herzegovina, especially in
Sarajevo, mostly collapsed. Many hospitals were leveled, while
building damage and equipment failure put others out of action.
Throughout the war, primary care centres have been the main source
of formal help for most people.
<P>
The Japanese government donated funds for the Sarajevo field office
to repair general practitioners' surgeries in all parts of the
city. These so-called ambulantas provide primary care services.
More than 50 of them had been destroyed beyond repair.
<P>
Working with the Office of the United Nations Special Coordinator
for Sarajevo, WHO used local building contractors to make urgent
repairs to 27 ambulantas. More will be restored in the coming
months.

<img src="ar39.gif" align=right>

<H2>Can WHO help stop war?</H2>

<P>
Health is a key element of the peace process. But can health help
stop war? WHO believes that health workers can contribute in important
ways.
<P>
The nearly four-year war has separated many health professionals
who were once colleagues. Disease leaps geopolitical borders.
Throughout 1995, WHO supported the political peace process through
bringing health workers together to discuss mutual problems and
develop joint actions.
<P>
Health workers tend to be open-minded, sharing a common sense
of humanity and responsibility for the sick and injured. With
a little bit of help, therefore, these people can be instrumental
leaders in the reconciliation process.
<P>
Without joint efforts, there are no effective interventions. Rodent
control is a good example. It makes no sense to lay rat control
plans in one part of a city and not in another.
<P>
Through several initiatives, WHO has been building a bridge for
humanitarian assistance in health and peace.
<H2>Airport meetings</H2>

<P>
In 1995, we organized and chaired four epidemiological meetings
at Sarajevo airport, attended by both Bosnia and Herzegovina government
and Bosnian Serb delegates. The meetings addressed communicable
disease epidemiology and rodent control for the greater Sarajevo
area.
<P>
Owing to the meetings' sensitive nature, minutes were not taken.
Instead, short points in management action plans were listed at
the end of each meeting. Unfortunately, even these elementary
planning sessions were halted during the intensive shelling of
Sarajevo in the spring and summer of 1995.
<P>
Starting in 1994, WHO and the Norwegion Medical Association have
brought together medical society representatives of the warring
parties several times.
<P>
The medical society representatives agreed to lobby their respective
governments for the free flow of humanitarian aid, freedom to
treat each other's patients in hospital, and the protection
of health facilities and workers. It is hard to judge the practical
effects of these initiatives. Since these meetings started, however,
there seem to have been fewer attacks on hospitals. Where WHO
was once criticized by the warring parties for working on all
sides, collaboration with WHO is now accepted by all.<BR>
<BR>

<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 30 August 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>

