<HTML>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>After the crisis</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>

<img src="ar41.gif">
</center>
<P>
The WHO presence in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) has led to more
knowledge about the health of war-torn populations and the needs
of health services in relation to resources. This knowledge has
been put to good use by all concerned. But what happens now?
<P>
In 1996 and beyond, we are stressing the importance of linking
relief to rehabilitation. The WHO field offices will continue
to provide emergency relief while advising on health care system
reform. Our aim is to ensure higher health standards while local
authorities resume responsibility for health and reduce the need
for relief aid.
<H2>Bosnia and Herzegovina </H2>

<P>
Responding to the overwhelming urgency in Bosnia and Herzegovina,
we are assisting the health ministries there in laying a long-term
reconstruction strategy while spotting and meeting short-term
needs. An effective management mechanism and coordination structure
are indispensable to that strategy.
<P>
This calls for intensive management training for key policy-makers
and managers, a health care development strategy, a physical infrastructure
plan, and physical and mental health rehabilitation programmes.
<H2>Moving towards health for all</H2>

<P>
WHO is engaged on several fronts in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
<P>
Policy planning. Consistent with a well established pattern of
assistance to Member States, WHO will continue to support health
authorities on all levels in developing action plans that foster
a long-term vision while addressing short-term needs. This work
extends to policies in high-priority areas transcending national
boundaries, such as rehabilitation, pharmaceuticals, immunization,
and the environment.
<P>
Needs assessment. Drawing on our network of field offices and
Coordinating and Reference Centres, and our contacts with experts
worldwide, we will work with the republic and regional institutes
of public health to evaluate current health
status and services.
<P>
Technical assistance. WHO staff and outside consultants will offer
continuing technical assistance in areas ranging from communicable
diseases, nutrition, woman and child health, mental health and
rehabilitation to basic infrastructure issues such as public health
engineering, hospital and other facility design and management,
and medical supplies and equipment.
<P>
Training. Given the acute need for training health professionals,
skill building in many specialties and managing reform and reconstruction
strategy,
<P>
WHO is drawing heavily on its experience in capacity building courses (for example,
within the regional models for mental health and physical rehabilitation).
<P>
Project development. Support for the reform and reconstruction
effort in Bosnia and Herzegovina calls for extraordinary efforts
in all areas and contributions by many donors. WHO will help develop
projects targeted to urgent needs. WHO will run selected projects
in areas of its special expertise, in consultation with the health
ministries, regional and local professionals, and other international
agencies.
<P>
Programme coordination. WHO will continue to encourage information
sharing among domestic and international bodies by organizing
seminars and workshops and circulating a regular update on health
reform and reconstruction to key people throughout Bosnia and
Herzegovina.
<P>
Field presence. A special strength of WHO&Otilde;s field presence
has been the ability of satellite staff to help national and outside
workers tackle problems as they arise. This on-site response capability
will be especially helpful in addressing health reconstruction
issues.
<H2>Croatia</H2>

<P>
As the transition to peace picked up momentum, WHO took part in
a technical fact-finding mission to Croatia organized by the United
Nations Development Programme (UNDP). The team assessed the extent
of war damage in Croatia and its consequences down the line.
<P>
Needs were evaluated in order to assist the Croatian government
to draw up plans for rehabilitation and renewal. Sites were visited
in a number of areas designated by the government. Assistance
was needed for 60,000 refugees and displaced persons, especially
in Eastern Slavonia.
<P>
One third of hospitals and health centres in Croatia were destroyed
during the war and need rebuilding.
<H2>Eastern Slavonia</H2>

<P>
Eastern Slavonia will be supported by the opening of a WHO field
office in Erdut/Osijek. Since we will be working closely with
the United Nations Transitional Administration for Eastern Slavonia
(UNTAES), our office will be located near UNTAES headquarters.

<P>
The WHO Special Representative for Croatia will be charged with
bringing both sides together to discuss issues of joint concern
and action planning. An international field officer has been appointed
to cover Eastern Slavonia. Her assignment is to oversee planning and gauge health
needs together with both Croat and Serb professonials.

<img src="ar42.gif" align=right>

<H2>Ten health commissions</H2>


Since 1994, WHO has assigned a senior public health advisor to
the Croatian health minister to assist in health system and reconstruction
planning. The master plan for Croatia is an extension of the WHO
strategy for health for all by the year 2000. The plan implementing
that scheme calls for the formation of 10 commissions on:
<UL>
<LI>primary care;
<LI>basic hospital services;
<LI>health promotion;
<LI>emergency medical services;
<LI>quality of health care assessment;
<LI>rehabilitation of war victims;
<LI>capital investment in health;
<LI>health information systems;
<LI>human resources development;
<LI>a national environment and health action plan.
</UL>


The first draft of the master plan was completed in December 1995.
Translated into English, it has been submitted to WHO and other
international bodies for comment. The WHO Liaison Office coordinates
the ten commissions and handles liaison with the WHO Regional
Office for Europe in Copenhagen and WHO headquarters in Geneva.
<H2>Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)</H2>

<P>
Although not directly damaged by the war, the health care system
of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)
is also in transition and in need of substantial outside assistance.
Economic stability will not come overnight; neither will the passage
from political isolation to international interaction.
<P>
The shift is coupled with culturally challenging demographic change,
including the repatriation or integration of as many as 600 000-700
000 refugees and expelled people into society.
<P>
Before the war, the former Yugoslavia was an active Member State
of WHO. Many WHO European health programmes have continued to
operate within the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and
Montenegro), despite limited interaction with WHO.
<P>
Whenever the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)
obtains membership in WHO this will help re-establish or strengthen
work for health promoting schools, Healthy Cities projects, accident
prevention and other programmes.
<P>
WHO will continue to provide humanitarian assistance within the
constraints imposed by Member States and donor interest. Efforts
will be made to reintegrate health professionals of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) into networks with
their European colleagues.
<P>
Joint conferences of the medical associations of Bosnia and Herzegovina,
Croatia, Slovenia, The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia and
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro) will
continue to be arranged by the Norwegian Medical Association and
WHO.
<P>
Other priorities include control of communicable diseases, polio
eradication, immunization programmes, national drug policy, mental
health and rehabilitation, as well as health policy and health
care reform.


<hr>
