<HTML>

<title>Annual Report 1995</title>
<body background="../../cbcbg01.gif">
<p>
<img src="../techhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../../Welcome.htm"><img src="../../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="../tech.htm"><img src="../../nextknap.gif"></A>

<img src="ar01.gif" border=5 align=left>
<center>

<H1>Sharing the vision</H1>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
<img src="ar43.gif">
</center>

<P>
This report is directed to the people who have supported and worked
with WHO in 1995: national governments, international agencies,
NGOs, businesses and private citizens. Your belief in what we
are doing to help the victims of this war is important to us.
Your support provides the means for WHO to do the job we were
set up to do.
<P>
Nearly four years of non-partisan work on and behind the lines
of these battlefields have helped us understand, once again, the
vital importance of linking international knowledge to local events.
<H2>Links save lives</H2>

<P>
This kind of linkage has saved lives and cut suffering in Bosnia
and Herzegovina, Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
(Serbia and Montenegro).
<P>
WHO-coordinated assistance helped local authorities maintain vital
services, improve care for those with war injuries, and continue
to care for all people, especially those at greatest risk.
<P>
WHO staff in our network of field offices helped ensure that hygiene
and medical supplies went where they should go. Supply gaps were
filled with less and less overlap. Health and nutritional status
was monitored and quick interventions were made whenever serious
threats to public health arose.
<P>
The best testimony to this approach has been not only what happened
but also what didn't happen. With death and suffering all
around, there was no disastrous epidemic. Communicable diseases
did not sweep through the population. Safe water and food supplies
reached the people. The wounded received care.
<H2>Capacity building from day one</H2>

<P>
The past years have also taught us how critical it is not just
to put out a fire, but to start fire prevention: to introduce
health capacity building from day one.
<P>
People and agencies have been strengthened and are better able
to deal with the sorts of problems they are now facing.
<P>
Capacity building is self-sustaining. It makes the system more
normal and human. It provides a pillar of support for care providers
who have to deal with their own traumas as well as with those
of their patients.
<H2>What matters most</H2>

<P>
What has guided WHO action since 1992 is our allegiance to public
health. When forced to take sides, WHO has - and will always -
come down on the side of suffering people. Condemning the actions
of one opponent or the other does not mean sacrificing neutrality.
Rather, it is acting in the spirit of the WHO policy of health
for all. This, to us, is what matters most.
<P>
WHO's Regional Office for Europe moves into 1996 with a sharper
focus on our mission in the world. We thank the people who believe
in WHO's work, our donors for their support, our home and field
staff for their dedication, and all our partners for sharing in
our vision of health.<BR>

<P>
<I>J.E. Asvall, M.D.</I>
<BR>
WHO Regional Director
<BR>
for Europe

<hr>
<center>
