<TITLE>Ljubljana Conference</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">


<img src="techhead.gif">
<br>

<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="tech.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="tphs.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></a>
<a href="tech.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>


<center>

<H2>WHO Conference on <br>European Health Care Reforms<BR>
Ljubljana, Slovenia 17-20 June
</H2>
</center>
The World Health Organization (WHO) Conference on European Health Care Reforms, to be held in Ljubljana, Slovenia on 17-20 June, will be the centrepiece of discussion and debate by European health politicians, administrators and researchers in 1996. This ministerial-level event, involving the 50 European Member States of WHO, has already aroused wide interest among politicians, experts and international and nongovernmental organizations.
<P>
A charter on health care reform (the Ljubljana Charter) will be presented for adoption by the Conference. Its purpose is to identify a set of principles and action strategies, in line with the European strategy for health for all, that can inspire everyone involved in health care to take part in improving current European health care systems. A draft of the Charter was sent to Member States for review in March 1996.
<P>
An analysis of health care reforms in Europe will be presented at the Conference. Participants will be provided with written documentation covering the following topics:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>values, norms and current health sector development
<LI>reforming public health services
<LI>optimal balance of centralized and decentralized management responsibilities
<LI>responsibilities of ministries of health in reformed health systems
<LI>priority-setting and rationing of health services
<LI>balancing competition and solidarity in health care financing
<LI>allocating capital in investing in health
<LI>ensuring value for money from pharmaceuticals
<LI>improving clinical outcomes and the appropriateness of care
<LI>contracting models and provider competition in Europe
<LI>appropriate role for co-payments
<LI>performance-tied payment systems for providers
<LI>citizen participation and patient choice in reformed health systems
<LI>impact of health care reform on health outcomes
<LI>development and implementation of reform policies: a conceptual  framework
<LI>review of the implementation of health care reforms in the European Region
<LI>health care reform trends in Canada and New Zealand
<LI>public health, health promotion and intersectoral action
<LI>primary health care and health care reforms
<LI>general practitioners and health care reforms
<LI>nursing in primary health care
<LI>hospitals and health care reforms
<LI>expenditure trends in health care reforms
<LI>substitution policies from the perspective of primary health care
<LI>restructuring hospitals and substitution policies
<LI>research and training for health care reforms
<LI>quality of care and health care reforms
<LI>provider management under health care reforms
<LI>health insurance
<LI>equity and health care reforms.
</ol>


All these topics will be discussed at the Conference under two broad themes:
<UL>
<LI>the role of government and the market
<LI>the management of change and support for health care reforms.
</UL>
This important debate will form the basis for the WHO Action Plan on Health Care Reforms in Europe.

<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 12 August 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>



