<TITLE>World Health Day</TITLE>
<body bgcolor=#000000 text=#ffffff link=aqua vlink=yellow>
<center>

<img src="whday07.gif"><p>
<img src="whday06s.gif">
<br clear=left>
</center>

<H1><font color=yellow>Healthy Cities for a better life in Europe	</H1></font>


Most people in Europe live in towns and cities. These can be wonderful and healthy places, with work, entertainment, education and services close to where people live. But the reality is often different. The health of urban areas is an increasing concern. Poverty, pollution, poor services and growing inequalities are widespread. Some places lack essential infrastructures; in other areas the existing infrastructures are decaying faster than they can be replaced. And, in every city, the relationship of people to each other and to their environment is a fundamental determinant of their wellbeing. Europe continues to become more urbanized, and some of the most intractable public health problems - accidents,  AIDS, drug abuse, respiratory disease and violence - are particularly associated with the interaction between social conditions and the urban environment.
<P>
Today, European cities not only face the challenge to improve the health and quality of life of their own populations but also are partly responsible for the health of people living elsewhere, who are affected by activities in the city and their effects on the local regional and global social and physical environments. As major consumers of non-renewable resources and contributors to global pollution by carbon dioxide and other pollutants, European cities are in the front line of the desire for sustainable development and concern about climate change.
<P>
In many places, decentralization trends are strengthening the remit of local governments to deal with these issues. Cities and urban communities can provide an ideal setting for healthy sustainable development. They also have structures that make joint action between sectors and the involvement of communities easier than at the national level. Municipal authorities can take the lead in bringing together efforts by workplaces, nongovernmental organizations, community groups, nationally and locally run services, education and cultural organizations, and communities to create the vision, strategies and action needed to improve their citys health.
<P>
Yet cities face huge difficulties in taking action.  Some are hindered by administrative systems that hamper rather than promote intersectoral cooperation. They are under increasing financial pressure, and they have difficulties in adapting to rapidly changing political, demographic and economic circumstances.

<H3>How can we make cities healthier?</H3>
Against this background, the WHO Regional Office for Europe created the Healthy Cities project to assist cities to take action for health for all. In January 1987, 11 cities became the founding members of the network. Today, 600 cities in Europe participate in more than 30 national and regional Healthy Cities networks in Europe, and these networks are growing throughout the world.
<P>
The European health for all strategy provides the strategic framework for the project, supplemented by more detailed guidance such as the European Environment and Health Action Plan and Agenda 21.  The implications are that change is needed both in how things are done, as well as in what is done. 
<p>
Of key importance is the need to recognize that health is everybodys business, that action must involve the people who live in the city as well as all relevant sectors, and that the principle of equity should underpin all decision making.
<P>
The agenda for cities includes:

<UL>
<LI>the development of a municipal health plan based on health for all / Agenda 21;
<LI>involving communities in planning and action to improve the health of the city;
<LI>creating new approaches for public health and urban environmental management;
<LI>developing mechanisms to collaborate with all relevant sectors and levels of government; <LI>networking with other cities for exchange of information and mutual support.
</UL>


WHO Healthy Cities networks consist of the following main elements:

<UL>
<LI>the WHO project cities network, which is a network of cities that are committed to a comprehensive approach to working towards and attaining the goals of the project (including a process of systematic monitoring and evaluation that allows experience to be <LI>analysed, and good practices disseminated (see map on back page);
national and subnational Healthy Cities networks, along with EURONET (a forum that facilitates cooperation between the national networks in Europe (see map inside of back <LI>page);
<LI>multicity action plans (MCAPs), implemented by networks of cities working together on specific issues of common concern;
<LI>special (model) projects in cities in central and eastern Europe, to help them carry through  health care and environmental reforms by means of international cooperation, technical twinning arrangements and mechanisms for resource mobilization.
 </UL>


The Healthy Cities project assists cities through a process of mutual learning, international networking and technical assistance. Cities differ widely in their conditions and methods of urban management, as the attached figures illustrate. This gives the European Healthy Cities
network an excellent basis for mutual learning. The project has developed a wide body of knowledge and experience which will soon be considerably augmented by a major review of the second phase of the project due to end in 1997. The following pages list some of the publications and documentation from the Project, a selection of graphs from the Healthy Cities indicators database and maps showing the WHO project cities network and national networks in Europe.

<HR>

