<HTML>
<TITLE>Healthy Cities evalutation project</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif">
<P>
<IMG SRC="../techhead.gif" ALT="Technical programmes" HEIGHT="87" WIDTH="472">
<BR>
<A HREF="../../Welcome.htm"><IMG SRC="../../homeknap.gif" height=20 width=110 border=0></A> <A href="../tech.htm"><IMG src="../../sectknap.gif" height=20 width=110 border=0></A> <A href="index.htm"><IMG src="../../prevknap.gif" height=20 width=110 border=0></A> <A href="dublin96.htm"><IMG src="../../nextknap.gif" height=20 width=110 border=0></A>



<H1><CENTER><IMG SRC=" hcpsmall.gif" ALT="Healthy City small logo" WIDTH="147" HEIGHT="104" ALIGN="LEFT">Healthy Cities evaluation project </CENTER>
</H1>
<P>
<BR clear=left>
<HR>
<P>
Return to <A HREF="index.htm">WHO Healthy Cities homepage</A>
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Top"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>1996 is evaluation year for the WHO Healthy Cities project </CENTER></H3>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE >
<TR><TD WIDTH=236><B><IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"></B><FONT SIZE=4> <A HREF="#Dates">Important dates</A>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"> <A HREF="#Approach">The approach</A>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"> <A HREF="#Partners">Evaluation partners</A> </FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=236><B><IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"></B><FONT SIZE=4> <A HREF="#Introduction">Introduction</A>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"> <A HREF="#Themes">Evaluation themes</A>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="blueb01.gif" height=14 width=14 ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"> <A HREF="#Timetable">Evaluation timetable</A> </FONT>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE >
<TR><TD WIDTH=472><CENTER><A NAME="Dates"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H2>Important dates </H2>
<P>
<A HREF="dublin96.htm">Healthy Cities technical symposium: Dublin, 25-26 October 1996</A>.
<P>
<B>Evaluation</B> is the main theme of the technical symposium to be held in Dublin on 25 and 26 October 1996. The technical symposium follows the usual six monthly Healthy Cities business meeting which will be held in Dublin on 23 and 24 October 1996.
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Introduction"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H2>Introduction </H2>
<P>
<A HREF="#Top">Return to top</A>
<P>
Evaluation is an essential component of the WHO Healthy Cities project. By the end of the second phase of the project, WHO and project cities should be able to demonstrate the added value and the impact of their efforts. Project cities represent the testing ground for new ideas and innovative approaches. The project is complex, it has multiple layers of activity both at local and international levels and it covers a wide spectrum of actions in the fields of health policy, health promotion, environmental health, sustainable development, strategic planning, networking, community development and institutional change. <P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Approach"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H2>The approach </H2>
<P>
<A HREF="#Top">Return to top</A>
<P>
The project evaluation involves two main levels:<UL>
<LI>the <B>macro-level</B> (i.e. the evaluation of the overall international WHO project) and
<LI>the <B>local level</B> (i.e. the in-depth evaluation of the total or aspects of city projects).
</UL>
<P>
Both levels are necessary to generate the evidence that the sponsors and stakeholders (local, national and international) of the project need to continue and sustain their support for Healthy Cities. Furthermore this process will provide the information and the know-how for the hundreds of cities involved in the healthy cities movement around the world who look to the European WHO network for inspiration and guidance.<P>
The macro-level evaluation is initiated and coordinated by WHO in close partnership with project cities. The local-level evaluations are initiated and undertaken by project cities. These are two parallel but clearly interlinked and complementary processes and they should feed into each other. The in-depth evaluation of certain key aspects of the project across project cities (macro-level) will allow a better understanding of the process of change in different socio-cultural environments and the development of alternative model approaches.<P>
The macro-evaluation of the first phase of the WHO project (1988-1992) was mainly focused on the creation of the pre-conditions for change by assessing the structures and mechanisms for the implementation of the project, based on the requirements for participation in the WHO network. <P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Themes"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H2>Evaluation themes </H2>
<P>
<A HREF="#Top">Return to top</A>
<P>
The main themes of the macro-evaluation of the second phase (1993-1997) of the WHO project are: Health policy, Networking and Project management. The emphasis will be on:<OL>
<LI>assessing the products, outcomes and processes relating to health policy making (development and implementation of policies, preparation of health profiles and plans and development of process indicators to measure change)
<LI>identifying and assessing the formal and informal networking mechanisms at international and local levels that facilitate advocacy, innovation, solidarity, inter-sectoral action and use of information technology.
<LI>understanding and assessing project management in the context of its key functions: providing leadership and coordination, catalyzing alliance building and facilitating integration.
</OL>
<P>
Subject areas that cut across the above three theme lines are: Health Promotion, Environmental Health and Sustainable Urban Development, Community Development and the creation of Public Health Infrastructures.<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Timetable"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13></A></CENTER>
<H2>Evaluation timetable </H2>
<P>
<A HREF="#Top">Return to top</A>
<P>
The macro-evaluation of the second phase will have two stages:<H4><A NAME="First_stage">1st stage (May 1996 to October 1996)</A> </H4>
<UL>
<LI>General review and assessment of the work of the WHO Healthy Cities network using questionnaires and published city reports and documents as the main source of information for this purpose.
<LI>Reporting at the <A HREF="dublin96.htm" >Dublin technical symposium</A>.
</UL>
<H4><A NAME="Second_stage">2nd stage (November 1996 to December 1997)</A> </H4>
<UL>
<LI>In depth evaluation through city visits, in-situ interviews and analysis of city documents.
<LI>Reporting at the Healthy Cities symposium which will take place in June 1988.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Partners"><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13> </A></CENTER>
<H2>Evaluation partners </H2>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="mailto:p.humphreys@lse.ac.uk">Professor Patrick Humphreys</A> at <A HREF="http://lito.lse.ac.uk/socpsy/depthome.html">LSE Health</A>.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.rulimburg.nl/~who-city/eve.html">Dr Evelyne de Leeuw</A> at <A HREF="collabor.htm#Maastricht">WHO collaborating centre for research on healthy cities</A>.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG src="byline.gif" height=13 width=13> </CENTER>
