<HTML>
<title>AIDS publications</title>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<img src="bookhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="publicat.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="intro.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="airqual.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>




<H1 align=center>AIDS</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Psychosocial aspects of HIV and AIDS and the
evaluation of preventive strategies</H2>

<H3>Report on a WHO meeting</H3>

WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 36<BR>
1990, 45 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1127 0<BR>
Sw.fr. 10.- <BR>
Order No. 1310036<P>
The spread of HIV infection and AIDS depends very much on the way people behave. Those in
some population groups have been successfully persuaded to modify behaviour that put them at
increased risk. How this modification was achieved and how progress can be maintained are
crucial to controlling the spread of HIV. In this context, psychosocial factors have a vital role in
influencing behaviour. These not only determine who is vulnerable, but also help create
opportunities for prevention and determine the obstacles to risk reduction. They may also help
explain what shapes the responses of communities, professionals and policy-makers to the
growing epidemic.<P>
Participants in this fourth in a series of WHO meetings concentrated on four broad areas. They
felt that studies of knowledge, attitudes, behaviour and practices can be a valuable tool for
national AIDS programmes if used appropriately. They emphasized the importance of
maintaining the quality of programme monitoring and evaluation. They identified school and
college students as vital target audiences for AIDS education, and providers of health education
and social services for training in AIDS issues. Finally, they encouraged policy-makers and
programme managers to establish partnerships with journalists, as the mass media remain the
most efficient means of reaching the largest number of people.<P>
This is a useful and encouraging review for decision-makers, managers of national AIDS
programmes, professionals in the health, educational and related sectors, and the general
public.<P>
<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 7 August 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>

