<H1 align=center>Annual Report</H1>
<HR>
<H2>WHO in Europe. Meeting the
challenges</H2>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 57<BR>
1995, 17 pages [E, F, G, R]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1321 2<BR>
Sw.fr. 12.-<BR>
Order No. 1310057<P>
<P>
This report highlights some of the most interesting, innovative and effective activities of
the WHO regional Office for Europe in the past two years. The title summarizes WHOs
approach. Guided by the regional policy for health for all, with its primary goal of equity
in health, the Regional Office has developed new tactics and alliances to meet the needs
of the 50 diverse countries that comprise the WHO European Region.<P>
The report begins by sketching the health divide between the western and eastern halves
of the Region. Western countries continue to show improvements, while social, economic
and political transformation, sometimes accompanied by war, have revived old threats to
health and created new ones in the east. The remainder of the report describes WHOs
response to this situation, its development of methods and partnerships, and its notable
successes.<P>
Focusing on the countries in greatest need - the eastern half of the Region - the Regional
Office, with its partners, has tackled the resurgence of communicable diseases,
humanitarian assistance in the former Yugoslavia, high rates of maternal and infant death,
and the needs for integrated management of the environment and health, training in
nutrition, better training for nurses and health care system reform. Addressing issues
affecting the Region as a whole, the Regional Office has also done valuable work to
promote health through schools, to reduce smoking and drug abuse, to improve the
quality of health care and to help countries use the health for all approach to make health
policies of optimal effectiveness, efficiency and equity. Finally, the Regional Office has
fulfilled its role as an international centre of health information, providing the data
needed to guide its activities and those of governments and other organization interested
in health. Here its activities range from surveying health in the Region as a whole to work
on more specific topics, such as early warning of communicable diseases and making the
first-ever profiles of womens health.<P>
This report gives an insight into the work of the WHO Regional Office for Europe as it
faces the challenges of working for health in the new Europe.<P>
<hr>
