<H1 align=center>Health Policy and Evaluation</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Implementation of the Global Strategy for
Health for All by the Year 2000: second
evaluation</H2>

<H3>Eighth report on the world health situation - Volume
5: European Region</H3>

WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 52<BR>
1993, vi + 280 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN (HQ) 92 4 160285 6<BR>
ISBN (EURO) 92 890 1316 8<BR>
Sw.fr. 48.-<BR>
Order No. 1310052<P>

Volume 5 of the <I>Eighth report on the world health situation</I> is the European
Region's contribution to a seven-volume work that provides a detailed assessment, at
global, regional and country levels, of the extent to which strategies to develop health
systems based on primary health care are being successfully implemented. Emphasis is
placed on changes in the health situation in the European Region as measured through
data, covering the period 1985-1990, on several well defined indicators of health status
and progress on reaching the goal of health for all.<P>
The volume is in two parts. Part I is an overview in eight chapters of socioeconomic
developments, changes in the health system, and changes in health status as indicated by
statistics on morbidity and mortality. The main body of Part I follows the structure of the
regional targets for health for all, adopted by the Member States in 1984.<P>
Part II provides a detailed account of health conditions in selected individual Member
States, covering demography, health status (equity, health potential, mortality and
morbidity), lifestyles, health and the environment, and developments in the health service
system, and finishing with a summary of the country's progress towards health for all.
Those Member States that underwent rapid and extensive political and socioeconomic
change (with its consequent effect on the health services) between the collection of data
and the publication of the results are addressed in the opening section of Part II.<P>
<HR>
<H2>The health of Europe</H2>
<H3>Summary of the second health for all
evaluation</H3>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 49<BR>
1993, 18 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1313 3<BR>
Sw.fr. 12.-<BR>
Order No. 1310049<P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, Europe saw the beginnings of a process of change. Slowly at first and
then gathering pace, this process developed into the enormous political and social
changes now under way in central and eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. At
the same time, all European countries are faced with severe economic problems.<P>
It is against this backdrop that the results of the second large-scale evaluation of WHO's
health for all strategy in Europe must be seen. Undertaken in each country of the Region
in 1990-1991, the evaluation is possibly the last and most extensive overview of the
health of Europe on the brink of the new era.<P>
The evaluation shows that, on balance, health in the Region improved in the 1980s, with
increased life expectancy, progress on eliminating infectious diseases, and reduced
mortality from the leading causes of death. Development on other fronts, however, was
moderate to disappointing, with no real progress at all on the primary target for health for
all - equity. But there are real grounds for optimism in the fact that health policy
development has taken a big step forward. It is surely within the framework of national
policies based on health for all that the future health of all European peoples lies.<P>
This publication provides a succinct overview of the results of the evaluation in Europe,
published as Volume 5 of the <I>Eighth report on the world health situation</I>.<P>
<I>" ... the most comprehensive report of its kind ..." - The European</I><P><I>
</I><HR>
<H2>Health for all targets</H2>
<P>
<H3>The health policy for Europe</H3>
<P>
European Health for All Series, No. 4<BR>
1993, xi + 228 pages [E, F, G, R]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1311 7<BR>
Sw.fr. 36.-<BR>
Order No. 1360004<P>
<P>
In 1985 the Regional Office published <I>Targets for health for all</I>, setting out the
38 targets endorsed by the 33 European Member States of WHO in September 1984. This
was a breakthrough in European health development: for the first time, the Member
States had agreed to adopt a single health policy as a common basis for individual and
cooperative action. The new and revised targets incorporated in the present book reflect
changes that have taken place in the Region since 1984 and a more up-to-date
understanding of the problems involved in target setting and achievement. In addition, the
concern with ethics is a new theme reflected throughout the book.<P>
The book comprises eight chapters, five of which set out the targets themselves. In
chapter 3, targets 1-12 express in specific terms the improvements in health sought over
the 20 years between 1980 and the year 2000. Chapter 4 (targets 13-17) addresses the
health work that is essential to attain lifestyles conducive to health, while chapter 5
(targets 18-25) is concerned with the contribution that the environment makes to health,
and Chapter 6 (targets 26-31) with the provision of appropriate services for prevention,
treatment and care. In chapter 7, targets 32-38 provide the infrastructure for sustained
political, managerial and financial support to the strategies set out in chapters 4-6.<P>
Each target is presented together with the problems that need to be addressed and the
suggested means of solving those problems.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Forty years of WHO in Europe</H2>
<P>
<H3>The development of a common health policy</H3>
<P>
By Leo A. Kaprio<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 40<BR>
1991, xi + 135 pages [E, F]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1303 6<BR>
Sw.fr. 24.-<BR>
Order No. 310040<P>
<P>
The Europe of 1991, when this story finishes, is vastly different from the continent of 40
years ago when the WHO Regional Office for Europe began its work. The story began
with a Europe not only devastated by the Second World War but embarking on decades
of what was to be known as the "cold war" between east and west. Yet despite the
apparently irreconcilable ideological differences, and their expression in political and
military confrontation, the record of the Regional Office and its Member States of all
political persuasions is one of unqualified success.<P>
Professor Kaprio's book is intentionally far from exhaustive. It is a subjective account of
development in cooperation for health among the European Member States - both with
one another and with WHO. It will delight both those who have shared in the building of
that cooperation and those who are coming fresh to this historic episode.<P>
<P>
<HR>
<H2>Health in Europe</H2>
<P>
<H3>The 1993/1994 health for all monitoring report</H3>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 56<BR>
1994, 58 pages [E, F, G, R]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1320 6<BR>
Sw.fr. 17.-<BR>
Order No. 1310056<P>
<P>
Everyone knows that the WHO European Region is undergoing profound, sometimes
violent, political, social and economic change, particularly in the central and eastern
countries and the former USSR. This book tracks the effects of these changes on health
and some of the ways in which countries are responding. <P>
Regular monitoring and evaluation are vital parts of the European strategy for health for
all. While the 1990/1991 evaluation took place just as the wave of change struck the
Region, the 1993/1994 monitoring exercise could measure its effects on health. This book
gives the results of the exercise, including a brief and easily understood summary.<P>
This book is essential reading for professionals, researchers and policy-makers in health
and related fields, and anyone interested in the tides of health in Europe.<P>


See <a href="/country/euro/part0h.htm"><b><i>Health in Europe</I></B></A>




