<h1 align=center>Health Promotion</h1>
<HR>
<H2>Health promotion research</H2>

<H3>Towards a new social epidemiology</H3>

Edited by B. Badura and I. Kickbusch<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 37<BR>
1990, x + 496 pages<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1128 9<BR>
Sw.fr. 80.-<BR>
Order No. 1310037<P>

Social factors affect health. Social epidemiologists have shown not only the harmful
effects of stress and the helpful ones of social support but also the importance of the
wider physical and social environment. This raises two questions for health promotion
research. How can we better understand the social determinants of health and disease?
How can healthy public policy transform present knowledge into action? This book gives
some of the most recent, relevant and reliable answers to both.<P>
<I>"... an extremely useful source-book ..." - Family practice</I><P><I>
</I><I>"... is a treasure trove of information of both theoretical and practical
significance ... I will return to this book regularly ..." - Canadian journal of public
health</I>
<HR>
<H2>Health promotion and chronic
diseases</H2>

<H2>Discovering a new quality of health</H2>

Edited by Annette Kaplun<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 44<BR>
1992, xviii + 461 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1307 9<BR>
Sw.fr. 68.-<BR>
Order No. 1310044<P>

A wide-ranging analysis of the ways in which health promotion approaches can be used
to help the chronically ill and disabled exploit their potential to lead healthy and
productive lives. Citing a number of promising developments in recent years, the book
calls for a fundamental change in society's attitudes towards the chronically ill, whereby
emphasis is placed on their potential and due attention is given to their need for support
that goes beyond medical care. With this goal in mind, the book evaluates a wealth of
recent experiences and research findings in order to identify practical measures that can
be pursued by the health care sector, by public and private organizations, and by the
chronically ill and their families. Three main chronic conditions are considered: coronary
heart disease, cancer and chronic pain.<P>
The book features 54 papers authored by experts in cardiology, oncology, pain
management, rheumatology, psychology, physiology, rehabilitation medicine and
epidemiology, and by representatives of numerous self-help groups throughout Europe.
Papers are presented in twelve main parts. Papers in the first part set out a conceptual
framework for helping the chronically ill cope with the stress of illness and enhance their
health potential. The second part explores the importance of self-reliance, self-help and
self-determination in patients recovering from a heart attack. The needs of cancer patients
are covered in the third part, which considers the role that alternative therapies and
behavioural approaches can play in extending survival time and enhancing the quality of
life. The fourth part, on chronic pain, points to the need for a combined involvement of
social, psychological and medical knowledge in the management of chronic pain.<P>
Other chapters relate experiences in changing public health policies, in creating
supportive environments, in strengthening community action, and in developing the
personal coping skills of the chronically ill and disabled. Information ranges from advice
on how self-help groups can gain media support, through a discussion of the reasons why
the chronically ill seek alternative therapies, through descriptions of experiences with a
variety of new therapies for helping heart patients, cancer patients, families with a
handicapped child, and persons suffering from chronic pain, migraine and rheumatism.
The remaining chapters, concerned with the need to reorient health services, consider the
specific changes that need to be made in training, health research and health care. Over
500 references to the literature are included.<P>
<I>" ... The range and diversity of topics addressed in this beautifully presented, clearly
written and well-referenced book suggest that it should be essential reading for those
involved in all aspects of the provision and delivery of health care ..." - Nursing
times</I><P><I>
</I><I>" ... The book is always thought provoking, and the ideas in it deserve to be
considered by the mainstream health service ..." - British medical journal</I><P><I>
</I><HR>
<H2>Economic change, social welfare and
health in Europe</H2>
<P>
Edited by Lowell S. Levin, Laurie McMahon and Erio Ziglio<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 54<BR>
1994, 131 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1318 4<BR>
Sw.fr.29.-<BR>
Order No. 1310054<P>
<P>
Never before in peacetime has the convergence of political and economic change had
such a powerful impact on the health and wellbeing of the 850 million people of the
WHO European Region. Countries that have been insulated from such shifts now feel
their effects. People who have always had jobs are frustrated in unemployment and
bewildered about what action their governments should take. This multi-author
publication looks at how such a social change can affect people.<P>
First, it traces the development of theories on peoples response to unemployment. Then
it presents two recent studies on the effects of unemployment and income levels in
Finland and Sweden, describes the effects of economic changes in the United Kingdom
on people and their families, and compares the different cases of Finland and Hungary.
Ironically, men find the loss of their jobs doubly painful. While unemployed women often
have home responsibilities to keep them busy, men are left with nothing that supports
their self-esteem.<P>
Finally, two chapters look at the wider perspective of the interaction between the welfare
state and social change. Unemployment is but one of the several dimensions of social
change and is both cause and consequence. An extraordinarily complex range of
interacting variables emerges, in both countries and communities. Depending on which
end of the telescope one looks through, solutions vary. The negative effects of social and
economic pressure can be solved by long-term structural changes at the country level, or
by short-term relief adjustments at the individual level.<P>
The contributors to this book help us appreciate that these solutions must be
complementary rather than conflictual. They also help us understand the start political
reality that this is more easily said than done. But the book clearly describes the issues at
stake in the debate, and that is the crucial first step.<P>
<hr>

<h2>The health of youth<br>

A cross-national survey</h2>
<P>
By <I>A. King, B. Wold, C. Tudor-Smith and Y. Harel
</I>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications,
<br>
European Series, No.69
<br>
1996, x + 232 pages (E)
<br>
ISBN 92 890 1333 8
<br>
Sw.fr. 59.-.
<br>
Order No. 1310069<BR>
<P>
The WHO Health Behaviour in School-Aged Children (HBSC) Study
is a collaborative cross-national research study, designed to
increase understanding of the health-related attitudes and behaviours
of young people. It has attracted a growing number of participating
countries. This particular report gives the results of the fourth
survey carried out since 1982, on schoolchildren in 24 countries
in the European Region and Canada. 

<P>
This publication will be essential reading for health policy-makers,
health educators and researchers in health promotion.
<p>

The survey looks at 11-, 13- and 15-year-old children's attitude
towards and experience of  a wide range of health-related behaviours
and lifestyle issues including: smoking, drinking, exercise, diet,
health and illness, injuries, and school and social life. While
children's use of tobacco and alcohol increases with age, they
exercise less as they grow older.  Many children's diets are unhealthy
and worsen with age.  Injuries from leisure activities are high,
particularly among those who play sports.  More positively, a
majority of students do not usually feel lonely, helpless and
out of things; they reported making friends easily, having at
least two close friends, and talking easily to their mother.
Girls find their teenage years more difficult than boys.  However,
girls like school more than boys do.  The school setting appears
to contribute to the perceptions students have about their health
and happiness: those who are satisfied with school tend to show
positive attitudes in several areas and reported less damaging
behaviours. 
<P>
The implications for health promotion policies and programmes
include: 
<UL>
<LI>legislation on the sale of tobacco and alcohol to young people
should be strengthened and more actively enforced;
<LI>health promotion programmes against tobacco and alcohol should
start early and be extended to all pupils;
<LI>school and leisure-related policy in areas such as sport and
exercise, nutrition and injuries should be further examined;
<LI>the working and living conditions offered by schools should
be improved;
<LI>health promotion initiatives should combine health-enhancing
behaviours and positive experiences for students and should simultaneously
address schools, families and leisure settings.
</UL>



These implications will be of great interest to health-policy
makers and health educators, while the continuing expansion of
the HBSC Study will give researchers valuable insight into how
to carry out a cross-national survey.  

<P>
The report includes appendices on the school system in each country,
the methodology used in the survey and the names of the principal
investigators.  

<p>




