<H1 align=center>Legislation</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Lgislation sanitaire et personnes
ges</H2>
<H3>Une tude europenne</H3>

By P. Vellas<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 33<P>
1990, 95 pages [F]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 2124 1<BR>
Sw.fr. 16.50<BR>
Order No. 2310033<P>
<P>
A major problem in recent decades has been the rapid aging of the European population.
This trend seems likely to persist and may well become even more marked by the year
2000. Another cause for concern is the expected spectacular increase in those over 80
years of age. It is this group, the most vulnerable, that will require the greatest effort if the
health and quality of life of the population at large are to be improved. Health legislation
is not only one of the most effective means of improving the physical, mental and social
wellbeing of the elderly; it is probably the only way of translating policy into practice.
Yet there are serious disparities and shortcomings in the legislation of the European
countries, not to mention huge inequalities in the budgets allocated to services for the
elderly. This book offers a fresh view of the contribution legislation can make to solving
these problems, identifying the areas where, although currently absent or inadequate in
many European countries, legislation might be particularly useful. The book will
therefore be of interest to all concerned with these problems and in particular to lawyers,
politicians and legislators.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Is the law fair to the disabled?</H2>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 29<BR>
1990, xiii + 354 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1120 3<P>
Sw.fr. 45.-<BR>
Order No. 1310029<P>
<P>
The disabled have the same rights as everyone else, but are they always encouraged and
enabled to exercise them? This survey of 25 European countries explores the laws
affecting the disabled and how they are implemented. The countries take two main
approaches to equality for the disabled: while some feel it is less discriminatory to
incorporate disability issues in a number of different existing laws, others prefer to adopt
a single law specific to the disabled. The book shows that the emphasis is now on self-
help and independence, rather than on disability pensions and homes for the disabled.
This is due not only to changing social attitudes, but also to the increased emphasis on
incentives for employers to employ disabled people, grants for the disabled to adapt their
homes, and a switch of funds from institutional establishments to community support
services. Disabled people are increasingly able to earn their own living, travel about, live
independently and take part in social and sporting events.<P>
This is a heartening review of the conditions disabled people now live under in the
European Region, as we near the end of the International Decade of Disabled Persons. It
should be read with interest by the disabled themselves, by all those involved in their
affairs, and by anyone concerned about the way society treats its minority groups.<P>
<I>"Any burgeoning European ... will find this book fascinating ... an invaluable
collection of 25 countries' contributions on the subject of the legal and social rights of
disabled people ... a singularly important publication." - Journal of the Royal Society of
Health</I><P><I>
</I><HR>
<P>
