<HTML>
<title>Non communicable diseases publications</title>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">

<img src="bookhead.gif">
<br>
<a href="../Welcome.htm"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="publicat.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="matchld.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="nuclear.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>




<H1 align=center>Noncommunicable diseases</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Assessing hypertension control and
management</H2>
<H3>Hypertension Management Audit Project: a
WHO/WHL Study.</H3>

Edited by T. Strasser and L. Wilhelmsen<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 47<BR>
1992, xiv + 181 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1301 9<BR>
Sw.fr. 39.-<BR>
Order No. 1310047<P>

Hypertension affects up to 30% of people in certain European populations, and seriously
jeopardizes their health. If properly managed, hypertension can be reduced and its effects
minimized, but the question is how often this is achieved in practice. This publication
reports on the results of the WHO Hypertension Management Audit Project carried out to
assess the levels and quality of the management of hypertension in selected European
countries. <P>
Centres in Germany, Hungary, Israel, Italy, Romania, Spain, Switzerland and the former
Yugoslavia took part in the Project, by carrying out one or more of five kinds of survey.
The community survey identified the proportion of undiagnosed and untreated, as well as
overdiagnosed and unnecessarily treated, hypertensives in a sample population. The
patient survey then reviewed the treatment history of patients confirmed as hypertensives.
The consumer inquiry treated patients as consumers and examined their views about the
treatment they had received. The physician inquiry assessed the knowledge and attitudes
of physicians involved in the treatment of hypertension. This contrasted interestingly with
the actual treatment identified in the patient survey. Finally, the drug utilization study
assessed the volume and type of drug prescriptions in relation to the hypertensive
population. <P>
The results show that the level of detection has improved over the last two decades, but
technological diagnostic tests are still preferred to simpler but more relevant behavioural
questions. Treatment is still not as effective as it could be. While most physicians
understand the correct techniques for the management of hypertension, far fewer carry
them out in practice. Thus the greatest potential for improvement in the care of
hypertensive patients lies in the psychological sphere. A better understanding is needed of
why patients, as consumers, are or are not happy and comply with treatment, and of why
physicians, as providers, do or do not give treatment in line with their stated beliefs.<P>
This is a most valuable survey of how the known techniques for managing hypertension
are being carried out. Although it spans countries from all corners of Europe, it shows
remarkable similarities despite cultural and health care differences.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Comprehensive cardiovascular community
control programmes in Europe</H2>
<P>
Edited by P. Puska in collaboration with<BR>
E. Leparski, G. Lamm, H. Heine, J. Pereira, <BR>
Z. Pisa and D.Thelle<P>
EURO Reports and Studies, No. 106<BR>
1988, vi + 91 pages [E, F, G, R]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1272 2<BR>
Sw.fr. 6.-<BR>
Order No. 1330106<P>
<P>
Evaluates the methods and findings of nine European pilot programmes designed to
determine whether interventions, aimed at entire communities, could modify risks for
cardiovascular diseases and improve prevention and control. Experiences in different
countries, most covering more than a decade, are critically compared in an effort to draw
conclusions about the success of community-wide interventions in reducing population
risk factor levels and decreasing the incidence of cardiovascular mortality.<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Palliative cancer care</H2>
<P>
Policy statement based on the recommendations of a WHO
consultation<P>
<P>
1989, viii + 40 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1059 2<BR>
Sw.fr. 15.-<BR>
Order No. 1340041<P>
<P>
A policy statement intended to focus attention on the crucial need for palliative care in
cancer patients. Information is specific to cancer problems and methods of management
prevailing in Europe. Addressed to health authorities and the medical and nursing
professions, the report issues guidance on what needs to be done to ensure that patients
with advanced cancer benefit from available methods for the management of pain and
other symptoms. Emphasis is placed on the changes in thinking, services and resources
needed to help cancer patients achieve their maximum physical, emotional, spiritual,
vocational and social potential. Details range from a list of common symptoms and
sources of discomfort in patients, through 14 essential elements of good symptom control,
to advice on the organization of health services for care of the dying in a hospital, in the
community, and in hospices and palliative care units. <P>
<hr>
