<H1 align=center>Nursing</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Nursing in action</H2>
<H3>Strengthening nursing and midwifery to support
health for all</H3>

Edited by Jane Salvage<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 48<BR>
1993, 123 pages [E, F*, R*]<BR>
[also German version published by Quintessenz, ISBN 3-86128-332-8]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1312 5<BR>
Sw.fr. 24.-<BR>
Order No. 1310048<P>

The profound changes now taking place in Europe's health care raise key questions for
nurses and midwives. The issue is not whether they should change their practice, but how
they will change it - and what role they will play in meeting the health needs of the
future.<P>
Nurses are already debating these questions, and have chosen WHO's strategy for health
for all as their guiding star. In every Member State of the European Region, a movement
has started to create a new kind of nurse: an autonomous, skilled practitioner whose role
is not to serve other professionals but to inform, support and care for the patient and the
community.<P>
Creating this role, and ensuring it has the necessary support, are formidable tasks. How
can they be tackled? This book provides the starting point. It combines vision and action
in chapters on:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Defining the nurse's role and functions
<LI>Changing nursing practice
<LI>Developing regulatory systems
<LI>Reforming nursing education
<LI>Preparing leaders.
</UL>

Nursing in action is a book for all nurses, midwives and health personnel doing nursing
work. It also provides food for thought to policy-makers, health service managers, health
professionals and consumers working towards health for all. It provides an overview of
WHO nursing policies and guidelines which is relevant to nurses everywhere, and is an
excellent introductory text for those in the forefront of nursing development.<P>


