<H1 align=center>Nutrition</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Food and health data</H2>

<H3>Their use in nutrition policy-making</H3>

Edited by W. Becker and E. Helsing<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 34<BR>
1990, 171 pages [E, F*, G]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1125 4<BR>
Sw.fr. 26.-<BR>
Order No. 1310034<P>

Nutrition policies are a relatively new phenomenon in Europe. They require health
promotion to be made an important consideration in all food-policy decisions. Nutrition
policy-makers try to establish what sort of diet a population should be eating in order to
become and remain healthy. To do this, they need to know not only what the population
ought to be eating, but also what they are actually eating. Food balance sheets, household
budget surveys and individual-level studies all provide data on the dietary patterns of
populations. <P>
This book makes a critical assessment of these data sources, examining what each can
(and cannot) tell us and how they should be used. It will be a vital guide to all those who
could and should contribute to people's nutritional wellbeing: food producers and
manufacturers, officials in ministries of agriculture, industry, trade and health, and
individuals in positions that entail decision-making on food such as caterers, hospital
administrators, and food importers and retailers.
<HR>
<H2>Healthy nutrition</H2>

<H3>Preventing nutrition-related diseases in Europe</H3>

By W.P.T. James in collaboration with A. Ferro-Luzzi, B. Isaksson and W.B. Szostak<P>
<P>
WHO Regional Publications, <BR>
European Series, No. 24<BR>
1988, 111 pages [E, F, G, R]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1115 7<BR>
Sw.fr. 20.-<P>
Order No. 1310024<P>

A stimulating discussion of ways in which European governments might adjust food
policies to incorporate health objectives in line with the overwhelming evidence linking
dietary factors to disease. Authored by experts in medical nutrition, the book serves as
both a rich source of data on European eating patterns and a persuasive call for actions
that can help Europeans select foods conducive to good health. Concrete policy
recommendations are presented with a full awareness of the difficulties involved in
altering traditional food choices, changing agricultural policies, and improving
manufacturing practices within the food industry.<P>
The most extensive chapter evaluates what is known about the relationship of dietary
patterns in different European countries to the prevalence of coronary heart disease,
cerebrovascular disease, diabetes, obesity, cancer, cirrhosis of the liver, bone disease in
the elderly, oral disease, nutritional anaemia and goitre. Findings from this evaluation are
then used to examine ways in which nutrition-based food policies can facilitate
prevention.<P>
<I>"... presents nutritional facts and epidemiological findings clearly and convincingly
... a valuable resource for clinical nutrition counselling as well as for the planners of a
healthy food supply..." - Medicine and war</I>


