<H1 align=center>Substance Abuse</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Drug abusers in prisons: managing their
health problems</H2>

<H3>Report on a WHO meeting</H3>

WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 27<BR>
1990, 52 pages<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1118 1<BR>
Sw.fr. 10.-<BR>
Order No. 1310027<P>

The proportion of drug abusers in prisons has grown enormously in recent decades. This
has put a great strain on the health services available to prisoners, which is exacerbated by
the recent steep rise in the rate of infection of drug abusers with HIV. This book looks at
the methods used to identify drug abusers on admission to prison and measures used to
treat drug dependence. It looks closely at the special nature of drug treatment in prison:
both the ethics of treating people who are incarcerated against their will and the likely
effect of their lack of motivation on the outcome. It also looks at health problems related
to drug abuse, such as AIDS and suicide.<P>
This in-depth review should be read by those in the public health and criminal justice
sectors who are responsible for the health and welfare of the prison population, as well as
by researchers concerned with methods of treating drug dependence.<P>
<HR>




<a name="tobacco"><H2>It can be done</H2></A>

<H3>A smoke-free Europe</H3>

WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 30<BR>
1990, 67 pages [E]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1121 1<BR>
Sw.fr. 18.-<BR>
Order No. 1310030<P>

"To all the thinking people concerned with the saving and not the destruction of human
life, the message from the First European Conference on Tobacco Policy is clear. Target
number one is a smoke-free Europe. It can be done." This book summarizes the tough
lines of action mapped out during Europe's first conference on tobacco policy, a
watershed in the history of action against tobacco. <P>
The conference, which united some of the most experienced scientists, social scientists,
and experts on health education and public health policy in Europe, drew unprecedented
force and determination from a number of developments in research and public opinion,
including data showing the increased risk of lung cancer and other severe diseases in non-
smokers exposed to tobacco smoke, the growing view that tobacco-polluted air is a matter
of grave environmental concern, and the increasing unwillingness to swallow the
industry's argument for corporate freedom at the expense of so many lives. <P>
The book opens with a six-point charter asserting the moral rights of Europe's citizens to
be protected not only from the diseases tobacco causes but also from the severe hazards
of breathing air polluted by tobacco smoke. To make it possible for every person in
Europe to enjoy the rights stipulated in the charter, the book sets out ten precise strategies
for a smoke-free Europe, further concluding that a tobacco control policy that
encompassed these ten strategies could bring about a significant reduction of tobacco
consumption in Europe and could eventually eliminate the diseases caused by
tobacco.<P>
The book is itself heavily and pointedly illustrated. The pictures of coffins and of model
ads showing an amputated leg or the cancer surgeon at work contrast sharply with a series
of cartoons depicting the cigarette, with its watering can of poison, under the increasingly
well-armed attack of a stormy climate of opinion, a surgeon's scalpel, the muscle of
fitness, stethoscopes, a gavel, and the ball-and-chain of a tax increase. These illustrations
work to enforce the report's conclusion that a popular movement to rid Europe of
tobacco-related disease will be irresistible. It can be done, and this book shows how.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Management of drinking problems</H2>

By Peter Anderson<BR>
WHO Regional Publications,<BR>
European Series, No. 32<BR>
1990, 168 pages [E, F, G]<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1123 8<BR>
Sw.fr.26.-<BR>
Order No. 1310032<P>

In many parts of Europe alcohol consumption has risen considerably over the past 25-30
years, and this has been matched by a huge increase in alcohol-related problems. Many
European countries see this as a major public health problem second only to cigarette
smoking. The approach of WHO to this question is to emphasize the importance of a
response embedded in the community and the need for early recognition, rather than
specialist treatment. WHO has also suggested ways of using reporting systems or other
strategies for small-scale monitoring, implying that early recognition is possible and that
nipping the problem in the bud will prevent further damage. The logic and economic
practicality of primary-level intervention are undisputed, but more work is urgently
needed to translate the rhetoric into workable, everyday activities. This book sets out to
examine the issues in detail. It is based on the reports of three working groups convened
by WHO. The first group considered treatment and rehabilitation programmes for alcohol
abuse, the second examined the respective roles of the primary care and specialized
services, and the third reported on the implementation and evaluation of programmes for
problem drinkers. The book concludes with a list of over 350 references.<P>
<HR>
<h2>Publication Series of the European Alcohol
Action Plan</h2>

In the WHO European Region, alcohol production and trade are big business, and
harmful drinking has high costs to health and society. Because many of the problems
related to alcohol use can be prevented, the WHO European Alcohol Action Plan
promotes comprehensive policies to reduce harmful consumption in all countries of the
Region. WHO is producing a series of nine publications to support the Action Plan and
the making and implementation of policies in countries.<P>
<P>
The nine booklets address many of the issues involved in policy-making and action to
reduce harmful drinking and its consequences for drinkers, their families and society.
They cover a range of topics, including:<P>
<UL>
<LI>approaches to policy and their economic aspects
<LI>taking and evaluating action on alcohol at different levels
<LI>treatment approaches
<LI>special groups and settings, such as young people, the mass media and the workplace.
</UL>
Each booklet discusses both problems and opportunities for action in the subject area.<P>
The series offers useful and interesting reading for anyone concerned with health
promotion, substance use and particularly responses to the harm caused by alcohol use. It
will make an important contribution to the success of the European Alcohol Action Plan
and thus to progress towards health for all.<P>
Titles in the series:<P>
<I>Evaluation and monitoring of action on alcohol</I><BR>
By<I> </I>Peter Anderson and Juhani Lehto<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No. 59<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1323 0<P>
<I>Approaches to alcohol control policy</I><BR>
By Juhani Lehto<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No.60<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1324 9<P>
<I>The economics of alcohol policy</I><BR>
By Juhani Lehto<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No. 61<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1325 7 (in press)<P>
<I>Alcohol and the media</I><BR>
By Marjatta Montonen<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No.62<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1326 5 (in press)<P>
<I>Community and municipal action on alcohol</I><BR>
By Bruce Ritson<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No.63<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1327 3 (in press)<P>
<I>Alcohol and primary health care</I><BR>
By Peter Anderson<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No.64<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1328 1 (in press)<P>
<I>Treatment approaches to alcohol</I><BR>
By Nick Heather<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No. 65<br>
ISBN 92 890 1229 X (in press)<P>
<I>Young people and alcohol, drugs and tobacco</I><BR>
By Kellie Anderson<BR>
WHO Regional Publications, European Series, No.66<BR>
ISBN 92 890 1230 3<P>
