<H1 align=center>Books published on behalf of
WHO/Europe</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Published by the British Medical
Association</H2>
<H3>Clearing the air</H3>
<H4>A guide for action on tobacco </H4>
By Martin Raw, Patti White and Ann McNeill<BR>
1990, 151 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 7279 0287 3<BR>
 5.95 sterling within Europe<BR>
 7.95 sterling outside Europe<P>
<P>
The latest in a succession of practical guides for action to control tobacco. The heart of
this book is its case studies - descriptions of actions that have been taken to achieve
different policy objectives. Section one outlines the key elements of a tobacco control
programme and describes how a group of British doctors responded to the tobacco
problem. Section two offers case studies drawn from experiences in Europe, North
America and Australia. Among the stories told are how a tobacco company tried to
suppress a booklet about tobacco promotion for Swedish children, a description of the
Australian MOP UP and BUGA up campaigns, and how the 1988 Calgary Winter
Olympics became the smoke-free Olympics. The last section lists key individuals,
organizations and publications that will help readers to develop their own actions against
tobacco.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Chapman &amp  Hall</H2>
<H3>Ecogenetics</H3>
<H4>Genetic predisposition to the toxic effects of chemicals</H4>
Edited by Philippe Grandjean<BR>
1991, xiv + 288 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 412 39290 9<P>
 35.- sterling<P>
<P>
Explores the increasingly important area of inherited hypersusceptibility to environmental
chemicals. Nineteen chapters, written by an international team of experts, review the
experimental, pharmacological, toxicogenetic and epidemiological evidence and consider
the implications for preventive action and future research. The important ethical and legal
aspects are covered, as is the role of genetic factors in the pathogenesis of ischaemic heart
disease and major types of cancer. <P>
<a href="http://www.thomson.com/orderinfo.html">Order form</A>
<HR>
<h2>Published by CRC PRESS</h2>

<H2>Allergic hypersensitivities induced by
chemicals: recommendations for
prevention</H2>
<P>
Edited by J.G. Vos, M. Younes and E. Smith<BR>
1996, 348 pages<BR>
ISBN 0-8493-9226-8<BR>
US $ 120 (US $ 99.95 in the US)<P>
<P>
The prevalence of allergic disorders appears to be rising in many countries, particularly
among children. These allergies include dermatitis, hay fever, asthma, reactions to insect
stings and to drugs and food additives. Many are caused by synthetic chemicals, to which
more and more people are exposed. <P>
This book, commissioned by WHO and written by a group of international experts, brings
together the latest knowledge in this field. It looks at how allergic sensitization of the skin
and the respiratory tract is triggered and by which chemicals, and what diagnostic and
predictive tests can be used to prevent or treat it. It makes recommendations about the
priority actions that scientists and public health officials can take to improve knowledge
of allergens and their mechanisms among both the public and the health professions.
Health professionals such as physicians, nurses, health managers, immunologists and
toxicologists will find it invaluable in their work with allergies, allergens and allergy
sufferers.  <P>
<a href="http://www.crcpress.com/order/crcorder.htm">Order form</A>
<HR>

<h2>Environmental epidemiology </h2>

<h3>Exposure and disease</h3>

Proceedings of an International Workshop on Priorities in Environmental
Epidemiology<BR>

<P>
Edited by Roberto Bertollini, Michael D. Lebowitz, Rodolfo Saracci
&amp; David A. Savitz
<P>
1996, 256 pages
<P>
ISBN 1-56670-067-1
<P>
US $72.00 (US $59.95 in the US)

<P>
This publication is a unique resource identifying priorities for public health research in selected areas of environmental epidemiology. It is a compilation of the specialized knowledge and opinions of environmental epidemiology experts, brought together at a workshop
organized by the Rome division of the WHO European Centre for Environment and Health.  The chapters cover the topic from three different viewpoints: environmental exposures, major disease groups related to the environment and epidemiological methodology.  To prioritize, the authors used a set of criteria based on exposure conditions, health effects and the feasibility of human studies. This publication provides essential guidance for research emphasis and the allocation of financial and technical resources.

<hr>













<H2>Published by DWSO Press</H2>

<H2>Attempted suicide in Europe:</H2>
<P>
Findings from the multicentre study on parasuicide by the WHO
Regional Office for Europe.<P>
<P>
By A.J.F.M. Kerkhof, A. Schmidtke, U. Bille-Brahe, D. Deleo and J. Lnnqvist.<P>
<P>
Series: Psychological Studies 16<BR>
1994, 296 pages<BR>
ISSN 0928-8059-16<BR>
ISBN 90-6695-102-8<BR>
US $45.-<P>
<P>
In Europe, nonfatal suicidal behaviour has been identified as a major public health
problem and a considerable drain on resources. Unfortunately, due to cross-cultural
differences both in medical treatment of nonfatal suicidal behaviour and in research
methodology, it is almost impossible to make valid comparisons between countries. The
collaborative multicentre study that forms the basis for this book helps to provide an
epidemiological picture of attempted suicide in Europe.<P>
This book presents the results of the first phase of the study, which were released at the
Conference on Attempted Suicide in Europe held in the Netherlands in 1993. It also
includes the invited lectures given at the conference.<P>
The monitoring of recent trends in the epidemiology of attempted suicide presented here
will enable the identification of sociodemographic risk factors. Hopefully, this book will
encourage the establishment of effective services for preventing and treating this
behaviour.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Edinburgh University
Press</H2>

<H3>Alcohol &amp  drugs</H3>

<H4>Research &amp  policy</H4>

Edited by Martin Plant, Cees Goos, Wolfram Keup and Esa sterberg<P>
<P>
1990, 185 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 7486 0113 9<BR>
 30.- sterling<P>
<P>
Tackles two of the biggest and most vexing health problems in Europe. The contributors
to this book examine the key practical aspects in the use and misuse of alcohol and illicit
drugs. They discuss survey methods and current sources of data from different parts of
Europe and analyse their limitations. The book also gives recommendations to improve
research and policy related to alcohol and drug problems and the spread of HIV infection
and AIDS among intravenous drug users.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Editions Ecole nationale de
la sant publique, Rennes</H2>

<H3>Villes et sant</H3>

1990, 250 pages [F]<BR>
ISBN 28592470.3<BR>
FF 170.-<P>

Outlines the principles of the WHO Healthy Cities project, which began in 1986. The
book focuses on the action taken by participating cities in Canada, such as Quebec, and
Europe, such as Lige and Lisbon, to put these principles into action. <P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Edition Sigma</H2>

<H3>Unemployment, poverty and quality of working
life</H3>

<H4>Some European experiences</H4>

Edited by Bengt Starrin, Per-Gunnar Svensson and Helmut Wintersberger<P>

1989, 366 pages<BR>
ISBN 3 924859 74 4<BR>
DM 24.-<P>

Provides a wide range of information from 11 European countries on the health
implications of unemployment, poverty and quality of working life. Some of the topics
carefully dealt with are the submerged economy, coping and adaptation strategies, health
effects of factory closure, and psychological and social interventions. Policy implications
are discussed, and recommendations to European countries are made based on available
data. <P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Elsevier Science
Publishers</H2>
<H3>Environmental and health impact assessment of
development projects</H3>
<H4>A handbook for practitioners</H4>

Edited by Robert G.H. Turnbull<BR>
1992, 282 pages<BR>
ISBN 1 85166 597 8<BR>
 69.- sterling<P>

The health impact of economic development projects and policy is often a secondary
consequence of other environmental effects. The worldwide development of
environmental impact assessment procedures has provided a way to include and assess
the health impacts of the same development projects. This book introduces the twin
concepts of environmental impact assessment and health impact assessment, and the
related concept of risk assessment and management, describes the development of
modern toxicology as a multidisciplinary science, explores the uses of data bases and
information sources, and identifies future research needs in the field. It then provides
various case studies as examples. It will be useful to all professionals involved in
planning or implementing development projects. It will be particularly relevant to those
who have had little experience in integrating human health considerations into such
projects. It will be of special value in addressing the needs of the countries of central and
eastern Europe.
<HR>
<h2>Guiding principles for the use of biological markers in the
assessment of human exposure to environmental factors -
an integrative approach of epidemiology and
toxicology</h2>

Edited by M. Younes, J.C. Larsen and M. Krzyzanowski<P>

Special issue of <U>Toxicology,</U> 101 (1,2): 1-124 (1995) <BR>
ISSN 0300-483X<BR>
IR98.-<P>

Biological markers can improve the assessment of exposure to environmental factors.
This special issue reviews the available biomarker-based methods of exposure assessment
to carcinogens and non-carcinogens, in terms of their validity, their applicability to
exposure assessment and/or risk evaluation and the feasibility of their application in
population studies. Written by both toxicologists and epidemiologists, the articles take an
integrative approach to identify the needs for the further development of such methods, to
define criteria for the validation of biological markers for use in population studies, and
to draw up guiding principles for their application. 
<HR>
<h2>Methodology for assessment of exposure to environmental
factors in application to epidemiological studies</h2>

Edited by M. Krzyzanowski, E. Lebret and M. Younes<P>
Special issue of <U>The Science of the total environment</U>, 168 (2): 91-194
(1995)<BR>
ISSN 0048-9697<BR>
Dfl. 100.-<P>

Any study of the health effects of environmental factors should include the assessment of
exposure. Many indicators of exposure are crude, but rapid progress is being made in
their development. This special issue reviews the many exposure assessment methods
available, with emphasis on measurements performed in the environment and indirect
methods. The articles explore ways of validating such methods, identify available
methods that can be thus validated, and suggest areas for further development.
<HR>
<H2>Published by FADL Publishers</H2>
<H3>Promoting health in the urban context</H3>
By Trevor Hancock and Leonard Duhl<P>

WHO Healthy Cities Papers No. 1<BR>
1988, 54 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7437 228 9<BR>
Dkr 49.50<P>

A preliminary synthesis of some of the literature pertaining to health in the urban setting.
This book is aimed at stimulating informed debate on the relationship between health and
the urban setting.<P>
<HR>
<H3>A guide to assessing healthy cities</H3>

WHO Healthy Cities Papers No. 3<BR>
1988, 42 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7437 232 7<BR>
Dkr 49.50<P>

What is a healthy city? This book, which focuses on the WHO Healthy Cities project,
helps its partners in the project to answer this question. Chapters cover assessing the
Healthy Cities project, assessing the components of the project, how the city sees things,
and context and analysis. 
<HR>
<H3>The new public health in an urban context: paradoxes
and solutions</H3>

WHO Healthy Cities Papers No. 4<BR>
1989, 157 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7749 006 1<BR>
Dkr 49.50<P>

A series of chapters stemming originally from a 1987 conference but with extensive
revision. <P>
<HR>
<H3>Good planets are hard to find</H3>

By Ilona Kickbusch<BR>
WHO Healthy Cities Papers No. 5<BR>
1989, 31 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7749 020 7<BR>
Dkr 49.50<P>

Aimed at stimulating discussion on an ecological public health. In doing so, it is intended
to help widen the theoretical and conceptual base of the WHO Healthy Cities project.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Rehabilitation following chemical accidents</H3>
A guide for public officials<P>
Environmental Health Series No. 33<BR>
1989, 37 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7437 250 5<BR>
Dkr 45.-<P>

Provides decision-makers and managers with an overview of the entire rehabilitation
process to ensure a comprehensive approach to the problem and to facilitate mobilization
of the necessary resources, including expertise. This book is based on technical studies
<P>
and publications commissioned as part of the Regional Office's programme on disaster
preparedness. Chapters cover: organizational framework; establishment of rehabilitation
needs and objectives; post-emergency health care; post-emergency social, economic and
psychological care; rehabilitation of the environment; environmental monitoring;
feedback and adjustment; information storage and retrieval; and international
cooperation.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Levels of PCBs, PCDDs, and PCDFs in breast
milk</H3>
<H4>Results of WHO-coordinated interlaboratory quality control
studies and analytical field studies</H4>

Edited by Erkki J. Yrjnheikki<BR>
Environmental Health Series No. 34<BR>
1989, 90 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7437 254 8<BR>
Dkr 80.-<P>

What is the potential health risk to infants associated with exposure to these chemicals
through breastfeeding? To help answer this question, data are needed that are comparable
and reliable. This book presents the analytical results from interlaboratory quality control
studies and analytical field studies that take a long step in this direction. Conclusions
regarding risk assessment are also given.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Guidelines for iodine prophylaxis following nuclear
accidents</H3>

Environmental Health Series No. 35<BR>
1989, 38 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7749 016 9<BR>
Dkr 45.-<P>

Provides authoritative and practical guidance on all aspects of iodine prophylaxis in
relation to nuclear accidents. Specific exposed population groups are covered: pregnant
women and fetuses; neonates; lactating mothers; infants, children and adolescents;
younger adults; and older adults. The logistics of stable iodine administration are detailed.
The rationale underlying the guidelines is also included. This book should prove useful to
national and local authorities and to other organizations preparing contingency plans for
all types of nuclear emergency. <P>
<HR>
<H3>Levels of PCBs, PCDDs, and PCDFs in human milk
and blood</H3>
<H4>Second round of quality control studies</H4>

Edited by Erkki J. Yrjnheikki<BR>
Environmental Health Series No. 37<BR>
1991, 75 pages<BR>
ISBN 87 7749 063 0<BR>
Dkr 75.-<P>

That PCBs, PCDDs and PCDFs are present in human milk and blood is well known, but
the significance of their adverse health effects still needs to be established. A basic
requirement for this is the gathering and analysis of data that are reliable and comparable.
Quality control procedures are needed to ensure that such data are available. The
analytical results presented in this book are an important step in that direction. This
second round, in which 14 countries participated, is part of an ongoing multinational
study. This book describes the study design, analytical considerations, statistical analysis,
and criteria for the qualification of laboratories to determine concentrations of these
chemicals.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Franco Angeli</H2>
<H3>Health manpower education for health for all: issues
to be considered</H3>
<H4>Proceedings of a consultation held in Venice (December 4 to
8, 1989) </H4>
Edited by J.P. Menu and M. Garcia-Barbero<P>

1991, 153 pages<BR>
ISBN 88 204 6880 8<BR>
L. 20 000<P>

Health for all cannot be achieved if health personnel do not have the appropriate
education to carry it out. This publication reports on the highlights of an international
consultation held to define an educational policy for all European health professionals
who wish to become an active force in pursuing the targets of health for all. The basic
elements of this policy are identified as: training in teamwork, multiprofessional and
interdisciplinary cooperation, continuing education, a problem-solving approach and
community involvement in health problems. Health personnel will also have to shift from
its present, essentially disease-oriented attitude to a health-promotive, disease-preventive
attitude. While applying in particular to all categories of health worker, this report is
addressed to everyone involved, directly or indirectly, in health care systems and hence
the strategy of health for all.
