<HR>
<H2>Published by Kluwer</H2>
<H3>The rights of patients in Europe</H3>
<H4>A comparative study</H4>
Edited by Henk Leenen, Sjef Gevers and Genevive Pinet<P>

1993, 189 pages<BR>
ISBN 90 6544 671 0<BR>
Dfl.108.-/US $60.-<P>

This book is based on the results of a study on patients' rights in the Member States of the
WHO European Region. Topics included in the discussion are informed consent, access
to patients' medical records, privacy and the confidentiality of data, minors' rights, mental
patients' rights, complaints procedures, ethics committees, the rights of incompetent
adults, and civil, penal, administrative and disciplinary law in health care. The book also
covers the mechanisms for the protection and enforcement of these rights. A comparative
approach is used, when studying the rules of the various countries, to demonstrate present
and future trends. The authors also highlight, analyse and discuss the response of
legislation on the development of patients' rights. This book is ideal for universities,
lawyers, doctors, health authorities, private and public health care organizations and
international organizations.
<HR>
<H2>Promotion of the rights of patients in
Europe</H2>

1995, 139 pages<BR>
ISBN 90 411 01 004<BR>
Dfl. 95.-<P>

The previous book showed that, whatever the health care system, more and more
countries share the same principles for the rights of patients. WHO followed this up with
a consultation in 1994 to harness this growing movement and help countries develop
clear policies on patients rights, by defining the principles of patients rights and placing
them in a common European framework for action. The resulting publication contains the
deliberations of those who took part, touching on such issues as information and consent,
confidentiality and privacy, care and treatment, and patients rights within the context of
the health care system. It also looks at the roles of the health professional and the patient
as consumer. Finally it looks ahead to the strategy to promote patients rights, and
includes the Declaration on the Promotion of Patients Rights, including the Principles.

<HR>
<h2>The added value of geographical information systems in
public and environmental health</h2>

By Marion J.C. de Lepper, Henk J. Scholten and Richard M. Stern<P>

The GeoJournal Library, volume 24<BR>
1995, 355 pages<BR>
ISBN 0-7923-1887-0<BR>
Dfl. 230.-/US $ 139.-/ 92.-sterling<P>

This book is one of the first to introduce the potential of the new and rapidly developing
GIS technology in public and environmental health. It brings together a balanced sample
of written work that covers important aspects of the principles involved in GIS as well as
demonstrates the opportunities that GIS can offer to research and planning in public and
environmental health. Its chapters focus on the demand and supply of spatial information
in public and environmental health. Some examples of current applications are provided,
followed by a discussion on the possibilities of spatial analysis for research and planning.
This book also addresses issues related to the implementation of GIS at both national and
international levels.<P>
The volume not only provides a very good introduction to the state of the art and
developments in the application of GIS in public and environmental health; it also serves
as a seedbed for future research efforts.<P>
This book is aimed at students and teachers of GIS as well as researchers, planners,
policy-makers and other professionals who wish to learn more about GIS and are
concerned with the application, implementation and use of GIS in public and
environmental health.
