<H2>Published by MTP Press</H2>
<H3>The effects of drug regulation</H3>
By Graham Dukes<P>

1985, 36 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 85200 879 1<BR>
 29.50 sterling<P>
<P>
Sets out to answer the question: what are the effects of the work of regulatory agencies on
the availability of drugs, on the pharmaceutical industry and on the health of individuals
in Europe? Based on a series of WHO studies, the book begins by putting the situation
today into a historical context, and goes on to discuss the repercussions of regulation for
the community, and presents an analysis of current knowledge and the plans and
prospects for future research. This book will be valuable to all those concerned with the
development, distribution and control of drugs.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Nuffield Institute for Health
Services Studies</H2>
<H3>New directions in managing health care</H3>
<H4>Proceedings and outcome of a working group on new
approaches to managing health services</H4>

Edited by R. Bengoa and D.J. Hunter<P>

1991, 145 pages<BR>
ISBN 1 871977 11 8<BR>
9.50 sterling<P>

Throughout the European Region, health care systems are becoming increasingly
concerned with cost containment and the efficient use of resources. This has led them all,
despite their manifest differences, to take a renewed interest in market principles as a
possible solution. A WHO working group met to review the situation in Germany,
Hungary, Israel, the Netherlands, Poland, Spain, Sweden, the former USSR and the
United Kingdom - all countries that are either undergoing system-wide reform or
exploring new arrangements for health care organization and management. The
participants, all centrally involved in the health service reforms in their countries, gave an
insight into and assessment of the likely effect of the reforms and the implications they
would have for health care. This book contains a summary of the meeting, the country
reports and a review of past trends in health care and the new directions their
management should take. It is vital reading for all involved in or concerned about the
evolution of health care systems in the Region.
<HR>
<H2>Published by Oxford University
Press</H2>
<H3>Geographical and environmental epidemiology</H3>
<H4>Methods for small-area studies</H4>
Edited by P. Elliott, J. Cuzick, D. English and R. Stern<P>

1996, 382 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 19 262235 8<BR>
 29.50 sterling<P>

The public is increasingly anxious about environmental pollution and its potential effects
on health. But traditional epidemiological techniques are ill-suited to detect purely local
effects, such as near certain industrial or nuclear power plants, of the kind that alarm the
public the most. An important new approach to this problem is the use of small-area
studies, in which health and environmental exposure data are analysed with much finer
geographical resolution than ever before. This book is the first to summarize the new
developments in data availability, methodology, and the execution of small-area health
studies. It introduces geographical and small-area studies, summarizes the data
requirements for such studies, reviews the statistical methodology and identifies areas for
future work in geographical correlation studies and other concerns, gives a historical
perspective of environmental epidemiology and guidelines for investigating and
interpreting disease clusters, and provides some examples of small-area and geographical
correlation studies. This book should be of interest to practising epidemiologists,
geographers, environmentalists, statisticians, toxicologists and public health physicians
concerned with the impact of environmental exposure on the health of the population. It
should also be read by students of various disciplines associated with environmental
epidemiology and environmental science, as well as by health-policy makers, health
economists, politicians in the fields of environment and health, and informed lay
people.
<HR>
<H3>Health behaviour research and health
promotion</H3>
Edited by Robert Anderson<P>

1988, 286 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 19 261600 5<BR>
 30.- sterling<P>

Sets education and individual action - still important components of health promotion
programmes and of health-related behaviour - within the broader context of causation and
intervention. As this book points out, this approach has exciting implications for research,
which must now encompass all aspects of the structures and institutions of society. While
the volume rightly discusses definitions and terminology, it lays more emphasis on
theory, concepts and policy. Comprising contributions by experts in the field, this book
marks an important step towards setting research priorities and developing a fundamental
programme of research and action.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Alcohol policy and the public good</H2>
<P>
By Griffith Edwards et al.<P>

1994, 226 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 19 262561 Pbk <BR>
ISBN 0 19 262562 Hbk<BR>
 14.95 sterling<P>

Alcohol contributes to multiple and costly problems, affecting individual and family
health, welfare, employment and crime. Too often this cost and suffering have been
viewed as intractable. <P>
The authors boldly argue that such pessimism is unjustified, and that there is ample
evidence on which to identify a rational basis for effective public health policies in this
arena. Critical analysis is directed at a wide rage of policy choices including pricing,
ecological measures, public education, primary care and action on drunk driving.
Drinking problems, the authors conclude, are not carried by an uncontrollable
tide.
<HR>
<H2>Published by Pergamon Press</H2>
<H3>Iodine prophylaxis following nuclear accidents</H3>
Edited by E. Rubery and E. Smales<P>

1990, 182 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 08 037496 4<BR>
 30.- sterling<P>

What is the correct dosage of iodine for protecting people, especially pregnant women
and the fetus, following a nuclear accident? This volume authoritatively answers that
question. It presents the papers that formed the basis for the development of guidelines on
iodine prophylaxis issued by the WHO Regional Office for Europe. Papers cover the
normal function of the thyroid and the responses to iodine, the theoretical basis for stable
iodine prophylaxis, risks and benefits of stable iodine prophylaxis, and the indications for
the use of stable iodine. <P>
