<HR>
<H2>Published by SOGESS</H2>
<H3>WHO Healthy Cities project</H3>
<H4>A project becomes a movement</H4>
Edited by Agis D. Tsouros<P>

1990, 80 pages<BR>
ISBN 88 85393 01 2<BR>
US $15.-<P>

Evaluates the progress made in just four years, from 1987 to 1990, by the Healthy Cities
project, an innovative approach to promoting health and improving the urban
environment. With its network of 30 cities, the project now touches more than 18 million
people in 18 European countries.<P>
After sketching out the characteristics of a healthy city, the book outlines the underlying
strategy of the Healthy Cities project and the major events that helped convert its ideas
into action. A review of progress made in the cities focuses on the factors that influence
development, such as city size and economic differences, and the keystones for success,
such as effective committees, strong community support, sound project administration
and managerial and political accountability. The book then describes the action taken
locally by cities in a wide range of areas, such as helping the disadvantaged, greening the
city, involving children in community life and raising consumer awareness of
nutrition.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by E &amp  F Spon</H2>
<H3>Healthy housing: a practical guide</H3>
By Ray Ranson<P>

1991, 292 pages<BR>
ISBN 0 419 15400 0<BR>
 18.99 sterling<P>

The objective of this guide is to encourage administrations to formulate a sound housing
policy to solve basic health-related housing problems and to meet WHO's objective of
healthy housing for all. Many technical, social, planning and policy factors relating to
housing may affect people's physical and mental health and social wellbeing. These
factors can be expressed in terms of basic human requirements which can, accordingly, be
incorporated into housing standards, policies and goals of attainment relevant to an
individual country's needs, resources and priorities. No universal interpretation of healthy
housing is possible, but this guide outlines the typical requirements that can form the
necessary basis.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Published by Springer-Verlag</H2>

<H3>Baseline evaluation</H3>

<H4>CINDI: countrywide integrated noncommunicable diseases
intervention programme</H4>

Edited by W. Morgenstern, M.S. Tsechkovski, E. Nssel and G. Schettler<P>

1991, 54 pages<BR>
ISBN 3 540 54646 4<P>

Twelve European countries, Canada and Israel participate in the CINDI programme. This
book describes the baseline situation in these countries before the start of the programme.
Trends in premature mortality from some major noncommunicable diseases are given, as
well as the prevalence of risk factors for these diseases in the population (such as high
blood cholesterol, high blood pressure, overweight and smoking). The results stress the
necessity of a countrywide integrated approach:  noncommunicable diseases account for
two thirds of premature deaths in the CINDI countries, and about 70% of the adult
population is at risk. This report follows on from the CINDI Protocol and guidelines and
should enable the CINDI countries to assess the value of the approaches and interventions
recommended in them.
