<HR>
<H2>Published by Styx</H2>
<H3>Drugs and money</H3>
<H5>The problem of cost containment</H5>

By F.M. Haaijer-Ruskamp and M.N.G. Dukes<P>

Sixth edition<BR>
1991, 70 pages<BR>
ISBN 90 72371 21 6<BR>
Dfl. 32.80<P>

With the rising cost of medical care coupled with a slowdown in the growth of the
western economy, the money spent on prescribed drugs has become a matter of violent
controversy. The need for economy in health care is clear; what is contested however is
the extent to which it is wise to attempt to save expenditure on drugs, rather than on other
services. If the flow of money is reduced, will this put patient care at risk? Will the
research effort or the return on investment in the pharmaceutical industry be endangered?
Other questions concern the way in which money can be saved:  how can wastage be
reduced, how can prescribers be encouraged to use medicines more critically, and how is
one to determine what constitutes a fair price for a research-based drug?<P>
Answers to such questions as these too often come only from those whose interests are at
stake; because those interests differ, so do the answers which are given ... and the
controversy continues.<P>
Since 1984, a team set up by the WHO Regional Office for Europe and its collaborating
centre at the University of Groningen has provided regular studies of these vexed matters,
designed to provide policy-makers, industry and all those involved in patient care with
concrete and documented evidence on where the truth lies. Much of the truth that emerges
is distilled from the many attempts that have been made in various countries to control
pharmaceutical expenditure - sometimes successfully, yet more often to no effect and
sometimes doing more harm than good. With the present sixth edition, Drugs and money
again provides a compact and updated guide to these vital issues.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Use and regulation of vitamin and mineral
supplements</H3>
<H4>A study with policy recommendations</H4>

Edited by Jaap Schrijver, Elisabet Helsing, Graham Dukes and ke Bruce<P>

1993, 102 pages<BR>
ISBN 90 72371 59 3<P>

Vitamins and minerals are an important part of the diet of anyone keen to maintain their
health. Most countries recommend similar daily intake levels of these substances. Yet the
sales of such products to supplement the diet varies widely from country to country and
many people regularly ingest vastly more vitamins than they need. This book is an
attempt to identify the extent of overconsumption, and to help health personnel and the
public learn when and how vitamins and minerals should be used correctly. It reviews
existing policies towards minerals and vitamins, identifies the background data on such
micronutrients and their supply in the diet, examines the current patterns of their use as
supplements to the diet, discusses the possible indications for supplements in specific
population subgroups, describes the preparation and content of the various products on
the market, and makes recommendations for policy, use, regulation and surveillance. This
review should be read by policy-makers, regulatory bodies and the health professions.<P>
<HR>
