<HR>
<H3>Towards a theory of health promotion</H3>

<H4>A logical analysis</H4>

By Lennart Nordenfelt<P>

Health Service Studies 5<BR>
1989, 104 pages<BR>
ISBN 91 7870 488 X<BR>
ISSN 1100 6021<BR>
US $25.-<P>

A major part of the programme of WHO's European Regional Office is directed towards
lifestyles conducive to health and the development of a healthy environment. Given the
broadness of the issue of health promotion and its potential for conflict, it is important to
continue discussing and analysing its philosophical base. This is one philosopher's
analysis of and attempt to develop a theory of health promotion.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Health care systems at the crossroads</H3>

<H3>The Swedish health care system in an international
perspective</H3>

Edited by Johannes Vang and Gunnar Wennstrm
<P>
Health Service Studies 6<BR>
1991, 79 pages<BR>
ISBN 91 7870 840 0<BR>
ISSN 1100 6021<BR>
US $25.-<P>

In the past, the Swedish model has often been seen or referred to as a paragon for health
care systems in welfare states. Lately, however, the Swedes have started to complain
about their health care system.<P>
Through its Ministry of Health and Social Affairs and the National Board of Health and
Welfare, the Swedish government, in collaboration with the Swedish Federation of
County Councils, has initiated a study of the structure, financing and organization of the
Swedish health care system - a study entitled Crossroads. This study is intended to
evaluate the present health care structure in the light of criticism and the problems
associated with the rising costs of caring for an aging population in times of contracting
economy. The study, which is directed towards the macrostructural level, will hopefully
uncover and delineate some of the critical issues in the Swedish health care system.<P>
This booklet constitutes the proceedings of a joint WHO/Swedish seminar in convened in
June 1990 to provide a forum for an international appraisal of Swedens health and
medical services, making special reference to international developments and the WHO
health for all strategy..

<hr>
