<TITLE>European Centre for Environment and Health</TITLE>
<body background="../cbcbg01.gif">


<img src="abouhead.gif">
<br>

<a href="../Welcome.html"><img src="../homeknap.gif"></A>
<a href="about.htm"><img src="../sectknap.gif"></A>
<a href="offices.htm"><img src="../prevknap.gif"></A>
<a href="bilt01.htm"><img src="../nextknap.gif"></A>


<H1 align=center>European Centre for Environment and Health</H1>


<hr>

As a direct outcome of the European Charter on Environment and Health, WHO/Europe has established the WHO European Centre for Environment and Health. Each location of the Centre has its own specific areas of skills and  expertise and implements technical cooperation projects in central and eastern Europe. The Centre is an integrated part of the Environment and Health Department.
<p>

<dl>
<dd><B><img src="../blueb01.gif"><A HREF="bilt01.htm"> The Bilthoven Operational Division</A></B> focuses on air pollution, toxicology and descriptive epidemiology. <p>

<B><img src="../blueb01.gif"><A HREF="rome01.htm"> The Rome Operational Division</A></B> concentrates on water and waste issues with international dimensions, food safety, radiation  protection and analytical epidemiology.<P> 

In addition, both the Bilthoven and Rome Divisions are developing a European environment and health information system.  <P>
<B><img src="../blueb01.gif"><a href="nancy01.htm"> The Nancy Project Office</B></A> tackles the problems of community, water, wastewater, waste management and urban development.


<hr>
<center>
<table>
<tr><td><img src="../whoblk.gif"></td><td>   WHO Regional Office for Europe<BR>
<font size=2>URL: http://www.who.dk/</font><BR>
<font size=2><i>Updated 24 July 1996 - jfr@who.dk</i></font></td></tr>
</table>


