<h1 align=center>Resolutions 1996</H1>
<hr>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R1</h3><BR>
04326/08346<BR>
9 September 1996
<H1>Report of the Regional Director<BR>
on the Work of WHO in the European Region<BR>
1994-1995</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having examined and reviewed the Regional Director's report
on the work of WHO in the European Region in 1994-1995 (document
EUR/RC46/2) and the related information document;
</UL>

<OL>
<LI>THANKS<B> </B>the Regional Director for his report;
<LI>EXPRESSES<B> </B>its appreciation of the work accomplished
by the Regional Office in the 1994-1995 biennium;
<LI>ASKS the Regional Director to take into account and reflect,
in particular in the development of the Organization's programmes
and in the future work of the Regional Office, the suggestions
made during the discussion.
</OL>

<HR>
<BR>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R2
</H3>



04816/08386<BR>
9 September 1996
<H1>Report of the Standing Committee<BR>
of the Regional Committee</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having considered the report of the Standing Committee of
the Regional Committee (documents EUR/RC46/3 and EUR/RC46/3 Add.1)
and the proposed action and recommendations contained therein;
</ul>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Standing Committee for its thorough work and commends
all members on their high level of commitment on behalf of the
Regional Committee;
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director and the staff of the Regional
Office for assisting the Standing Committee;
<LI>ENDORSES the conclusions and proposals of the Standing Committee,
as discussed in the Regional Committee;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to take action, as appropriate,
on the conclusions and proposals contained in the report of the
Standing Committee, with the modifications emerging from the discussions
held and the resolutions adopted by the Regional Committee at
its forty-sixth session.
</OL>


<HR>


<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R3
</H3>



08136/08426<BR>
10 September 1996
<H1>Health Care Reform and Reconstruction<BR>
in Bosnia and Herzegovina</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having considered the report by the Regional Director on health
care reconstruction in Bosnia and Herzegovina;
<LI>Noting WHO's active leadership as chair of the Sectoral Task
Force on Health, providing coordinated support to all concerned
with health development in the country;
<LI>Noting that WHO has worked both at the policy level, to sponsor
the establishment of national working groups for health programme
development, and at the field level to ensure that essential health
services are restored;
<LI>Noting that WHO has established relations with all entities
and that the aim is to have a health service infrastructure which
is economically, functionally and administratively rational, once
the political tension subsides and the state can function normally;
</UL>

<OL>
<LI>WELCOMES and APPRECIATES the presence and the work done by
WHO and its partners on health care reform and reconstruction
in Bosnia and Herzegovina;
<LI>URGES the Regional Director and his staff to continue to pursue
this work with vigour and determination;
<LI>ENCOURAGES Member States actively to support health care reform
and reconstruction with financial and staff resources.
</OL>



<HR>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R4</H3>



05766/08606<BR>
12 September 1996
<H1>Proposed Programme Budget for 1998-1999</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having reviewed the proposed programme budget for the biennium
1998-1999 (document EUR/RC46/5 Rev.1) and taken note of the comments
made in this respect by the Standing Committee of the Regional
Committee (document EUR/RC46/3) and by individual Member States
during the written consultation held between February and May
1996;
<LI>Emphasizing the critical role of the WHO regular programme
budget in initiating and promoting action towards the attainment
of health for all (HFA) in the 21st century;
<LI>Noting that, in the formulation of the programme budget proposals,
due consideration has been given to:
<UL>
<LI>the evaluation of the 1994-1995 programme;
<LI>guidance provided by regional and global governing bodies
on priority-setting and budgetary reform, <I>inter alia</I> in
the regional contribution to the Ninth General Programme of Work
covering the period 1996-2001 (document EUR/RC43/3) and in resolutions
EUR/RC45/R5 on programme reductions for 1996-1997, EUR/RC45/R6
on updating of the EUROHEALTH programme, and WHA46.35, WHA47.8,
WHA48.25 and EB97.R4 on budgetary reform, including the reorientation
of allocations; and
<LI>political and socioeconomic developments and trends in the
European Region;
</UL>

<LI>Having reviewed the preparation of regional programme budget
policies and drawing attention to the importance of making optimal
use of WHO's resources in support of national strategies for HFA
in the 21st century;
<LI>Reaffirming resolutions EUR/RC42/R6, EUR/RC43/R10, EUR/RC44/R9
and EUR/RC45/R10, which all call for more equitable distribution
of the regular budget between regions and headquarters in the
light of global and regional developments, and noting that the
question of regional allocations will again be on the agenda of
the Executive Board at its ninety-ninth session in January 1997;
</UL>

<OL>
<LI>WELCOMES the form of budget presentation and the continued
improvements to the clarity of presentation and understandability
of the programme budget and the inclusion of data on expenditure
in the preceding biennium;
<LI>ENDORSES the proposed programme budget for 1998-1999, which
is to be financed with regular funds (and funds from other sources,
to the extent that the latter become available);
<LI>RECOMMENDS the inclusion of the European Region's proposed
programme budget for 1998-1999 in the Director-General's programme
budget for the Organization for 1998-1999;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director, during preparation and implementation
of the regional programme, to take into account the views expressed
by the Regional Committee, and in particular:
<UL>
<LI>to continue to give high priority to supporting health for
all development in Member States and to intensifying support for
countries most in need;
<LI>to continue to ensure the transparent, efficient and economic
use of all available resources;
<LI>to continue to make efforts to raise voluntary donations;
</UL>


<LI>FURTHER REQUESTS the Regional Director to continue to make
every effort, together with the European members of the Executive
Board, to secure a more equitable allocation of resources from
the regular budget of the Organization to the European Region,
in accordance with the provisions of resolution EUR/RC45/R10 and
in view of the inadequate regular budget allocation to the European
Region.
</OL>

<HR>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R5</H3>


05936/08646<BR>
12 September 1996
<H1>Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having considered the Regional Director's report on transmissible
spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs) (document EUR/RC46/11), as
well as the report of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
(EUR/RC46/3) and the recommendations regarding TSEs contained
therein;
<LI>Taking account of the consultation organized by WHO with the
participation of the International Office of Epizootics (OIE)
on 14 and 16 May 1996;
<LI>Taking account of the European Union's surveillance system
and the recommendations of the OIE;
</UL>

<ol>
<li>ENDORSES the recommendations made by the Standing Committee,
to take immediate action regarding potentially foodborne TSEs;

<li>URGES Member States:
<OL>
<LI>to implement the public health protection measures outlined
at a consultation organized by WHO with the Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations and OIE on 2 and 3 April 1996;
<LI>to cooperate with the Regional Office in establishing appropriate
countrywide systems for the surveillance of Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease;
<LI>to support the Regional Office programme with voluntary contributions
when possible;
</OL>




<li>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to further strengthen the Regional Office's role in relation
to TSEs;
<LI>to establish an epidemiological surveillance system on the
incidence of human TSEs in all countries of the Region that would
be compatible with the system already established in the European
Union, and to report data to all Member States;
<LI>to allocate the necessary funds from the regular budget to
set up and manage such a system;
<LI>to alert Member States to any new preventive and/or curative
measures which might protect human health from the risk of TSEs
in the Region (including measures stemming from the findings of
recent research);
<LI>to report back to the Regional Committee at its forty-seventh
session.
</OL>

</ol>
<hr>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R6
</H3>



05756/08686<BR>
12 September 1996
<H1>Pharmaceuticals: Present Developments and Future Challenges
</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having considered the report of the Regional Director on pharmaceuticals
in the European Region (EUR/RC46/12);
<LI>Recognizing the important role that pharmaceuticals play in
health care;
<LI>Aware of the need to evaluate carefully the outcomes that
the use of pharmaceuticals have on the health situation;
<LI>Taking account of the establishment of the European Agency
for the Evaluation of Medicinal Products (EMEA) by the European
Union;
<LI>Aware of the direct support that the Regional Office has provided
to countries, and especially to those in central and eastern Europe
and the newly independent states (CCEE/NIS) for pharmaceutical
sector reform and in humanitarian relief operations;
<LI>Concerned about the persistent irrational use of drugs and
the existing financial constraints that jeopardize access to needed
medicines for large segments of the population in several Member
States;
<LI>Recalling World Health Assembly resolutions on the revised
drug strategy (WHA49.14, WHA47.11, WHA47.13 and WHA47.17), the
WHO ethical criteria for medicinal drug promotion (WHA47.16) and
the role of the pharmacist (WHA47.12);
</UL>



<OL>
<LI>URGES Member States:

<OL>
<LI>to commit themselves to drawing up drug policies that provide
access for the whole population to needed medicines at an affordable
cost to the society and the individual;
<LI>to continue to strengthen the regulation and quality assurance
of pharmaceuticals as appropriate, including control of their
marketing, and of spontaneous and intensive monitoring of adverse
drug reactions;
<LI>to apply the interagency Guidelines for Drug Donations;
<LI>to carefully evaluate the implementation of policies on the
appropriate use of drugs and on cost-containment with regard to
their effectiveness and outcomes;
<LI>to evaluate the roles that the public and private sectors
play with regard to pharmaceuticals, taking into account the responsibilities
that the state has for guaranteeing access to safe and effective
medicines for the whole population at a sustainable cost to society;
<LI>to mobilize financial and human resources to assist the work
of the regional programme in supporting pharmaceutical sector
reform in Member States;
</OL>




<LI>APPEALS to those involved in the production and sale of drugs,
as well as health personnel involved in their presentation, to
use ethical criteria as appropriate to their spheres of competence,
activity and responsibility;

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to support Member States in the design, implementation and
monitoring of effective national policies and programmes in the
field of pharmaceuticals;
<LI>to continue and strengthen direct support to CCEE and NIS
for pharmaceutical sector reform;
<LI>to assist in the coordination of pharmaceutical supplies and
policies in humanitarian relief operations;
<LI>to intensify intercountry collaboration on promoting the appropriate
use of medicines and on evaluating health outcomes from the use
of medicines;
<LI>to stimulate international collaboration and exchange of information
and experiences in the field of drug regulation and quality assurance;
<LI>to encourage the appropriate training of pharmacists and the
further development of their professional role as providers of
drug information and counsellors on health promotion and disease
prevention.
</OL>

</OL>



<HR>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R7
</H3>



08296/08726<BR>
12 September 1996
<H1>New, emerging and re-emerging communicable diseases, including
malaria</H1>


The Regional Committee,<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Noting with concern the recent emergence or re-emergence of
large epidemics of communicable diseases in many eastern countries
of the European Region, and particularly the rise in syphilis
and other sexually transmitted diseases, the dramatic increase
in the numbers of HIV-infected people, the increase in tuberculosis
incidence and mortality, malaria epidemics in parts of the Region,
and the occurrence of epidemics of food- and water-borne diseases;
<LI>Welcoming the intensive efforts made by the staff of the Organization
to elaborate and implement communicable disease prevention and
control programmes, particularly the diphtheria control and poliomyelitis
eradication programmes, the strengthening of immunization and
efforts to control cholera and tuberculosis in close cooperation
with Member States and international, governmental and nongovernmental
organizations;

<LI>Recalling resolution EUR/RC45/R6 on &quot;Updating of the
EUROHEALTH Programme&quot;, adopted by the Regional Committee
at its forty-fifth session, which recognizes that special priority
should be given by Member States and the Regional Organization
in the 1996-1997 biennium to the prevention and control of communicable
diseases;
<LI>Recalling also resolution WHA49.11 of the Forty-ninth World
Health Assembly on &quot;New, emerging and re-emerging infectious
diseases: special programme on malaria&quot;, by which regional
committees are urged to ensure that malaria control programmes
are vigorously pursued and that regional and subregional plans
of action are prepared;
</UL>

<ol>
<li>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<ol>
<LI>to take into account the current situation regarding new,
emerging and re-emerging communicable diseases including malaria
and, based on this, to update the plan of action, including training,
for communicable disease control as part of the EUROHEALTH programme
elaborated in response to resolution EUR/RC45/R6;
<LI>to strengthen cooperation with Member States, international,
governmental and nongovernmental organizations in the fight against
emerging and re-emerging communicable diseases including malaria,
taking into account the successful cooperation in diphtheria control
and poliomyelitis eradication efforts;
<LI>to strengthen cooperation with WHO headquarters and other
regional offices, regarding the implementation of resolution WHA49.11;
</ol>

<li>URGES Member States:
<OL>
<LI>to support this updated plan of action for the intensification
of communicable disease prevention and control by providing additional
voluntary donations in money or in kind and to assist the Regional
Director in raising additional resources from other organizations
and funding agencies;
<LI>to establish a systematic and active surveillance programme
and to reinforce training programmes on emerging and re-emerging
communicable diseases including malaria at country level;
</OL>




<li>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report back to the Regional
Committee at its forty-seventh session on the implementation of
this resolution.
</ol>
<hr>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R8
</H3>



04246/08766

<H1>Date and Place of Regular Sessions of the Regional Committee
in 1997 and 1998</H1>


The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Having reviewed the decision taken at its forty-fifth session,
as expressed in resolution EUR/RC45/R9:
</UL>

<OL>
<LI>CONFIRMS that the forty-seventh session, by invitation of
the Government of Turkey, shall be held in Istanbul, Turkey, from
15 to 19 September 1997;
<LI>DECIDES that the forty-eighth session shall be held at the
Regional Office for Europe in Copenhagen from 14 to 18 September
1998.
</OL>


<HR>

<H3>Resolution EUR/RC46/R9
</H3>



05266/08816<BR>
13 September 1996

<H1>Third evaluation of progress towards
health for all in the European Region of
WHO (1996-1997)
</H1>
The Regional Committee,
<UL>
<LI>Recalling resolution WHA39.7 which <I>inter alia</I> recommends
a triennial periodicity for the assessment of progress towards
health for all (HFA);
<LI>Bearing in mind resolution EUR/RC4l/R5 which endorses the
updated regional HFA targets and indicators;
<LI>Reaffirming resolution EUR/RC43/R8 which urges Member States
to use HFA indicators and data in producing national HFA-oriented
public health reports and to develop core HFA data sets for their
countries;

<LI>Having considered the document <I>Third evaluation of progress
towards health for all in the European Region of WHO (1996-1997)</I>
(EUR/RC46/9) and the corresponding framework document (EUR/RC46/Inf.Doc./2);


</UL>



<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director, the advisory group and the experts
involved for their valuable contributions to the preparation of
these documents;
<LI>ENDORSES the evaluation framework and procedure, and more
specifically the proposed main changes in the third HFA evaluation
(1996-1997), respecting differences in health care systems in
Member States and the different contents of the 38 targets;
<LI>RECOMMENDS that the third HFA evaluation should provide an
important input into renewal of the regional HFA strategy;
<LI>URGES Member States:
<OL>
<LI>to establish and to support consistently the appropriate mechanisms
to carry out efficiently the third HFA evaluation in their countries,
in accordance with the needs of health policy development at different
levels and with the proposed evaluation procedure;

<LI>to provide the Regional Director with relevant information
in so far as possible on the progress and experience in implementing
their HFA-oriented strategies, including the review of statistical
data in accordance with the global and regional HFA indicators,
taking into account internationally accepted standards;
<LI>to seek Regional Office support as necessary for the implementation
of these activities;
<LI>to use the HFA evaluation exercise to promote, as appropriate,
HFA-oriented public health reporting at all levels in countries
and to distribute their HFA evaluation conclusions widely at all
levels within their own countries;
<LI>to continue to support the Regional Office in its efforts
to improve the use and international comparability of HFA data
and to try to work towards establishing countrywide integrated
databases of health statistics as an essential practical step
in this direction;
<LI>to promote greater interaction in the Region between the activities
of WHO and those of all other bodies concerned, including NGOs,
in order to stimulate common efforts for attaining HFA;
</OL>

<li>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to transmit all relevant evaluation documents, together with
the report of the Regional Committee, to the Director-General
as a European regional contribution to evaluation of the implementation
of the global HFA strategy;
<LI>to set up a group of national experts and representatives
of other bodies active in the field, with the task of evaluating
the present system of monitoring and drawing up proposals for
a lean and dynamic system in line with a renewed HFA strategy;
<LI>to report to the Regional Committee at its forty-seventh session
on the main findings, conclusions and implications of the third
evaluation of progress towards HFA in the European Region of WHO,
in accordance with the agreed evaluation procedure.
</OL>
</ol>
