<H1 align=center>Resolutions 1995</H1><HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R1</H2>
<H2>Membership of global advisory committees and 
other bodies</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having studied the recommendations of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
contained in document EUR/RC45/19 regarding procedures for selection of members of the Standing
Committee, the global advisory committees and the European Environment and Health Committee, and for
nominations for membership of the Executive Board;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>ADOPTS the following amendments to the Rules of Procedure of the Regional Committee:<BR>
(a)	in the first paragraph of Rule 14.2.1, replace the last sentence with the following sentence:<BR>
The Regional Director shall notify all Members of the Region prior to the start of the World Health
Assembly of the nominations so received and shall send to all Member States the curricula vitae of the
candidates proposed.<BR>
(b)	replace the second paragraph of Rule 14.2.1 with the following:<BR>
The Standing Committee, in consultation with the Executive President of the Regional Committee and the
Regional Director, shall seek consensus among countries nominating candidates.  In so doing the Standing
Committee shall seek reasonable geographical distribution of countries represented on the Standing
Committee and take into account the quality and experience of the individual candidates. Should it not be
possible to reach consensus, an election shall take place in accordance with Rules 38 to 46.<BR>
(c)	after Rule 14.2.6 insert:
<br>
<B>VI A.	ELECTION OF REPRESENTATIVES TO THE<BR>
EUROPEAN ENVIRONMENT AND HEALTH COMMITTEE </B><br>
<B>Rule 14. 3</B><br>
14.3.1	The Committee shall elect four representatives to the European Environment and Health
Committee (EEHC) established in accordance with the Helsinki Declaration of 22 June 1994. The
Committee shall, when electing the members of the EEHC, take into account the need to ensure
equitable geographical distribution, adequate representation of the interests of the Region, and an
opportunity for all Members of the Region to participate in the work of the EEHC as well as other
considerations relevant to maximizing the effectiveness of the work of the EEHC.<br>
14.3.2	Nominations for membership of the EEHC shall be made by Member States notifying the
Regional Director six months before the start of the Regional Committee session of their interest in
having a representative on the EEHC. All nominations shall be accompanied by curricula vitae, in
standard format, of the candidates proposed. The Regional Director shall notify all Members of the
Region prior to the start of the World Health Assembly of the nominations so received and shall send
to all Members the curricula vitae of the candidates proposed.<br>
14.3.3	The Standing Committee, in consultation with the Executive President of the Regional
Committee and the Regional Director, shall seek consensus among countries nominating candidates.
In so doing the Standing Committee shall seek reasonable geographical distribution of countries
represented on the EEHC and take into account the quality and experience of the individual
candidates.<br>
14.3.4	Should it not be possible to reach consensus an election shall take place in accordance 
with Rules 38 to 46.<p>
<li>DECIDES that:<br>
(a)	nominations from Member States wishing to designate a member of the Executive Board shall be
supported by a curriculum vitae, in standard format, and notified to the Regional Director six months
before the start of the Regional Committee session; the Regional Director shall notify all Members of
the Region prior to the start of the World Health Assembly of the nominations so received and shall
send to all Member States the curricula vitae of the candidates proposed;<br>
(b)	nominations from Member States interested in and eligible for membership of a global advisory
committee shall be supported by curricula vitae, in standard format, for each application for
membership of any committee; such nominations shall be notified to the Regional Director six
months before the start of the Regional Committee session; and the Regional Director shall notify all
Members of the Region prior to the start of the World Health Assembly of the nominations so
received and shall send to all Member States the curricula vitae of the candidates proposed;<br>
(c)	should it not be possible to reach consensus using the procedure as outlined in Rules 14.2.1 and 
14.3.3, then an election shall be held in accordance with Rules 3846.</ol>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R2</H2>
<h2>Report of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee</h2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having considered the report of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee (documents
EUR/RC45/2 and EUR/RC45/2 Add.1) and the proposed action and recommendations contained therein;
</UL>
<ol>
<LI>THANKS the Standing Committee for its thorough work and commends all members on their high
level of commitment on behalf of the Regional Committee;<P>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director and the staff of the Regional Office for assisting the Standing
Committee;<P>
<LI>ENDORSES the conclusions and actions proposed by the Standing Committee, as discussed in the
Regional Committee;<P>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to take action, as appropriate, on the conclusions and proposals
contained in the report of the Standing Committee, with the modifications emerging from resolutions
adopted by the Regional Committee at its forty-fifth session.
</ol>
<HR>
<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R3</H2>
<H3>Technical discussions at future sessions of the Regional
Committee</H3>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Noting the recommendation of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee on technical
discussions at future sessions of the Regional Committee;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>DECIDES to rescind its request to the Regional Director (as contained in resolution EUR/RC44/R15)
<LI>to make arrangements for technical discussions at its forty-sixth session in 1996;<P>
<LI>FURTHER DECIDES that, as from the forty-sixth session onwards, technical discussions will be
replaced by informal briefings and discussions on the programmes of the Regional Office.
</OL>

<HR>
<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R4</H2>
<H2>European Health Policy Conference:
Opportunities for the Future</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Bearing in mind resolutions EUR/RC30/R8 and EUR/RC34/R5 endorsing the regional health for all
(HFA) strategy and targets and EUR/RC41/R5 updating the regional HFA targets;
<LI>Recognizing the urgency of the health challenges facing Europe;
<LI>Noting with interest fresh initiatives in countries to spread the HFA approach from country to
subnational and local levels, and the evident validity and relevance of this approach in the new Europe;
<LI>Strongly agreeing that policies for health must be based on principles of equity and participation in
decision-making;
<LI>Affirming that intersectoral policies and strategies for health must be shaped at country, subnational
and local levels as appropriate and must clearly define priorities and targets for improving health, by
promoting and facilitating healthy lifestyles, a healthy environment and accessible, acceptable and effective
health care;
<LI>Taking account of the fruitful discussions held and the Declaration adopted at the European Health
Policy Conference: Opportunities for the Future, organized by the WHO Regional Office for Europe in
collaboration with the Council of Europe and with the support of the European Commission, in
Copenhagen from 5 to 9 December 1994;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Office for its work in preparing the above conference in collaboration with the
Council of Europe and with the support of the European Commission;<p>
<LI>WELCOMES the Copenhagen Declaration adopted at the European Health Policy Conference;
<LI>URGES all countries to continue to assess their policies and strategies for health and to take the
necessary action to ensure that they are fully in line with the HFA approach;<p>
<LI>ENCOURAGES the use of national HFA policy frameworks in countries of central and eastern
Europe and the newly independent states to guide international organizations, investors and donors towards
addressing priority areas and concerns in their collaborative programmes;<p>
<LI>URGES all international and integrational organizations working in health and health-related sectors
that have not already done so to support the development of policies for health for all in countries.<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to:
<br>
(a)	increase the efforts to support Member States, and particularly the countries of central and
eastern Europe and newly independent states, in developing national policies and strategies
based on HFA principles at national, subnational and local levels, as appropriate;<br>
(b)	investigate innovative ways of promoting and facilitating the sharing of expertise and
knowledge, analysing experiences and strengthening problem-solving skills in countries.</ol>
<HR>






<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R5</H2>
<H2>Programme reductions for 1996-1997</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having considered the reports of the Regional Director contained in documents EUR/RC45/5 and
EUR/RC45/20;
<LI>Recalling its endorsement, at its forty-fourth session in September 1994, of the proposed programme
budget for the European Region for 19961997 (resolution EUR/RC44/R9);
<LI>Recalling the World Health Assembly appropriation resolution WHA48.32 and the subsequent
decision by the Director-General, which has resulted in a US $6.45 million reduction in the expected
programme budget for the European Region;
<LI>Noting that the European Region will be carrying a larger share of the budget reduction than would
have been the case if the withdrawal of funds had been proportionate to the projected inflation estimates for
1996-1997;
<LI>Concerned about the effects this budget reduction will have with regard to the services that the
Regional Office is able to give to European Member States in general, and to countries covered by the
EUROHEALTH programme in particular;
<LI>Concerned also about the effect this reduction will have on many Regional Office staff who have
served the Organization in a devoted manner for many years;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director and the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee (SCRC)
for their rapid and well balanced response to the World Health Assembly appropriation resolution;<P>
<LI>ENDORSES the Regional Directors proposals (as discussed in the Regional Committee) for
effecting a US $6.45 million reduction in the expected programme budget for 19961997 as endorsed by
the Regional Committee at its forty-fourth session;<P>
<LI>REQUESTS the SCRC, in consultation with the Regional Director, to develop proposals for a
medium-term strategy in the light of a realistic assessment of available resources, and in so doing:<BR>
	(a)	to review the programme areas (EUROHEALTH, Europe-wide and humanitarian assistance) and
their priorities as agreed by the Regional Committee at its forty-fourth session;<BR>
	(b)	to focus future programmes on areas where WHO has comparative advantage;<BR>
	(c)	to recommend any necessary changes to the developing role of the SCRC and its relationship to
the Organization as a whole; and<BR>
	(d)	to submit proposals to the Regional Committee at its forty-sixth session;<P>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to pursue his efforts to alleviate the plight of those members of
the staff who will be losing their employment with the Organization.</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R6</H2>
<H2>Updating of the EUROHEALTH
Programme</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Recalling its discussions and earlier resolutions on this subject (EUR/RC40/R7, EUR/RC41/R2,
EUR/RC42/R6, EUR/RC43/R10 and EUR/RC44/R10) and bearing in mind the fact that since 1991 a
significant amount of experience and knowledge has been acquired by the European Regional Organization
concerning the situation in EUROHEALTH countries, their needs and the strategies necessary to meet
them;
<LI>Having considered the updated version of the EUROHEALTH programme (document EUR/RC45/6),
which reflects the discussions and recommendations of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
(SCRC);
<LI>Acknowledging with appreciation the extensive work done within the programme in previous years in
spite of the shortfall in financial resources;
<LI>Noting that the steps taken by the European Regional Organization in implementing the programme
have already resulted in a gradual change of attitude in EUROHEALTH countries towards health
development;
<LI>Noting with satisfaction the continuing evaluation of the programme by the SCRC and the progress
made in EUROHEALTH countries;
<LI>Recognizing the importance of the EUROHEALTH programme as a major strategy for achieving the
first regional target for health for all and as a tool for focusing support on countries in greatest need;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>Strongly SUPPORTS the EUROHEALTH programme and its six medium-term priority areas
(communicable diseases, womens and childrens health, health policies, health care reform, environmental
health, and noncommunicable diseases and the promotion of better health);<p>
<LI>CONSIDERS that on a biennial basis the SCRC, in consultation with the Regional Director, should
set short-term objectives within all six priority areas, based on country needs;<p>
<LI>RECOGNIZES that the changing pattern of communicable diseases in the Region causes particular
concern in many countries and should therefore be given special priority by Member States and the
Regional Organization in the biennium 19961997;<p>
<LI>URGES Member States to make voluntary contributions available for 19961997, in money or in
kind, and to assist the Regional Director in raising additional resources from other organizations and
funding agencies to support in particular the special priority area of communicable diseases;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to discuss with Member States the nature and timing of their
voluntary donations before the start of the 19961997 biennium;<p>
<LI>Further REQUESTS the Regional Director to make a comprehensive evaluation of the
EUROHEALTH programme, including its Europe-wide component, for submission to the Regional
Committee at its forty-ninth session.
</OL>
<HR>







<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R7</H2>
<H2>The repercussions on public health of nuclear accidents and of
the Chernobyl accident</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having reviewed the report of the Regional Director on the public health repercussions of the
Chernobyl accident (document EUR/RC45/9);
<LI>Recalling resolutions EUR/RC36/R8 and EUR/RC37/R2 relating to nuclear accidents and public
health, approved by the Regional Committee at its thirty-sixth and thirty-seventh sessions, respectively;
<LI>Recalling also resolution WHA44.36 relating to the International Programme on the Health Effects of
the Chernobyl Accident adopted by the Forty-fourth World Health Assembly;
<LI>Taking into account the increased incidence of childhood thyroid cancer in areas affected by the
Chernobyl accident;
<LI>Recognizing the continuing fears of large numbers of people about the possible effects on their own
and their families health of the Chernobyl disaster;
<LI>Recognizing the efforts made by the affected countries to protect the health of their populations from
the effects of the disaster;
<LI>Aware of the need for greater scientific understanding of the long-term effects of radiation on health;
<LI>Cognizant of the risks of possible future accidents and their effects on public health in the Region;
<LI>Emphasizing the need for greatly improved harmonization of international efforts in relation to the
effects on public health of the Chernobyl disaster;
<LI>Commending the continuing work of the European Centre for Environment and Health in this field
and thanking the States which have already contributed to it;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>AUTHORIZES the Regional Director to continue his efforts to obtain greater support, including
financial contributions, for carrying out investigations into the health consequences of the Chernobyl
disaster;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to further strengthen the Regional Offices role in emergency
preparedness for radiation accidents and its capacity to respond to such accidents;<p>
<LI>AUTHORIZES the Regional Director to further strengthen WHOs emergency response activities in
the Region in the field of radiation accidents;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to draw the attention of Member States and the international
community to the need for assistance to countries with affected populations;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report periodically on progress in his annual reports;<p>
<LI>URGES Member States to support the efforts of the Regional Director in implementation of this
resolution.
</OL>
<HR>







