<DD>Professor J.-F. Girard (France)
<DT><I>Members:</I><P>
<DD>Dr Marta di Gennaro (Italy)
<DD>Dr L. de Carvalho Mago (Portugal)
<DD>Dr K.T. Tchamov (Bulgaria)
</DL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R9</H2>
<H3>Date and Place of Regular Sessions of the
Regional Committee in 1996 and 1997</H3>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having reviewed the decision taken at its forty-fourth session as expressed in resolution
EUR/RC44/R6:
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CONFIRMS that the forty-sixth session shall be held at the Regional Office for Europe in
Copenhagen from 9 to 13 September 1996;<p>
<LI>DECIDES that the forty-seventh session, by invitation of the Government of Turkey, shall be held in
Turkey from 15 to 19 September 1997.
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R10</H2>
<H2>Regional allocations under the Regular Budget</H2>

<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Having considered the report of the Regional Director in document EUR/RC45/5 which, <I>inter
alia</I>, outlined the discussion which took place during the ninety-sixth session of the Executive Board
on the subject of regional allocations, including the fact that the allocation under the Regular Budget to the
European Member States remains at 6% while European Member States collectively contribute over 45%
of the Organizations global budget;
<LI>Recalling Regional Committee resolution EUR/RC42/R6 which <I>inter alia</I> drew the attention
of the Director-General and the Executive Board to the urgent needs in the European Region, particularly
in central and eastern European countries, which call for a more adequate regional allocation from the
global budget of the Organization;
<LI>Recalling further Regional Committee resolution EUR/RC43/R10 which noted that the share of
resources allocated to the WHO regions as a whole was inadequate to take effective action on priority
health needs in the large number of countries requiring intensified cooperation in health, and therefore
recommended that members of the Executive Board, as well as representatives to the World Health
Assembly from the European Region, make an effort to improve the Regions share of global regular
budget resources commensurate with the needs of their Member States;
<LI>Noting also Regional Committee resolution EUR/RC44/R9 which requested the Director-General to
ask the Executive Board to review and analyse the methods of allocation and the actual distribution of
resources from the regular budget, and to report on options and make recommendations to the World
Health Assembly in 1995;
<LI>Continuing to be concerned that the present allocation of the regular budget to the European Region
has remained unchanged, with only minor variations due to exchange rate fluctuations, practically since the
inception of the Organization, notwithstanding;<BR>

(a)	the dramatic geopolitical changes that have taken place in Europe since the early 1990s
and which have led to an increase in the number of members from 31 to 50, several of whom are
facing serious deteriorations in the health situations of their populations due to the effects of war,
economic deterioration and social disruption;<BR>
(b)	the dramatic changes in epidemiology in a number of Member States with regard to
diphtheria, cholera, poliomyelitis and even noncommunicable diseases such as cardiovascular
diseases;<BR>
(c)	the fact that several Member States are now officially categorized by the World Bank as
least developed countries;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>REGRETS that, in spite of all of the above-mentioned deteriorations, the financial resources
remain unchanged, and that pressing health needs remain unmet in many parts of the European Region due
to the current inadequate provision of regular budget resources to the Regional Office;<p>
<LI>RECALLS the concern at several previous sessions of the Executive Board and the World Health
Assembly, most notably the ninety-fifth session of the Board in January 1995, and the view that a reduction
in central administrative costs could help free the necessary funds for a more equitable distribution of
global resources to regional levels;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to bring to the Director-Generals attention, as has already
been done at the current session, the Regional Committees firm conviction that the regular budget
allocation to the European Region needs to be increased, to reflect present realities in the Region;<p>
<LI>CALLS ON the members of the Executive Board from the European Region to raise this matter
during the ninety-seventh session of the Board in January 1996;<p>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report back to the Regional Committee at its forty-sixth
session on developments in implementation of this resolution.

</OL>
<HR>






<H2>Resolution EUR/RC45/R11</H2>
<H2>Process for updating the health policy for Europe</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>Recalling the recommendations of the Executive Board Working Group on the WHO Response to
Global Change and resolution EB92.R2;
<LI>Taking note of Executive Board resolution EB95.R5 and World Health Assembly resolution
WHA48.16 on the process for renewing the health for all (HFA) policy, objectives and targets and
adjusting the strategy in response to global change;
<LI>Bearing in mind resolution EUR/RC41/R5, whereby it approved the updated regional HFA targets
and indicators, including a regional plan of action, and resolutions EUR/RC43/R8 and EUR/RC44/R5
regarding the process for monitoring and evaluation of progress towards HFA;
<LI>Recognizing that the European HFA policy adapts global HFA policy principles to the specific
requirements of the Region;
<LI>Having considered document EUR/RC45/11 setting out the link between the regional action plan and
the global updating schedule;
<LI>Concerned that the process be kept simple and not unduly heavy and costly;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>WELCOMES the updating of the global HFA policy;<p>
<LI>ENDORSES the proposal to link the regional and global updating processes;<p>
<LI>URGES Member States to participate actively in any consultation processes;<p>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to convey to the Director-General its recommendation that:<BR>
(a)	in view of the importance of renewing the HFA policy for future decades, all Member
States be given the opportunity to give their views in a comprehensive, concrete and timely
manner and be continuously involved in the process of preparing the special event connected to
the World Health Assembly in 1998;<BR>
(b)	the global policy be updated at regular intervals; <BR>
(c)	the periodicity of the monitoring and evaluation of progress towards HFA, as well as of
the General Programme of Work, be reviewed to ensure the most cost-effective input into the
regular updating of the policy;<BR>
(d)	regional and global processes be realigned accordingly.
</OL>
