<H1 align=center>Resolutions 1994</H1>
<hr>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R1</H2><P>
<H2>Reports of the Regional Director on the work of WHO in the European Region 1992-1993
</H2><P>

<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>
<LI>	Having reviewed the reports on the work of WHO in the European Region in 19921993
in conjunction with EUR/RC44/Inf.Doc./1;<P>

<LI>	Welcoming the new structure of the Regional Director's report;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his reports;<P>

<LI>EXPRESSES its appreciation of the work accomplished by the Regional Office in the
19921993 biennium;<P>

<LI>ASKS the Regional Director to take into account, in the future work of the Regional
Office, the suggestions made during the discussion.<P>
</UL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R2</H2><P>
<H2>Additions and amendments to the rules of procedure of the Regional Committee and the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having studied the recommendations of its Standing Committee (as contained in
document EUR/RC44/3) regarding further changes to the Rules of Procedure of the Regional
Committee and the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee;<P>
</UL>


<OL>
	<LI>ADOPTS the following changes:
	<OL>
		<LI>(a) Rules of Procedure of the Regional Committee for Europe<P>
			<OL>
			<LI>(i) in Rules 5, 11, 17, 47.3, 47.6 and 48 after "him" wherever the word appears insert
<I>"or her"</I>;<P>

			<LI>(ii) in Rules 11, 15, 21, 25, 26, 47.2. 47.4, 47.10(b) and 47.10(c) after "he" wherever the
word appears insert <I>"or she"</I>;<P>

			<LI>(iii) in Rules 12, 23, 24, 26, 31 and 47.10(a) after "his" wherever the word appears insert
<I>"or her"</I>;<P>

			<LI>(iv) in Rule 10.3 after "not elected" delete "by the I-SCRC";<P>

			<LI>(v) in Rule 14.2.1 add a new second paragraph:<P>

<I>Should the Regional Committee be unable to reach a consensus on the persons to be
elected as members of the Standing Committee, the President, the Executive President
and the Deputy Executive President, in consultation with the Regional Director, may
propose a list of candidates from among nominations made in accordance with this
Rule who, in their view, would best fit the criteria for membership of the Standing
Committee;</I><P><I>
</I><P>

			<LI>(vi) in Rule 21 after "himself" insert <I>"or herself"</I>; and after "languages by"
			replace "an interpreter" by "interpreters"<I>;</I><P>

			<LI>(vii) in Rule 47.7 replace "Chairman" by <I>"President"</I>. <P>
</ol>
	<LI>(b) Rules of Procedure of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee<P>

			<OL>
			<LI>(i) in Rule 1 after "Europe" delete "and" (the first word in parenthesis);<P>

			<LI>(ii) in Rule 2.3 replace "on" by <I>"of"</I>;<P>

			<LI>(iii) in Rule 2 after paragraph 4 add:<P>

<I>"5.	Members may be accompanied by one alternate or adviser"</I> (the
remaining paragraphs in this Rule to be renumbered accordingly);<P>

			<LI>(iv) in Rule 14 after "he" insert <I>"or she"</I>;<P>

			<LI>(v) in Rule 16 after "his" insert <I>"or her".</I> <P>
			</OL>
</OL>
</ol>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R3</H2><P>
<H2>Increase in membership of the Executive Board
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having noted the report of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee, which
draws attention to the changes that have occurred in the European Region in recent years,
particularly relating to the increase in the number of WHO Member States affiliated to the
European Region, and the proposal to increase accordingly the membership of the Executive
Board to thirty-three members;</UL><P>
<OL>
<LI>RECOMMENDS an increase in the membership of the Executive Board to thirty-three
members, and a subsequent increase in members affiliated to the European Region to eight
members;<P>

<LI>RECOMMENDS to the Executive Board, and through it to the World Health Assembly,
to consider amending the Constitution with a view to increasing the membership of the
Executive Board accordingly.<P>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R4</H2><P>
<H2>Nomination of the Regional Director
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Considering Article 52 of the Constitution; and in accordance with Rule 47 of its Rules of
Procedure;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>NOMINATES Dr Jo Eirik Asvall as Regional Director for Europe; and<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Director-General to propose to the Executive Board the appointment of Dr
Jo Eirik Asvall for a further period of five years from <BR>
1 February 1995.<P>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R5</H3><P>
<H2>Strategy for attaining health for all by the year 2000
</H2>
<H2>Regional monitoring 1993-1994
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Recalling resolution WHA39.7, which <I>inter alia </I>recommends a triennial
periodicity for the assessment of progress towards the goal of health for all by the year 2000
(HFA), and resolution EUR/RC41/R9 reaffirming the request that the Regional Office further
develop its role as a European health information centre;<P>

<LI>	Bearing in mind resolution EUR/RC41/R5, whereby it approved the updated regional
HFA targets and indicators, and resolution EUR/RC43/R8, by which it endorsed the framework
and procedure for monitoring progress towards HFA in 19931994, and supporting international
collaboration with the aim of establishing a joint European health statistics centre;<P>

<LI>	Having considered the document containing a summary of the 19931994 report on
monitoring of progress towards HFA (document EUR/RC44/12);<P>

<LI>	Recognizing the need to make the regional HFA strategy and its implementation better
known to all those who play a role in the field of health;<P>

<LI>	Aware of the need to increase efforts to accelerate progress and to help those countries
most in need;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>EXPRESSES ITS APPRECIATION of the efforts made by Member States and WHO to
promote progress towards the goal of HFA at country and European levels and to assess this
progress;<P>

<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for the summary report on the 1993-1994 HFA
monitoring exercise;<P>

<LI>ENDORSES that document as the European contribution to the global report on
monitoring of progress towards HFA, once it has been updated to include all replies received
from countries as well as the views expressed by the Regional Committee;<P>

<LI>URGES Member States:<P>
<OL>
<LI>if they have not yet forwarded their contributions to the HFA monitoring exercise, to
provide WHO with the required information as soon as possible;<P>

<LI>to continue to promote the regular collection and analysis of relevant data on regional
and national HFA indicators and, if necessary, to set up appropriate structures and/or
mechanisms to carry out these tasks;<P>
</OL>


<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to forward the summary report on the 19931994 HFA monitoring exercise, updated as
provided for above, to the Director-General;<P>

<LI>in collaboration with the ministries of health of the Member States, to ensure wide
dissemination of the findings of the 19931994 HFA monitoring exercise within the
Region in order to improve knowledge of HFA and stimulate progress towards
attainment of that goal at European, country and local levels;<P>

<LI>to convey to the Director-General its recommendation that the present HFA monitoring
process should be continued and that an in-depth evaluation should be conducted both
by the Member States and by the Regional Office every six years, thereby making the
process coincide with the Organization's General Programme of Work.<P>

<LI>to further develop, in close coordination with WHO headquarters and the ministries of
health of the Member States, the establishment of mechanisms for the continuous
exchange of data with the main providers of data in countries, paying special attention
to relevance, quality and comparability;<P>

<LI>to continue efforts to strengthen collaboration with other intergovernmental
organizations, in particular EU and OECD, with the aim of ensuring the efficient and
economic use of resources.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2> Resolution EUR/RC44/R6</H2><P>
<H2>Date and place of the regular session of the Regional Committee in 1996 and change of date of the regular session in 1995
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having taken into consideration the report of the secretariat to the Standing Committee of
the Regional Committee on the need to change the dates of the forty-fifth session;<P>

<LI>	Recalling resolution EUR/RC43/R7;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>DECIDES that the forty-fifth session shall take place from 18 to 22 September 1995;<P>

<LI>DECIDES that the forty-sixth session shall be held at the Regional Office for Europe in
Copenhagen from 9 to 13 September 1996.<P>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R7</H2><P>
<H2>Report of the Regional Director to the Regional Committee on immunization and communicable disease control
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Noting the report of the Regional Director on immunization and communicable disease
control (document EUR/RC44/14);<P>

<LI>	Recalling resolutions EUR/RC41/R5 adopting the revised regional health for all (HFA)
targets, including target 5 on reducing communicable diseases, WHA46.33 endorsing the revised
plan of action for eradication of poliomyelitis by the year 2000, WHA42.32 underscoring the
importance of the elimination of neonatal tetanus, WHA45.17 recalling the goals set by the
World Summit for Children in 1990, and WHA46.36 endorsing strategies to control
tuberculosis;<P>

<LI>	Aware that:<P>
<uL>
<LI>the countries of the European Region have until recently achieved remarkable success
in the control of communicable diseases;<P>
<P>
<li>infectious diseases are still responsible for between 7% and 17% of deaths from all
causes in most countries of the Region and a higher proportion in many countries in
eastern and south-eastern Europe;<P>

<LI>as a result of changes in health care practices, new procedures for food production,
processing and packaging, environmental changes and reductions in public health and
disease prevention programmes, new and re-emerging infectious diseases have become
threats to the health of our populations;<P>

<LI>as a result of political, social and economic changes, especially in countries of central
and eastern Europe and the newly independent states, immunization and
communicable disease control programmes have been jeopardized;<P>
</uL>
<LI>	Recognizing that attainment of HFA target 5 will depend on the political will of countries
and on investment of adequate human and financial resources;

<LI>	Recognizing also that continued efforts are required to strengthen disease surveillance
and outbreak control, reinforce training and supervision, ensure the quality of vaccine
production, management and administration and pursue research and development;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>REAFFIRMS the regional goals of eliminating neonatal tetanus by the year 1995 and
diphtheria and poliomyelitis by the year 2000 and that the goals of the Expanded Programme on
Immunization remain a regional priority and represent a milestone towards achieving HFA by
the year 2000;<P>

<LI>EXPRESSES its concern at the feasibility of attaining the regional HFA target for
elimination of other diseases through immunization (such as hepatitis B and <I>haemophilus
influenzae B</I>);<P>

<LI>CONSIDERS it necessary, based on programme evaluation, to modify the operational
objectives of the regional immunization programme;<P>

<LI>APPRECIATES the support from intergovernmental, governmental and
nongovernmental organizations that are working together towards achieving a Region free from
vaccine-preventable diseases;<P>

<LI>URGES Member States to:<P>
<OL>
<LI>accelerate activities and commit all necessary resources in their countries to achieve the
targets set for childhood immunization;

<LI>support the realization of plans of action in countries for the control of diphtheria and
eradication of poliomyelitis and immunization plans in affected countries;

<LI>use World Health Day 1995 as an occasion for action at country level towards ending
the transmission of wild poliovirus within the European Region;

<LI>improve the quality of the laboratory support and epidemiological surveillance needed
for communicable disease control programmes, giving special attention to emerging and
re-emerging infectious diseases;

<LI>keep the Regional Office informed on a regular basis of the incidence and prevalence of
communicable diseases in their territory;
</OL>
<p>

<LI>CALLS ON organizations of the United Nations system, other intergovernmental
agencies and governmental and nongovernmental organizations to support primary immunization
of all children below two years of age in efforts for diphtheria control and poliomyelitis
eradication in the Region;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to implement the actions necessary to meet targets set for the eradication of
poliomyelitis and the control of diphtheria and other vaccine-preventable diseases;

<LI>to continue to mobilize donors and obtain their commitment to support immunization
and communicable disease control programmes, especially in newly independent
states;

<LI>to further strengthen the capacity of the Regional Office to undertake an integrated
programme in immunization and communicable disease surveillance, prevention and
control, with attention to emerging infectious diseases including hepatitis B;

<LI>to assist Member States in planning and implementing programmes for immunization
and surveillance as well as laboratory support for the control of communicable
diseases;

<LI>taking into account the current tragic tuberculosis situation in the newly independent
states, to pay particular attention to this problem by creating an expanded programme on
prevention and control of tuberculosis in the central Asian republics and other newly
independent states;

<LI>to keep the Regional Committee informed of progress made towards achieving regional
HFA target 5 on reducing communicable diseases.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R8</H2><P>
<H2>Joint and cosponsered United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Taking into account World Health Assembly resolution WHA46.37 calling for a study on
a joint and cosponsored United Nations programme on HIV/AIDS to provide for global
coordination of policies, approaches and funding, and recalling Executive Board resolution
EB93.R5 recommending the development and eventual establishment of a joint and cosponsored
United Nations programme on HIV/AIDS, to be administered by WHO, in accordance with the
consensus option and the ECOSOC resolution on the establishment of a cosponsored programme
(E/1994/L.18/Rev.1);<P>

<LI>	Noting that certain essential structures proposed for the joint programme, e.g. WHO
country representatives, are established only in one country of the Region, and that this could
jeopardize the expected input of WHO to the programme at country level in all other Member
States;<P>

<LI>	Believing therefore that in the European Region special mechanisms must be developed
to provide WHO support otherwise given by WHO country representatives;<P>


<LI>   Noting that the Regional Office for Europe has provided effective assistance to AIDS
programmes in Member States of the Region both directly and through its intercountry
programme;<P>

<LI>	Stressing the willingness of WHO to work for further improvements in coordination
among the various United Nations agencies involved in the joint programme;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Standing Committee in the spirit of strong support to the cosponsored
programme to closely monitor the process of establishing the joint programme, particularly in
respect of the tasks and responsibilities entrusted to the European Region within the new
programme especially with regard to CCEE/NIS;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director,<P>
<OL>
<LI>	to continue to consult with the Director-General and with the executive management
of the joint programme and the cosponsoring agencies active in the field of AIDS
prevention in the European Region on a differentiated operational structure for the
programme which takes into account the special characteristics of the European
Region;

<LI>	to offer the services of the Regional Office to the new programme to the greatest
extent possible in developing the most effective means of implementing the programme in
the European Region, including a coordinating mechanism that will assure collaboration
with the European Community Programme "Europe against AIDS" and the Council of
Europe;

<LI>	to intensify the existing collaboration at country level in the Region between
WHO/EURO, UNDP, World Bank, UNICEF, UNFPA and UNESCO;

<LI>	to study the modalities of ensuring full integration at country level of the support and
assistance provided by different cosponsors of the joint programme in the European
Region;

<LI>	to report to the Regional Committee at its next session in September 1995 on measures
taken to implement this resolution.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R9</H2><P>
<H2>Proposed Programme Budget for 1996-1997
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having reviewed the proposed programme budget for the biennium 19961997
(document EUR/RC44/5) and the analysis of the comments made by Member States and by the
Standing Committee of the Regional Committee (document EUR/RC44/4);<P>

<LI>	Noting that, in the formulation of the programme budget proposals, due consideration has
been given to the guidance provided in the document on programme budget priorities (document
EUR/RC43/4), to the regional contribution to the Ninth General Programme of Work covering
the period 1996-2001 (document EUR/RC43/3), to the health policy for Europe, to the World
Health Assembly resolution on budgetary reform (WHA46.35), to the results of the 1994
monitoring of progress towards health for all, to the evaluation of the 1992-1993 programme and
the evaluation of the first three years of the EUROHEALTH programme, and to the evaluation of
the emergency relief and humanitarian assistance programme, as well as to political and
socioeconomic developments and trends in the European Region, including the increase in
migrants and refugees;<P>

<LI>	Aware of the dramatic increase in the membership of the Regional Organization and of
the fact that many countries face serious health problems;<P>

<LI>	Recalling resolutions EUR/RC42/R6 and EUR/RC43/R10, which drew the attention of
the Director-General and the Executive Board to the special needs of several countries of the
European Region;<P>

<LI>	Noting the comments and proposals made by the Standing Committee of the Regional
Committee on the regional planning and evaluation process;<P>

<LI>	Further taking note of the Director-General's proposed emphasis on four global priority
areas during 19961997 (document EB93.35): (1) human health in a changing environment; (2)
proper food and nutrition; (3) integrated disease control as part of overall health care and human
development; and (4) dissemination of information for advocacy and for educational, managerial
and scientific purposes;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>WELCOMES the new easy-to-read layout of the proposed<I> </I>programme budget
and REQUESTS the Regional Director to continue efforts to make further improvements,
including analysis of the possibility of further reducing the lead time between programme budget
planning, approval of the programme budget and implementation;<P>

<LI>ENDORSES the proposed programme budget for 1996-1997, which is to be financed
with regular funds (and funds from other sources, to the extent that the latter become
available);<P>

<LI>RECOMMENDS the inclusion of the European Region's proposed programme budget for
19961997 in the Director-General's proposed programme budget for the Organization for 1996
1997;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director, during preparation and implementation of the
regional programme, to take into account the views expressed by the Regional Committee, and in
particular:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to continue to give high priority to support for health for all in Member States and to
intensified support for countries in most need;

<LI>to continue efforts to strengthen collaboration and coordination and to explore and make
use of joint funding and action both with international organizations or agencies active
in the health field and with countries in order to increase synergy as well as to avoid
duplication of work;

<LI>to continue efforts to mobilize extrabudgetary resources;

<LI>to continue to ensure the transparent, efficient and economic use of all available
resources;<P>
</OL>
<LI>FURTHER REQUESTS the Regional Director:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to coordinate efforts with the European members of the Executive Board so as to secure
an equitable allocation of resources from the regular budget of the Organization to the
countries in greatest need in all regions;

<LI>to request the Director-General to ask the Executive Board to review and analyse the
methods of allocation and the actual distribution of resources from the regular budget
and to report on options and make recommendations to the World Health Assembly in
1995.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R10</H2><P>
<H2>Evaluation of the EUROHEALTH programme
</H2>
<UL>

<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having considered the document on evaluation of the EUROHEALTH programme
(document EUR/RC44/6), including the external evaluators' recommendations and the Regional
Director's comments thereon;<P>

<LI>	Recalling its earlier discussions and decisions on this subject (resolutions EUR/RC40/R7,
EUR/RC41/R2, EUR/RC42/R6 and EUR/RC43/R10), and the fact that the programme was first
adopted in 1991, in consequence of which there is now a significant body of experience available
to the Regional Organization concerning the needs of EUROHEALTH countries and the range of
possible strategies to meet them;<P>

<LI>	Deeply concerned at the rapid deterioration in the economic conditions and in the level of
health of the population in many EUROHEALTH countries and its impact on social stability, as
well as at the increasing cleavage between health levels in EUROHEALTH countries and the rest
of the Region revealed by the HFA monitoring process, and mindful that the greater part of the
excess in mortality and disability is preventable;<P>

<LI>	Mindful also of the continuing shortfall in financial resources for implementation of the
EUROHEALTH programme;<P>

<LI>	Welcoming the positive initiatives taken by some Member States to harmonize their
bilateral cooperation activities with the EUROHEALTH programme, and also the clarification of
the complementary roles of WHO headquarters and the Regional Office in support of
EUROHEALTH countries, whereby the Regional Office is entrusted with the coordination of
support, the execution of operations, and negotiations with other bodies for assistance to
countries;<P>

<LI>	Aware of the improving conditions for multi- and bilateral cooperation, of the
possibilities for focusing efforts on the EUROHEALTH objectives of country health
development, and of the need to maximize the impact of the totality of assistance to
EUROHEALTH countries and to rationalize further the contributions of different partners;<P>

<LI>	Conscious of the fact that there is a lack of awareness among populations in the Region, 
as well as among various sectors and agencies in the Region, of the major contribution to 
improvement of health made by the EUROHEALTH programme (a programme that accounts for 
nearly two thirds of the regular budget of the Regional Office);<P>

<LI>	Agreeing with the external evaluators' endorsement of the strategy adopted by the
Regional Office in the implementation of the EUROHEALTH programme;<P>

<LI>	Recognizing that the greatest achievement of the EUROHEALTH programme so far has
been the gradual change in attitude towards health development in countries;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Governments of Bulgaria, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia and Lithuania, the external
evaluators, the Regional Director and staff for their valuable contributions to the evaluation;<P>

<LI>APPRECIATES the effective response of the Regional Office to the request of the
Regional Committee to implement and give the highest priority to the EUROHEALTH
programme;<P>

<LI>DECIDES:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to reaffirm health for all as the basic principle guiding the EUROHEALTH
programme and consequently to implement its strategy with continuous adaptation of the
programme and supporting management arrangements to the evolving health and
socioeconomic situations in the countries concerned;

<LI>to concentrate efforts on halting the further decline in health status in
EUROHEALTH countries through actions related to the most vulnerable groups of the
population and to priority health problems where effective action is possible, large
numbers of people are affected, and there is expectation of high impact and significant
improvement in the quality of care or the quality of life, notably perinatal care and safe
motherhood, immunization, communicable diseases and safe water supply, mental health,
and the prevention of death and injury due to external causes; 

<LI>to support long-term development, both to overcome the urgent problems and to
ensure a continuing and sustained improvement in health status to a level comparable
with the rest of the Region;

<LI>to offer support to countries in defining and implementing programmes within the
EUROHEALTH framework that are of priority importance to their health development,
taking full note of the need to support and sustain staff in their efforts to care for the
population and to safeguard the motivation of all health workers;<P>
</OL>
<LI>APPEALS to all Member States involved with EUROHEALTH countries to increase
their political and financial support to the EUROHEALTH programme strategy and to facilitate
the transfer of information and knowledge to EUROHEALTH countries;<P>

<LI>URGES Member States to work with the Regional Organization to establish, in a spirit of
health for all and partnership and mutual trust, health development consortia of donor and
recipient countries which reflect donor interests and the needs of the countries, such consortia
being either of natural geopolitical areas or groupings of countries to focus on a common interest
and concern;<P>

<LI>URGES governments of EUROHEALTH countries, in discharging their responsibility
for the health of their population, to implement actions in priority areas (such as those identified
in operative subparagraph 3(b) above) which are specifically determined by them within the
framework of a national health for all policy and strategy, to be used as the basis for a continuing
dialogue with all donor interests, and where necessary to seek the support of the Regional
Organization in this endeavour;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee (SCRC) to continue its
consideration of the EUROHEALTH programme and to provide support and advice to the
Regional Director in the determination of needs and the process of policy adjustment and in
contacts with countries and other organizations, and to intensify rapprochement with other bodies
(among them particularly the European Union and the Council of Europe) where strong, well
functioning working relationships need to be sustained in a spirit of coordination, cooperation
and complementarity;<P>

<LI>FURTHER REQUESTS the Standing Committee to advise the Regional Director on the
development of proposals for ensuring efficient use of donors' resources and for establishing
mechanisms which bring the donors, the EUROHEALTH countries and the Regional
Organization into an effective trilateral cooperative relationship focusing both on good
coordination and management and on evaluation of the outcomes and impact of activities
supported by donors; <P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to continue to give consideration to the evaluators'
recommendations in the light of discussions within the Regional Committee and to take
appropriate action, including:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to ensure the widest possible dissemination and understanding of HFA policy and
the objectives and underlying situation of the EUROHEALTH programme, as well as of
its importance to countries' health development, among donor organizations and relevant
nongovernmental organizations and among political leaders and health workers in
EUROHEALTH countries, both through the work of the liaison offices and other means,
especially the bilateral negotiation of WHO's programme of cooperation with countries
(the biennial medium-term programme) which adapts the strategy of the EUROHEALTH
programme to the countries' specific needs;

<LI>to confer with the SCRC and prepare an updated EUROHEALTH programme,
with identified priorities to address the changing needs, which responds to the dynamics
of the present and expected future realities of the countries concerned, and to present the
proposed programme to the Regional Committee at its forty-fifth session;

<LI>to take such action as he sees fit, with the support and advice of the SCRC, to
respond effectively to problems requiring urgent attention before then;

<LI>to offer to establish liaison offices in all EUROHEALTH countries, and to
strengthen links with subregional geopolitical structures of importance to these
countries;

<LI>to prepare proposals for discussion with the SCRC, and subsequent presentation
to the Regional Committee, on feasible means of facilitating the free flow of knowledge
at an acceptable cost to medical schools, WHO collaborating centres and other
institutions related to the health field, including cooperation with other agencies,
nongovernmental organizations and professional associations which are able to assist in
this endeavour;

<LI>to reinforce EUROHEALTH's monitoring and evaluation information systems as
integral parts of the management of education, information, prevention and emergency
preparedness programmes, including a capability for matching needs with the capacities
and interests of potential external partners;

<LI>to create a permanent mechanism to support EUROHEALTH countries in
improving and managing their own integrated monitoring and evaluation information
systems, thus enabling them to assess progress in their health development and permitting
them both to respond to the information needs of different external partners and to refine
and amend the EUROHEALTH programme;

<LI>to strengthen the resources of the EUROHEALTH programme to permit it to
develop further, especially by continuing to mobilize all forms of external resources,
develop information systems and transfer knowledge, and to give support to national
donor coordination mechanisms and to such health development consortia as may be
established between countries and donor interests;

<LI> to facilitate meetings between the ministries of health of EUROHEALTH
countries and the governments of donor countries, including their national bilateral
development agencies, and to continue to contribute to UN-initiated country strategy
meetings with support countries;

<LI>to collaborate with other regional and global intergovernmental and
nongovernmental organizations and other agencies active in this field;
<LI>to continue to submit regular reports to the Regional Committee on the
implementation of the programme, progress achieved and other developments.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R11</H2><P>
<H2>Election of members of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having considered document EUR/RC44/10 giving details of the candidates proposed for
election to the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>APPOINTS the following persons as members of the SCRC for a three-year term of office
from September 1994 to September 1997 in addition to the Deputy Executive President who is
Chairperson of the Standing Committee and therefore a member <I>ex officio</I> from
September 1994 to September 1995:<P>
<P>
	Chairperson:	Niall Tierney, Ireland<P>
	Members:	
Eldrid Nordb, Norway<P>
		Helmut Voigtlnder, Germany<P>
		Mihail Nikolaevich Saveliev, Russian Federation<P>
</OL>
<HR>


<H3>Resolution EUR/RC44/R12</H3><P>
<H3>ELECTION OF MEMBERS OF THE <BR>
EUROPEAN ENVIRONMENT AND HEALTH COMMITTEE</H3><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Recognizing the extent of adverse effects on health within the European Region
associated with unsatisfactory environmental conditions;<P>

<LI>	Acknowledging the particular prevalence of such effects within countries in transition
and war-ravaged Member States;<P>

<LI>	Concerned at the deterioration of many urban areas within the European Region, where
unsatisfactory housing, pollution, squalid conditions and social deprivation endanger human
health and in some places threaten to undermine the cohesion of society;<P>

<LI>	Mindful that maintenance of and improvements to health and wellbeing require a
sustainable system of socioeconomic development;<P>

<LI>	Conscious of the fact that such a system requires integrated action by all sectors of
government and society;<P>

<LI>	Encouraged by the commitment made by health and environmental authorities at the
Second European Conference in Helsinki to the establishment of a European Environment and
Health Committee (EEHC) to be chaired by a person elected by and from the nominated
members of the Committee at its first session;<P>

<LI>	Having due regard for nominations for membership of this body proposed by the
Standing Committee of the Regional Committee;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>ENDORSES the establishment of EEHC;<P>

<LI>NOMINATES the following four countries of the WHO Regional Committee for Europe
to put forward names of members with appropriate qualifications, knowledge, skills and
experience to the European Environment and Health Committee for a period of two years:<P>
<ul>
<li>United Kingdom
<li>Netherlands
<li>Hungary
<li>Finland;
</ul>

<p>
<LI>URGES Member States:<P>
<OL>
<LI>to draw up and implement national action plans for environment and health in
accordance with the provisions of the Helsinki Declaration;

<LI>to collaborate in environment and health in all cases where issues have transfrontier
implications or where action would benefit from shared experience and resources;

<LI>to provide broad support throughout the Region to the European Centre for
Environment and Health, which has a key role to play in implementation of the Helsinki
Declaration and the Environmental Health Action Plan for Europe and in support of
individual Member States.<P>
</ol>
<LI>URGES the Regional Director:<P>

<OL>
<LI>to provide the secretariat of EEHC, in cooperation, if appropriate, with one or more of
the other organizations involved;
<LI>to report to the Regional Committee at its forty-fifth session on procedures for the
nomination of future members of EEHC and on action taken by the WHO Regional
Office for Europe, in close cooperation with other intergovernmental and
nongovernmental bodies, to implement the Declaration and accompanying Action
Plan.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R13</H2><P>
<H2>Health assistance to countries in response to emergencies and disasters
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Recalling resolution EUR/RC43/R9 confirming WHO's constitutional obligation to
furnish appropriate technical assistance and, in emergencies, necessary aid upon the request or
acceptance of governments;<P>

<LI>	Noting that the response of the WHO Regional Office for Europe to the emergency in the
former Yugoslavia has been consistent with the guiding principles concerning coordination of
humanitarian assistance within the United Nations system as laid down in General Assembly
Resolution 46/182;<P>

<LI>	Having considered the Regional Director's progress report contained in document
EUR/RC44/13, and noting with satisfaction the initiative by the Regional Director to undertake
both an internal management review as well as an external evaluation of the humanitarian
assistance programme to the former Yugoslavia;<P>

<LI>	Having been informed by the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee about its
review of the report of the external evaluation team (document EUR/RC43/SC(4)/7);<P>

<LI>	Noting with satisfaction that the above two initiatives have already stimulated changes in
administrative coordination, organization and staffing, and greater decentralization of
administrative functions from the Regional Office to the field;<P>

<LI>	Noting also with satisfaction the partnership developed with many Member States;<P>

<LI>	Noting further that the emergency relief operation in the former Yugoslavia is the most
ambitious and far-reaching of its kind undertaken so far, with significant implications for the
work of the Regional Office;<P>

<LI>	Concerned that conflicts similar to those which have broken out in the former Yugoslavia
could well occur also in other parts of the Region in the future; <P>

<LI>	Aware of the implications for the overall functioning of the Regional Office of
emergency operations involvement;<P>

<LI>	Ever conscious of the admirable way in which the team of the Regional Office in the area
of conflict is carrying out the humanitarian work despite difficult conditions and personal
risk;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his progress report and endorses the conclusions
contained therein;<P>

<LI>THANKS the external evaluation team for their thorough evaluation in such a short time
and under difficult conditions;<P>

<LI>THANKS all WHO staff members working on the humanitarian assistance programme to
the former Yugoslavia for their dedication and contribution under difficult circumstances;<P>

<LI>THANKS other UN Agencies, intergovernmental and nongovernmental organizations for
fruitful cooperation and support;<P>

<LI>CONGRATULATES the Regional Director on initiating an open and objective
evaluation process, thereby making WHO the first United Nations agency to have done so for its
activities in the former Yugoslavia;<P>

<LI>RECOMMENDS that the Regional Director brings to the attention of the Global Policy
Council the need for similar external evaluations to be undertaken by other regions and WHO
headquarters of other ongoing or future emergency relief programmes;<P>

<LI>ENDORSES the basic principles laid down by the Standing Committee of the Regional
Committee regarding the involvement of the Regional Office in future humanitarian action and
emergencies, as set out in document EUR/RC44/4 Add.1;<P>

<LI>RECOMMENDS that the Regional Director consider the proposals of the external
evaluators, and in consultation with the SCRC formulate guidelines and criteria for the nature of
future involvement of the Regional Office in emergency relief situations;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director with WHO Headquarters<P>
<OL>

<LI>to initiate a review of existing administrative and financial procedures governing
emergency relief operations in the Region, with a view to improving timeliness of
response, streamlining of procedures and increased flexibility and delegation of authority
to the field, as well as reflecting on authority matters around decisions to involve
WHO/EURO in emergency relief operations;

<LI>	to keep the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee informed on progress
in this regard;

<LI>	to bring to the attention of the Global Policy Council the need for similar
procedures to be adopted for emergency relief operations in other WHO Regions;<P>
</ol>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to convey to WHO staff working in the areas of
conflict the Regional Committee's continued appreciation and thanks for the humanitarian work
they are carrying out under difficult conditions and often at personal risk;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report to the Regional Committee at its forty-fifth
session on action taken to implement this resolution.<P>
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R14 </H2><P>
<H2>Report of the Standing Commottee of the Regional Committee
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,<P>

<LI>	Having considered the report of the Standing Committee of the Regional Committee
(documents EUR/RC44/4 and EUR/RC44/4 Add.1) and the proposals and recommendations
contained therein;<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Standing Committee for its thorough and excellent work and commends all
members on their high level of commitment on behalf of the Regional Committee;<P>

<LI>THANKS the Regional Director and the staff of the Regional Office for assisting the
Standing Committee;<P>

<LI>ENDORSES the conclusions and proposals of the Standing Committee, as discussed in
the Regional Committee;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Standing Committee, on behalf of Member States, to continue to
promote coordination among international organizations in Europe, in accordance with the
provision contained in article 50(<I>d</I>) of the WHO Constitution,a in order to maximize the
collective support provided by all international organizations operating in the health field in
Europe;<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to take action, as appropriate, on the conclusions and
proposals contained in the report of the Standing Committee.<P>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC44/R15</H2><P>
<H2>Subject of technical discussions at the forty-sixth session
</H2><P>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,<P>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CONFIRMS that the subject of the main technical discussions at its forty-sixth session
shall be "The health of migrants and refugees";<P>

<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to make the necessary arrangements.<P>
</OL>
