<H1 align=center>Resolutions 1991</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R1</H2>
<H2>Annual report of the Regional Director to the Regional Committee
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the report on the work of WHO in the European Region in 1990;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his report;
<LI>EXPRESSES its satisfaction with the work accomplished by the Regional Office in 1990;  and
<LI>ASKS the Regional Director to take into account the suggestions made during the discussion in the
future work of the Regional Office.
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R2</H2>
<H2>Cooperation with countries of central and eastern Europe - The EUROHEALTH programme
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having studied the reports on the EUROHEALTH programme submitted by the Regional Director
(EUR/RC41/2, /6 and /Inf.Doc./4);
<LI>	Noting with satisfaction the efforts made by the European Member States and the World Health
Organization and the collaboration with the European Community, the Council of Europe, other United
Nations agencies and bilateral assistance organizations, the World Bank and nongovernmental
organizations, and other partners, to support the countries of central and eastern Europe in their current
period of transition;
<LI>	Considering the recent dramatic events in Europe and their potential implications, including a
likely increase in the number of countries that will be eligible for support under the EUROHEALTH
programme;
<LI>	Fully aware that the present situation represents a turning point in Europe's history with great
impact on the political, social and economic development in the Region;
<LI>	Conscious that Europe-wide support to health development in the EUROHEALTH target
countries, based on the principles of health for all, can be a major factor not only in promoting health but
also in reducing social tension, and thus contribute to harmonious and peaceful developments in this part of
Europe;
<LI>	Noting the large discrepancy between the need for EUROHEALTH assistance and the current
level of financial resources at the disposal of the Regional Office, and recognizing the technical and
administrative readiness of the Office and its networks to respond effectively, should substantial resources
be made available;
<LI>	Acutely aware of the Regional Committee's role and the responsibility of the World Health
Organization in European health development;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his reports and the Regional Office for the work carried out;
<LI>	RECOMMENDS the establishment of a special account for EUROHEALTH within WHO's
Voluntary Fund for Health Promotion;
<LI>URGES all Member States, intergovernmental and nongovernmental organizations and others:
<OL>
<LI>	to contribute to the EUROHEALTH funds mentioned in operative paragraph 2;
<LI>		to use the EUROHEALTH programme as one of the main channels for international
assistance;
</OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>		to give priority, in the programme budget proposals for 1994-1995, to continued
implementation of the EUROHEALTH programme at a funding level of at least 2 million dollars;
<LI>		to intensify efforts to attract extrabudgetary resources for the EUROHEALTH
programme, to continue to encourage donors to make wide use of the programme and to discuss with the
European Community, especially in its capacity as focal point for the group of 24 donor countries (G24),
the possibilities for further cooperation in order to assist the countries concerned in the most efficient way;
<LI>		to assist individual EUROHEALTH target countries in adapting the programme to meet
their own specific needs and encourage the subregional collaboration of individual EUROHEALTH
countries by grouping programmes in defined geographical areas;
<LI>		to create a system for collecting information on current health programmes and priority
problems in EUROHEALTH countries and for disseminating that information to the international
community;
<LI>		to continue the collaboration with WHO headquarters so as to use the Organization's
technical and financial resources to the benefit of the countries of central and eastern Europe according to
the decisions by the World Health Assembly and the Regional Committee;
<LI>		to submit a report on implementation, monitoring and plans for evaluation of the
EUROHEALTH programme to the Regional Committee at its forty-second session and, in due time, a
report on the outcome of the programme.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>




<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R3</H2>
<H2>Prevention and control of diabetes mellitus
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	In pursuance of regional HFA target 4 and of resolution WHA42.36 on prevention and control of
diabetes mellitus, adopted by the Forty-second World Health Assembly on 19 May 1989;
<LI>	Recognizing that in Europe diabetes mellitus is a debilitating and costly disease, both to the patient
and to society;
<LI>	Having considered document EUR/RC41/10;
<LI>	Welcoming the agreement established between the International Diabetes Federation, European
Region and the World Health Organization, Regional Office for Europe in order to develop and promote
activities which will offer diabetic persons the opportunities of developing and using their health potential
to live socially and economically fulfilling lives;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>ENDORSES the principles underlying the St Vincent Declaration and the proposed action programme
as outlined in document EUR/RC41/10;
<LI>URGES Member States to review their current diabetes programmes, set country achievement targets
and strengthen any components of their programmes that may not yet be in line with the basic principles of
diabetes prevention and control outlined in document EUR/RC41/10;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to:
<OL>
<LI>	mobilize the technical and other resources of the Regional Office, the WHO collaborating centres
on diabetes and other institutions able to provide appropriate support for a European action programme of
management and research into the prevention and control of diabetes mellitus and its complications;
<LI>	provide technical support to Member States in the development of country programmes for the
prevention and control of diabetes mellitus and its complications;
<LI>	continue to collaborate closely with the International Diabetes Federation and further enhance
cooperation with the European Community and other relevant bodies, with a view to expanding the scope of
joint activities in the prevention and control of diabetes and its complications;
<LI>		seek extrabudgetary support for the programme.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R4</H2>
<H2>Date and place of regular sessions of the Regional Committee in 1992 and 1993
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the decision taken at its fortieth session and taking into account the
recommendation contained in resolution EUR/RC30/R7;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CONFIRMS that the forty-second session shall be held at the regional headquarters in Copenhagen
from 14 to 19 September 1992;
<LI>DECIDES that, by invitation of the Government of Greece, the forty-third session shall be held in
Greece in September 1993, for a period not exceeding five days.
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R5</H2>
<H2>Strategy for attaining health for all bythe year 2000: Updating of the regional health for all targets
</H2>
<UL>
<LI> 	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling resolutions WHA30.43, WHA34.36, WHA36.35, WHA37.17 and WHA39.7 concerning
the policy, the strategy, the plan of action, and the monitoring and evaluation of progress for attaining the
goal of health for all (HFA) by the year 2000;
<LI>	Bearing in mind resolutions EUR/RC30/R8 and EUR/RC34/R5 endorsing the regional HFA
strategy and targets;
<LI>	Recognizing the considerable impact that the European HFA policy and its targets have had in the
Region as a whole as well as in individual Member States since its endorsement in 1984;
<LI>	Further recalling resolution EUR/RC40/R5 on "Evaluation of the strategy for health for all in
1990-1991" and resolution EUR/RC40/R6 on a "European HFA information strategy";
<LI>	Aware of the need to update the regional HFA targets, especially those scheduled to be attained by
1990, in view of developments in Europe during the 1980s;
<LI>	Bearing in mind the discussions at the thirty-ninth and fortieth sessions of the Regional Committee
on the need for an updated version of the regional HFA target book;a
<LI>	Having considered:
<OL>
<LI>	the updated regional HFA targets (document EUR/RC41/8);
<LI>		the report of the Consultative Group on Programme Development (document
EUR/RC41/6);
<LI>	the report on the second evaluation of the strategy for health for all by the year 2000
(EUR/RC41/7);
</OL>
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director, the advisory groups and the experts involved in the updating process
for their valuable contributions;
<LI>WELCOMES the update as an appropriate response to developments during the 1980s and as a further
incentive to continue the good work towards HFA; 	a <I>Targets for health for all</I>.  Copenhagen,
WHO Regional Office for Europe, 1985 (European Health for All Series, No. 1).
<LI>APPROVES for application as appropriate, having regard to the particular circumstances of individual
Member States:
<OL>
<LI>the updated regional HFA targets as expressed in document EUR/RC41/8 (including a new target on
health and ethics) and taking full account of the recommendations of the Regional Committee;
<LI>the revised plan of action and major milestones for implementation of the regional HFA strategy, to be
updated as necessary;
<LI>the list of indicators as amended by the Committee;
</OL>
<LI>URGES Member States:
<OL>
<LI>		to continue their efforts to establish (or amend) policies and set (or amend) their own
targets in line with the regional HFA policy and targets;
<LI>		to continue to give special emphasis to programmes in line with HFA policies and to
further develop structures and networking of partners required to support progress towards HFA;
<LI>		to strengthen monitoring of the European HFA implementation by using the regional HFA
indicators as integrated parts of their health surveillance systems;
<LI>		to seek cooperation with the Regional Office as and when required for these purposes;
</OL>
<LI>	REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to consult the Member States in writing on the full text of the updated European HFA targets
(EUR/RC41/Inf.Doc./1) in the appropriate working language;
<LI>	to convene a drafting group, chaired by one of the officers of the forty-first session of the Regional
Committee to analyse and incorporate the comments made into the full text of the updated European HFA
targets and to publish, distribute and promote the updated regional HFA target book as a European regional
contribution to attainment of the global target for health for all;
<LI>	to continue to network with partners (governments, nongovernmental organizations,
intergovernmental organizations, universities, etc.) to help promote wide acceptance of the HFA policy
throughout the Region;
<LI>	to continue research and development efforts towards better technical solutions and support for
HFA development in Europe;
<LI>	to use regional priorities for HFA development as a basis for Regional Office programme budget
and action strategies;
<LI>	to report to the Regional Committee on progress towards the attainment of health for all in
accordance with the HFA plan of action.
</OL></OL>

<HR>





<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R6</H2>
<H2>Ethics and health
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Noting that ethical issues are assuming increasing importance in scientific, health-related and
social work as well as in daily life;
<LI>	Emphasizing that any policy or activity related to research and health must be carried out in
accordance with principles of ethics and human rights;
<LI>	Recalling the work done in the field of health-related ethics by the Council for International
Organizations of Medical Sciences (CIOMS) and the Council of Europe;
<LI>	Recognizing the efforts WHO is making to promote respect for health-related ethical rules;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>EMPHASIZES the need for Member States to take account of health-related ethical imperatives in
implementing measures designed to attain the 38 targets for health for all;
<LI>DRAWS THE ATTENTION of the Member States in particular to the health-related ethical principles
contained in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the United Nations convention on human rights,
the working decisions of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights and the recommendations of the
Council of Europe;
<LI>WELCOMES the new European HFA target on health and ethics;
<LI>	REQUESTS the Regional Director to continue to strengthen the Regional Office's cooperation
with the Council of Europe in order to further the promotion of ethics in the area of health among Member
States;
<LI>	ASKS the Regional Director to report on implementation of this resolution in his next annual
report.
</OL>
<HR>




<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R7</H2>
<H2Ad hoc committee on the future orientations of the Regional organization in a changing Europe
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Considering the changing political, socioeconomic and health conditions, and health services in the
European Region, as well as the increasingly important role in health of all major intergovernmental and
regional integrational organizations in Europe;
<LI>	Stressing the key role of the Regional Committee and of the Regional Office in health leadership in
Europe;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>DECIDES to establish an ad hoc committee on the future orientations of the European regional
organization in a changing Europe, to prepare the foundations for a major discussion at the forty-second
session of the Regional Committee on:
<OL>
<LI>long-term strategic directions of the WHO European regional organization and its partnership within
the United Nations system and with other intergovernmental and integrational organizations;
<LI>possible implications thereof for:
<OL>
<LI>	the role and function of the Regional Committee;
<LI>	the organizational, managerial and advisory structures as well as the principles of funding of the
Regional Office;
<LI>	technical cooperation with Member States;
<LI>	the future priorities of the European regional programme;
</OL>
</OL>
<LI>DECIDES that the members of the ad hoc committee will be appointed by the officers of the forty-first
session of the Regional Committee in consultation with the Regional Director;
<LI>ENTRUSTS the ad hoc committee with determining its own method of work;
<LI>REQUESTS the Chairperson of the ad hoc committee to inform the CGPD of their preliminary
observations, and in the light of the CGPD's comments, to submit its final report to the forty-second session
of the Regional Committee;
<LI>URGES Member States to make their views known to the ad hoc committee before 1 March 1992;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to:
<OL>
<LI>		provide the secretariat support, including interpretation and translation into the four
working languages and other services necessary to facilitate the work of the ad hoc committee;
<LI>	set aside adequate time for broad consultation with Member States and for full consideration of the
report at the forty-second session of the Regional Committee.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>




<H2>Resolution EUR/RC41/R8</H2>
<H2>Managing the change to a smoke-free Europe
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling its adoption at its thirty-fourth session of the regional targets for achieving health for all
by the year 2000, and particularly target 16 relating to the promotion of nonsmoking, as well as resolution
EUR/RC37/R9 and World Health Assembly resolutions WHA39.14 and WHA40.38 on enhanced action on
tobacco;
<LI>	Taking note of the third progress report on the Action Plan on Tobacco (document
EUR/RC41/11);
<LI>	Welcoming the progress made by countries in implementing campaigns on tobacco or health, but
noting in particular the delays encountered in attaining the objectives set out in regional
<LI>target 17 for the reduction of smoking and the promotion of nonsmoking;
<LI>	Recalling the importance attached in resolution EUR/RC37/R9 to the exemplary role of health
authorities, personnel and institutions and having in mind the Director-General's call for tobacco-free health
services by World No-Tobacco Day in 1993;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CALLS on Member States to launch or enhance and evaluate the implementation of comprehensive
and effectively funded and managed campaigns to increase the number of nonsmokers particularly among
women and adolescents to at least 80% of the total population by the year 2000;
<LI>INVITES Member States to promote the principle that all health and educational premises are free
from tobacco smoke - with the exception of strictly limited designated smoking areas in hospitals - and
tobacco sales, to introduce programmes that foster the exemplary role of health professionals and teachers
as nonsmokers and to ensure the availability of support for smokers who wish to stop smoking;
<LI>INVITES Member States to join in celebrating World No-Tobacco Day on 31 May each year and to
focus on the themes approved by the Director-General;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to call for
<OL>
<LI>		an international convention banning smoking on international flights;
<LI>		the removal of duty exemptions on tobacco products on international flights and in duty
free shops;
</OL>
<LI>	FURTHER REQUESTS the Regional Director to develop, with Member States and in cooperation
with other intergovernmental and regional integrational organizations within the Region, a second action
plan to continue the campaign for a tobacco-free Europe for a further five-year period from 1992 to 1996
and to submit that plan to the Committee at its forty-second session.
</OL>
<hr>
