<H1 align=center>Resolutions 1989</H1>
<hr>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R1</H2>
<H2>Nomination of the Regional Director
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Considering Article 52 of the Constitution;  and
<LI>	In accordance with Rule 47 of its Rules of Procedure;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>NOMINATES Dr J.E. Asvall as Regional Director for Europe;
<LI>REQUESTS the Director-General to propose to the Executive Board the appointment of Dr J.E.
Asvall for a further period of five years from 1 February 1990.
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R2</H2>
<H2>The challenge of a smoke-free Europe
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling resolutions EUR/RC35/R7, EUR/RC36/R3, EUR/RC37/R9, EUR/RC38/R5, WHA31.56
and WHA33.35, relative to the campaign for health for all, the Action Plan on Tobacco and the protection
of nonsmokers;
<LI>	Recalling also the full international support given by the World Health Assembly to resolutions
WHA39.14 and WHA40.38 and the adoption, at the European level, of the regional targets for health for all
by the year 2000, particularly target 16;
<LI>	Taking note of document EUR/RC39/11 (ICP/GPD 110(13)/13) concerning the Action Plan on
Tobacco, second progress report:  the challenge of a smoke-free Europe, and in particular of the outcome
from the first European Conference on Tobacco Policy (Madrid, 7-11 November 1988);
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CALLS on Member States to include in their national health development specific policies and
programmes for action on tobacco, which are in line with the approaches described in the Action Plan, and
give effect to resolution EUR/RC37/R9 adopted by the Regional Committee at its thirty-seventh session in
1987;
<LI>INVITES Member States to consider taking measures as necessary in line with the conclusions of the
Madrid Conference;
<LI>URGES the Regional Director to:
<OL>
<LI>	actively support Member States in pursuing strategies aimed at implementing the Action Plan by
promoting the inclusion of tobacco control components in the Regional Office's collaborative programmes
with individual Member States;  and
<LI>	work to continuously improve the approaches and methods used in tobacco control by undertaking
studies, producing technical guidelines and providing information on innovative national experiences
regarding different aspects of tobacco control;
</OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to monitor and evaluate the Action Plan and report regularly to the
Regional Committee on the measures taken in the different areas of tobacco control and on the progress
made.
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R3</H2>
<H2>Annual report of the General Director
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the report on the work of WHO in the European Region in 1988 and the interim
report for the period January-June 1989;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his report;
<LI>EXPRESSES its satisfaction with the work accomplished by the Regional Office in 1988;
<LI>ASKS the Regional Director to take into account the suggestions made during the discussion in the
future work of the Regional Office.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R4</H2>
<H2>Development and management of health systems in Europe for health for all
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling resolution EUR/RC37/R7 on health personnel development in support of health for all,
and in particular operative subparagraph 1(b) which requested the Regional Director to consult with
Member States on the discussion paper analysing the recruitment, training and functions of personnel
responsible for the development and management of health systems in Europe;
<LI>	Having considered document EUR/RC39/10 on the development and management of health
systems in Europe for health for all;
<LI>	Recognizing that, in order to attain the targets for health for all at all levels of health systems, the
development and management of such systems call for a thorough knowledge of the factors underlying
health and illness, and considering that the personnel responsible for planning and management must be
given the opportunity of acquiring the desired knowledge or consolidating the knowledge they already have,
with a view to incorporating the new ideas and methods of the policy of health for all;
<LI>	Welcoming the initiative taken by the Association of Schools of Public Health in the European
Region (ASPHER) in establishing, with the Regional Office, a working group to promote the introduction
of the principles of health for all in the teaching dispensed by schools of public health;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>INVITES Member States that have not already done so:
<OL>
<LI>to analyse their situation in the light of the recommendations contained in document EUR/RC39/10;
<LI>on this basis to draw up, or where applicable to strengthen, the necessary policies and programmes for
the planning, management and evaluation of health systems, taking into account their repercussions on the
training of personnel involved in those policies and programmes;
</OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to:
<OL>
<LI>encourage acceptance, at international level, of the new approach to the prevention, diagnosis and
treatment of illness and promotion of health generated by the policy of health for all;
<LI>continue to cooperate with ASPHER, other institutions and the competent authorities in the Member
States, in proposing training objectives at different levels and in different disciplines and on helping to
promote research on health systems development and management.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R5</H2>
<H2>Eradication of poliomyelitis
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Considering resolution WHA41.28 pledging the global eradication of poliomyelitis by the year
2000;
<LI>	Aware of the fact that the efforts to eradicate poliomyelitis will strengthen the immunization
programmes of Member States delivered through existing primary health care services;
<LI>	Recalling regional HFA target 5, adopted by the Regional Committee at its thirty-fourth session in
1984 (resolution EUR/RC34/R5), whereby there should be no indigenous measles, poliomyelitis, neonatal
tetanus, congenital rubella, diphtheria, congenital syphilis or indigenous malaria in the Region by the year
2000;
<LI>	Referring to resolution EUR/RC35/R5 adopted by the Regional Committee in 1985, which urged
Member States to accelerate the implementation of existing immunization programmes and to make every
effort to increase vaccination coverage to meet regional HFA target 5;
<LI>	Noting the lack of progress in reducing the number of indigenous paralytic poliomyelitis cases
throughout the European Region since 1984;
<LI>	Recognizing the efforts made by the 26 Member States that have already protected their
populations from poliomyelitis caused by the wild polioviruses;
<LI>	Noting the necessity of the validation of simple rapid tests to confirm the presence of polio virus in
samples from individuals and from the environment;
<LI>	Having studied the report by the Regional Director on this subject;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>ENDORSES the plan of action for the eradication of poliomyelitis from the European Region,
contained in document EUR/RC39/9;
<LI>URGES the few Member States that still have cases of wild indigenous poliovirus poliomyelitis to do
everything necessary in order to strengthen the development of the programme within the framework of
their expanded immunization programmes;
<LI>FURTHER URGES all Member States to ensure that they have effective countrywide poliomyelitis
surveillance programmes and to report each confirmed case of poliomyelitis to the WHO Regional Office
for Europe within one week, specifying its type in accordance with the WHO classification to enable an
accurate assessment to be made of the progress of the programme;
<LI>INVITES Member States to make concurrent efforts to strengthen their immunization programmes
with a view to eliminating the other diseases preventable through immunization and already covered by
regional HFA target 5 (diphtheria, neonatal tetanus, measles and congenital rubella);
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to implement the regional plan of action for the eradication of poliomyelitis and to increase the
allocation of regular budget funds for this purpose by drawing on the Regional Director's Development
Programme in 1990-1991;
<LI>to supplement the funds available to the Regional Office by actively seeking extrabudgetary resources;
<LI>to report on progress to the Regional Committee every second year, until such time as the eradication
of poliomyelitis has been achieved in the Region.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R6</H2>
<H2>International decade for natural disaster reduction
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Noting resolution A/42/169 of the United Nations General Assembly, which designates the 1990s
as the International Decade for Natural Disaster Reduction, and World Health Assembly resolution
WHA42.16;
<LI>	Recalling resolution EUR/RC33/R5, which mandated the Regional Office to develop expertise in
disaster preparedness so that it could assist Member States on request;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>ENDORSES the proposals contained in document EUR/RC39/16;
<LI>CONCURS with the proposal to extend the scope of the Regional Office's mandate to include man-
made disasters;
<LI>URGES Member States to:
<OL>
<LI>	support and participate in the International Decade, but expand its scope to include man-made
disasters;
<LI>ensure the participation of the health sector in national committees established during the Decade;
<LI>develop disaster preparedness plans and guidelines as required, taking into account those proposed by
WHO;
<LI>develop clear and effective coordination mechanisms with nongovernmental organizations in order to
ensure a broad and rapid aid response to assessed needs during disasters;
<LI>develop rapid and open communication with the public, providing a realistic assessment of danger and
stating the measures that will be undertaken;
</OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to:
<OL>
<LI>further develop the Regional Office's response capability, the technical guidelines and the assessment
tools needed for the prevention and containment of such disasters;
<LI>	consult the individual Member States of the Region on whether they would wish the Regional
Office, in the event of a disaster within their borders, to:
<OL>
<LI>	send a WHO team of experts immediately, as part of the UNDRO team, to stricken areas to assist
in assessment of the health needs of the population;
<LI>	in cooperation with the government of the stricken country, inform the national health
administrations in other Member States of the health effects of the disaster and of the assistance required, to
ensure that the assistance provided meets the assessed needs;
<LI>		extend the Regional Office's assistance to include not only emergency aid in the event of
disaster but also the post-disaster rehabilitation phase.
</OL>
<LI>ensure, when a WHO team of experts is deployed, that measures are coordinated with other
international organizations, including the League of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R7</H2>
<H2>Consultation process, programme budget structure and programm evaluation reports
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the document on the consultation process, the programme budget structure and
programme evaluation reports (EUR/RC39/6);
<LI>	Recalling resolutions EUR/RC36/R2 relating to the presentation and structure of the programme
budget and EUR/RC38/R4 on management of WHO's resources - planning and evaluation of the Regional
Office's country and intercountry programmes;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>APPROVES, taking into account the comments made during the discussion, the proposed modification
of the consultation and programme budget documents, and the suggestion for a programme evaluation
report;
<LI>	REQUESTS the Regional Director in future to submit the consultation and programme budget
documents in the approved format, and to report on programme evaluation as suggested.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC39/R8</H2>
<H2>Date and place of regular sessions of the Regional Committee in 1990 and 1991
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the decision taken at its thirty-eighth session and taking into account the
recommendations contained in resolution EUR/RC30/R7;
<LI>	Taking into consideration the discussions on document EUR/RC39/3 - Matters arising out of
decisions of the World Health Assembly and of the Executive Board - especially regarding the decision by
the eighty-fourth session of the Executive Board to consult the Member States, through the Regional
Committees, on a possible change in the timing of meetings of WHO's governing bodies;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>DECIDES that
<OL>
<LI>should the timing of meetings of WHO's governing bodies remain unchanged, the fortieth session shall
be held at regional headquarters in Copenhagen from 10 to 15 September 1990;
<LI>should the timing of the Forty-fourth World Health Assembly be changed to October/November 1991
and that of the eighty-seventh session of the Executive Board to May 1991, the fortieth session of the
Regional Committee for Europe shall be held at regional headquarters in Copenhagen from 21 to 26
January 1991;
</OL>
<LI>FURTHER DECIDES that the forty-first session shall be held in Portugal in September/October 1991
(if (a) above applies) or in January/February 1992 (if (b) above applies), for a period not exceeding five
days.
</OL>
<hr>
