<H1 align=center>Resolutions 1988</H1>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R1</H2>
<H2>Annual report of the Regional Director
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the report on the work of WHO in the European Region in 1987;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for his report;
<LI>EXPRESSES its satisfaction with the work accomplished by the Regional Office in 1987;
<LI>ASKS the Regional Director to take into account the suggestions made during the discussion in the future work
of the Regional Office.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R2</H2>
<H2>Proposed Programme Budget for 1990-1991 and Preliminary Outputs for 1992-1995
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed in detail the proposed programme budget for the biennium 1990-1991 and noted the
modified presentation of the programme budget document (document EUR/RC38/7);
<LI>	Noting that, in the formulation of the proposals, due consideration has been given to the Organization's
Eighth General Programme of Work covering the period 1990-1995, to the regional programme budget policy
(document EUR/RC35/11), to the results of the evaluation of the 1984-85 programme and to the priorities given by
Member States in their replies to the written consultation;
<LI>	Having considered the comments made by the Consultative Group on Programme Development;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director, during implementation of the programme, to take into account the views
expressed by the Regional Committee, and in particular:
<OL>
<LI>to continue to give high priority to outputs in support of health for all;
<LI>to ensure the most efficient and economic use of all available resources;
</OL>
<LI>ENDORSES, on this basis, the proposed programme budget for 1990-1991, which is to be financed with
regular funds and funds from other sources, to the extent that the latter become available;
<LI>RECOMMENDS, on the same basis, its inclusion in the Director-General's proposed programme budget for the
Organization for 1990-1991.
</OL>
<HR>


<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R3</H2>
<H2>Strategy for attaining health for all by the year 2000: Regional monitoring, 1987-1988
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling resolutions WHA30.43, WHA34.36, WHA35.23, WHA36.35, WHA37.17 and WHA39.7
concerning the policy, the strategy, the plan of action, and the monitoring and evaluation of progress for attaining the
goal of health for all (HFA) by the year 2000;
<LI>	Reaffirming resolution EUR/RC33/R3 on the monitoring of progress in implementing the regional strategy
for attaining HFA by the year 2000, and resolution EUR/RC33/R4 on regional HFA targets;
<LI>	Having considered the report on monitoring of the regional strategy for HFA, 1987-1988 (EUR/RC38/11);
<LI>	Recognizing the need to make the regional strategy and its implementation better known to all those who
play a role in the field of health;
<LI>	Aware of the need to increase efforts to accelerate progress;
<LI>	Also aware that a number of regional HFA targets that are to be attained by 1990 will remain relevant after
that date, while others will have been largely reached by 1990, as shown in the monitoring report;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>EXPRESSES ITS APPRECIATION of the efforts made by Member States and WHO to promote progress in
implementing HFA at country and European levels, and to assess this progress;
<LI>THANKS the Regional Director for the monitoring report;
<LI>ENDORSES the monitoring report as the European contribution to the global report on monitoring of
strategies, updated to include all replies to be received from countries as well as the views expressed by the Regional
Committee;
<LI>URGES Member States:
<OL>
<LI>	if they have not yet forwarded their contributions to the monitoring report, to let WHO have the required
information as soon as possible;
<LI>	to continue to promote the collection and analysis of relevant data on regional and national HFA indicators
and, if necessary, to set up appropriate structures and/or mechanisms needed for carrying out these tasks;
</OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director:
<OL>
<LI>to forward the monitoring report, updated in line with operative paragraph 3, to the Director-General;
<LI>in collaboration with individual Member States, to prepare country reviews to be attached to the monitoring
report;
<LI>	in collaboration with the ministries of health of the Member States, to ensure wide dissemination of the
monitoring report within the Region in order to improve knowledge of HFA and stimulate progress towards its
achievement at European, country and local levels;
<LI>	to support, in close coordination with WHO headquarters, the development of information collection
systems that can assist countries to improve the assessment of progress towards HFA, and to facilitate data collection
in this respect;
<LI>	to prepare for the Consultative Group on Programme Development in April 1989, and subsequently for the
thirty-ninth session of the Regional Committee, a position paper indicating whether an updated version of the
regional HFA target book a) should be produced and submitted for approval to the forty-first session of the Regional
Committee in 1991 and, if so, in what form and by which process;


a <I>Targets for health for all</I>. Copenhagen, WHO Regional Office for Europe, 1985.<P>


<LI>	to prepare for the CGPD, and subsequently for the thirty-ninth session of the Regional Committee for
Europe, a position paper setting out options for simplifying future monitoring processes and for reviewing the
indicators.

</OL>
</OL>
<HR>



<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R5</H2>
<H2>Management of WHO's reousrces 
</H2>
<H2>Planning and evaluation of the Regional Office's Country and Intercountry Programmes
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling resolution EUR/RC37/R6 on the frequency and methodology of audits on medium-term
programmes of cooperation between WHO and individual Member States and the possible roles of the European
Advisory Committee on Health Research (EACHR), the Consultative Group on Programme Development (CGPD)
and the Regional Committee in this process;
<LI>	Having reviewed in detail the proposal contained in document EUR/RC38/4;
<LI>	Having considered the comments on this issue made by the CGPD and by its subgroup (documents
EUR/RC38/6 and /6 Add.1)
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>WELCOMES the proposal to reduce the lead-time between planning and implementation of the intercountry
programme;
<LI>AGREES to the proposed modification of the existing consultation process, thereby reducing workload and
cost, both to Member States and to the Regional Office;
<LI>SUPPORTS the new role outlined for the Regional Committee in programme policy formulation and in
evaluation;
<LI>	NOTES the two alternatives proposed for involving the EACHR and the CGPD in the evaluation of
intercountry programmes;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to present to the next session of the Regional Committee, after consultation
with the CGPD, suggested new formats for the consultation document, the programme budget document, and the
suggested programme evaluation report.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R6</H2>
<H2>Protection of nonsmokers in public places and workplaces
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recognizing and concerned by the clear scientific evidence of the damage caused by tobacco smoke to the
health of nonsmokers;
<LI>	Convinced of the need for action to protect nonsmokers in public places and in places of work;
<LI>	Recalling resolutions EUR/RC35/R7, EUR/RC36/R3, EUR/RC37/R9, WHA31.56 and WHA33.35, relating
to the campaign for health for all, to smoking and to the protection of nonsmokers in health premises;
<LI>	Recalling also the full international support given by the World Health Assembly to resolutions WHA39.14
and WHA40.38 and the adoption, at the European level, of the regional targets for health for all by the year 2000,
particularly target16;
<LI>	Taking note of document EUR/RC38/15 (ICP/GPD 110(12)/8) concerning the Action Plan on Tobacco:
progress report;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>URGES Member States to take effective measures to protect nonsmokers from the damage to their health
caused by involuntary smoking in workplaces, teaching institutions, all forms of public transport and all premises
used by the public;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to support Member States in the implementation of these measures by
producing technical guidelines and promoting action at regional level in all relevant areas including air transport;
<LI>ENCOURAGES Member States to intensify the establishment of programmes of education and public
information on tobacco and health issues, including smoking cessation programmes, with active involvement of the
health and education professions and the media, in line with operative sub-paragraph4(6) of resolution WHA39.14,
and to introduce a common non-tobacco day every year;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report periodically to the Regional Committee on the progress made in
smoking control.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R7</H2>
<H2>Prevention of mental, psychosocial and Neurological disorders in the European Region
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Aware of the severity, magnitude and major public health importance of mental, psychosocial and
neurological disorders;
<LI>	Taking note of the Director-General's report on the prevention of mental, psychosocial and neurological
disorders (WHA39/1986/REC/1) and the resolution on this subject adopted by the Thirty-ninth World Health
Assembly in 1986 (WHA39.25);
<LI>	Convinced that the implementation of a systematic programme of both the promotion of mental health and
preventive action in the European Region could bring a substantial reduction in suffering and disability, the
impairment of human potential and the economic loss for which these disorders are responsible;
<LI>	Believing that such a systematic programme is entirely consistent with the principles and concepts of the
regional health for all campaign and could be successfully incorporated into the health for all targets;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>URGES Member States to include specific proposals for the promotion of mental health and for the prevention
of mental, psychosocial and neurological disorders in their health policy and medium-term programme planning, as
an integral part of the strategy for achieving the health for all targets, taking, in particular, into account the problems
of psychogeriatrics and respecting the principle of non-discrimination against persons affected by mental,
psychosocial and neurological disorders;
<LI>ENDORSES the report by the Regional Director as a suitable basis for the development by Member States of
proposals and strategies for the promotion of mental health and for preventive action in the mental health field;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to pursue actively the development and strengthening of collaboration
between the Regional Office and Member States in activities to promote mental health and to prevent these
disorders, including:
<OL>
<LI>	the development and standardization of appropriate indicators for monitoring progress in the
implementation of preventive programmes;
<LI>		the organization and coordination of training programmes to give personnel of the health and
social services an adequate knowledge and understanding of mental, psychosocial and neurological disorders and of
the promotion of mental health and preventive measures;
<LI>		the promotion of epidemiological, evaluative, psychosocial and biological research into the
prevention of the disorders, with special emphasis on international collaborative projects.
</OL>
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R8</H2>
<H2>Women, health and development
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Recalling the Director-General's report <U>Women, health and development</U> of 1985, resolutions
WHA38.12, WHA38.27 and WHA39.18, and the Director-General's progress report of 1987 reaffirming WHO's
commitment to women, health and development;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to implement the measures suggested in document ICP/GPD 110(12)/7
Rev.1, as amended by the Consultative Group on Programme Development and in the light of the discussions at the
thirty-eighth session;
<LI>RECOMMENDS that Member States actively seek, with the support of professional women's organizations,
ways of achieving the goal of equity in the proportion of posts occupied by women at higher levels of national or
federal health administrations, with a view to strengthening national efforts aimed at (a) promoting women's health in
terms of quality of life rather than merely life expectancy, (b) enhancing the role of women in all sectors of public
health, including in family health and its promotion as well as in health programmes relating to maternal and child
health and primary health care, (c) increasing their participation in advisory bodies and expert committees dealing
with health, and (d) reducing their inequality in health and safeguarding their rights in national legislation;
<LI>FURTHER RECOMMENDS that the Executive Board take this matter up at global level;
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to report regularly to the Regional Committee on progress in this field in the
Region.
</OL>
<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R9</H2>
<H2>Date and place of regular sessions of the Regional Committee in 1989 and 1990
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
<LI>	Having reviewed the decision taken at its thirty-seventh session and taking into account the
recommendation contained in resolution EUR/RC30/R7;
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>	CONFIRMS that the thirty-ninth session shall be held in Paris, France, from 12 to 16 September 1989;
<LI>	DECIDES that the fortieth session shall be convened at the regional headquarters in Copenhagen in
September/October 1990 for a period not exceeding six days.
</OL>

<HR>

<H2>Resolution EUR/RC38/R10</H2>
<H2>Technical discussion at future sessions of the Regional Committee
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	The Regional Committee,
</UL>
<OL>
<LI>CONFIRMS that the subject of the main technical discussions at its fortieth session shall be "Healthy aging";
<LI>REQUESTS the Regional Director to make the necessary arrangements.
</OL>
